<FIRST>r a PM-APAppointment     07-06 0127</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Appointment,0130</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Correspondent Named for Knoxville</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Duncan Mansfield, a newsman in the Boston
bureau of The Associated Press, has been named correspondent in
charge of the AP's Knoxville bureau.
   Mansfield, 36, joined the AP in Columbia, S.C., in 1982, and
transferred to Detroit in 1984.
   After working for the Lansing (Mich.) State Journal for two
years, Mansfield rejoined the AP in Boston in 1987.
   He is a native of Aurora, Ill., and a graduate of the University
of South Carolina. He began his journalism career at The
Index-Journal in Greenwood, S.C., and also worked at The Greenville
(S.C.) News and The News and Courier in Charleston, S.C.
   In Knoxville he succeeds Kristi Umbreit, who recently was named
correspondent in Cleveland.
</TEXT>
