<FIRST>r a AM-KraftContest     07-06 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kraft Contest,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kraft Announces Number of Winners in Botched Contest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft is getting ready to roll out its
wallet now that it has tallied the number of customers who submitted
winning entries in its botched ``Ready to Roll'' promotion, a
spokeswoman said Wednesday.
   About 21,000 matched game-piece sets were received by Friday's
deadline, spokeswoman Kathy Knuth said, including about 10,000 for
what was to have been the contest's ``one and only'' grand prize _ a
$17,000 Dodge van.
   ``We had originally estimated this (alternate payout) plan would
cost $3 million to $4 million,'' she said. ``That is still
accurate.''
   A promotional insert in June 11 newspapers in the Chicago and
Houston metropolitan areas carried the right half of four game
pieces for ``Ready to Roll.''
   Specially marked packages of Kraft cheese contained a left half,
and under the original terms of the contest, matched pairs could be
redeemed for one of 8,000 packages of cheese; one of 500
skateboards; one of 100 bicycles; or at odds of 15-million-to-1, a
1990 Dodge Caravan LE.
   Kraft learned the contest was botched just hours after the Sunday
newspapers were on the streets, when several hundred customers
called to claim the van.
   Kraft, facing the likelihood of more ``Ready to Roll'' winners
than losers, immediately declared the contest null and void and
ordered the specially marked packages of cheese pulled from store
shelves.
   On June 15, the company, formally called Kraft General Foods
Group of Philip Morris, offered to quadruple the number of prizes
originally offered and add cash prizes and special drawings.
   The proposal came after the company entered into agreements of
``voluntary compliance'' with the attorneys general of Illinois and
Texas.
   Several angry players filed class-action lawsuits despite Kraft's
claims that it could not be held liable for the prizes. And several
of the winners said they would press on with the litigation despite
Kraft's offer to sweeten the pot.
   Under the new payout plan, players who matched game pieces for
the van and submitted them by Friday's deadline will receive $250
and be eligible for a July 14 drawing, in which four vans will be
awarded.
   Similarly, each player who matched game pieces for a bicycle will
receive $50, skateboard winners $25, and cheese winners $5. Those
players also will be eligible for prizes in the drawings.
   Ms. Knuth said Wednesday an exact breakdown was not yet
available, but that about 25 percent of the 21,000 winning entries
mailed to the company were for bicycles; 20 percent for skateboards;
and 10 percent for cheese.
</TEXT>
