<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     07-06 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers replacing Juneau's public pool have
confirmed what city officials feared: The lining of the 16-year-old
pool was full of holes.
   The pool was losing more than 10,000 gallons a day because of the
holes, formed in the aluminum lining by reaction to other metals in
the rock and fill surrounding the tank, city recreation director Jim
Dumont said Wednesday.
   ``It would be like turning your garden hose on at home and
letting it run for 24 hours,'' Dumont said.
   The extra water needed to keep the covered pool full cost the
city about $15 a day, plus the expense of additional chemicals and
heating.
   The new pool will cost about $1.29 million. Dumont said the
lining will be made of concrete.
   ``We're thinking of putting the aluminum samples in the display
case by the Assembly chambers so people can see how much damage was
done,'' Dumont said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIAN HARBOUR BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Here kitty, kitty,'' just
didn't do the job.
   Five boys who spent four days trying to free a kitten from a
drainage pipe finally found a means of rescue: tying pieces of fish
to a badminton net and lowering it into the pipe.
   Attracted by the fish, the kitten climbed onto the net and the
boys pulled her out. She was 12 feet down the pipe, said Sharon
Pittman, mother of four of the boys.
   The children dubbed the kitten Baby Jessica Too, in honor of
Jessica McClure, the Texas girl who was trapped in an abandoned well
for 2{ days in 1987.
   The rescue effort began Saturday after 5-year-old Cory Pittman
heard the kitten's cry. The kitten was pulled out Tuesday.
   Cory's 13-year-old brother, Tommy, said his family gave up a
holiday trip to help the kitten, but they didn't mind.
   ``We saved an animal's life. That's what counts,'' he said. ``We
wanted to save it and now we are going to nurse it back to health.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   T.R. Benker may not be the funniest comedian in
the world. But he has staked a claim as the most persistent.
   Benker capped a 72-hour joke-telling marathon Tuesday night back
where he began it three days earlier _ onstage at Bally's Catch a
Rising Star comedy club.
   In between, he told jokes on the radio, outside a casino and over
breakfast in coffee shops.
   The Guinness Book of World Records lists 50 hours as the longest
continuous joke-telling session.
   It was the Chicago comedian's sixth joke-telling marathon. And it
was most likely his last.
   ``Never, ever again,'' Benker said Wednesday. ``I can't even
remember my mom's name today.'' He didn't sleep the entire time and
had a five-minute break each hour.
   Audience reaction depended on the audience.
   ``I might tell a joke one hour and people would just kind of
stand there and do nothing,'' he said. ``An hour later I'd tell it
again and people would laugh their buns off.''
   Benker said he hoped his marathon did something to his career.
   ``This was the big one for someone to discover or manage me or
else to put me away,'' he said.
</TEXT>
