<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Angola-Peace Bjt   07-06 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola-Peace, Bjt,0859</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Slow To Develop in Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The beginning of the end to Angola's
14-year civil war looked promising.
   But less than two weeks after President Jose Eduardo Dos Santos
and UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi sealed a cease-fire with an historic
handshake at an African summit in neighboring Zaire, talks between
the government and rebels have collapsed.
   Now, peace seems further away than when the guns fell silent on
June 24.
   Herman Cohen, U.S. assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, is scheduled to arrive in Luanda on Friday to survey the
situation.
   He said Monday in South Africa that he expected a final
settlement in Angola before the end of the year. ``There have been
some tremendously important developments in Angola, and I believe
it's on the right track,'' he told a news conference.
   The United States, which has been providing UNITA with some $15
million a year in military aid since 1985, has never recognized
Angola since it gained independence from Portugal in November 1975.
   Although Cohen is not expected to announce the establishment of
formal diplomatic relations with Angola, diplomats in Luanda say a
low-level U.S. representation could soon be sent to the capital.
   Acknowledging political difficulties between the two countries,
Dos Santos has said he hoped for ``understanding and realism'' from
the United States:
   ``We hope that now another climate has been established in
southern Africa, we can draw the lines that will lead us to a
normalization with the United States.''
   An Angolan government delegation walked out of talks with UNITA,
short for the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola,
in Kinshasa, Zaire, on Friday. Angola accused the rebels of killing
more than a dozen people in attacks on civilian convoys and of
sabotaging Luanda's power supplies in violation of the cease-fire
signed in Gbadolite, Zaire.
   In a statement released in Lisbon, Portugal, UNITA said news of
the cease-fire is taking time to trickle down to their fighters
spread around this nation, which is twice the size of France.
   The rebels also insist their leader is not contemplating exile,
although Savimbi's reported acceptance of a ``temporary and
voluntary'' stay abroad, far from Angolan politics, was one
pre-condition for talks stated by the Angolan government.
   Dos Santos, following a meeting Monday with President Denis
Sassou-Nguesso of the Congo in the Congolese town of Pointe Noire,
told reporters that ``the cease-fire violations must stop ... so a
favorable environment is created for the re-integration of UNITA
members into Angolan society and institutions.''
   He ruled out any power-sharing agreement leading to a multiparty
system.
   Sources close to the government said the Gbadolite summit caught
government and rebels off guard and both sides are now unsure of
their next moves.
   Speaking on Angolan radio from Pointe Noire, Dos Santos described
the process that led to the Gbadolite summit of 20 African heads of
state as ``hurried'' and said it was originally scheduled for August.
   President Mobutu Sese Sekou of Zaire, a UNITA backer and
self-appointed moderator in the Angolan peace talks, is believed to
have pushed the summit forward so it would occur before his official
visit to Washington last week.
   ``Mobutu told the Angolan government Savimbi was ready to accept
their peace plan,'' a resident African diplomat said. ``But it looks
like a lot of things still have to be sorted out.''
   The diplomat dismissed as ``mere rumors'' published reports that
the Angolan government had offered UNITA three ministerial posts and
four provincial governerships.
   ``A first priority should be somehow getting their troops
separated and a monitoring, demilitarized zone set up,'' a Western
diplomat said. ``Then there's the problem of integrating the rebels
into the Angolan armed forces.'' Since January, 70 United Nations
monitors have been in Angola to oversee the phased withdrawal of
50,000 Cuban troops deployed in the country to help Angola fight the
guerrillas.
   According to the terms of a U.S.-brokered December 22 agreement
signed in New York by South Africa, Cuba and Angola, all the Cuban
troops are to have pulled back beyond the 13th parallel by August 1
and are to be out of the country by mid-1991.
   Cohen is slated to meet with Angolan, Cuban and South African
officials who form the commission monitoring progress of the
agreement.
   UNITA has been fighting the Cuban-and Soviet-aided Marxist
government since Angola's independence.
   Shortly before his inauguration in January, President Bush wrote
to Savimbi pledging continued military support, but Western
diplomats here say the tide could be turning.
   Diplomats say Dos Santos, a 47-year-old Soviet-trained petroleum
engineer, could face resistance to a settlement with UNITA from
within his own ruling party.
   Rumors of coup plots have buzzed around the capital since early
this year.
   But since he succeeded Agostinho Neto in 1979, Dos Santos has
surprised many observers by clamping down on party infighting and
has systematically concentrated more power in the presidency while
easing out Marxist hard-liners.
</TEXT>
