<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0728,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storm Dumps Heavy Rain on East Coast; Southwest Still Hot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 1, 4 and 6 with one graf each to CORRECT with revised
weather service figures for New Jersey.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain drenched the East Coast on Wednesday, causing
widespread flooding with eight inches of rain in New Jersey, and 10
inches in Maryland.
   The heat continued in the desert Southwest, where temperatures
near 110 degrees were recorded in parts of Arizona and California.
   Showers stretched along the Atlantic Coast from the Carolinas to
New York. Two people, including a 9-year-old boy, drowned and more
than 450 people were evacuated because of flooding in northern
Delaware.
   Salem County, N.J., was deluged with eight inches of rain and
southern Anne Arundel County, Md., had 10 inches. The National
Weather Service initially reported 20 inches fell in southeastern
Bucks County, Pa., and in the Philadelphia area, but revised that
report to 2.8 inches. It also revised lower an initial report of 13
inches of rain in Monroe, N.J.
   Heavy rain flooded tracks and disrupted Amtrak passenger service
along the railroad's busy northeast corridor. Busing and long delays
affected nearly 10,000 passengers, a spokesman said.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included 6.28 inches at Mt. Holly, N.J.; 5.7 inches at Wrightstown,
N.J.; 4.8 inches at downtown Philadelphia; 2.3 inches at Newark,
N.J.; 1.5 inches at Wilmington, Del.; and 1.2 inches at New York
City's Kennedy Airport.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57
degrees at Arcata Crescent City, Calif., to 112 degrees at Pierre,
S.D. Wednesday's low in the Lower 48 states was 26 degrees at
Truckee, Calif.
   Thursday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
middle and south Atlantic Coast states, the Ohio and Tennessee
valleys, the Gulf Coast states to southern and eastern Texas; and
widely scattered thunderstorms across northern Minnesota, northwest
Wisconsin and western upper Michigan.
   Highs were predicted in the 70s over western Washington and along
much of the Pacific Coast; 80s to lower 90s across most of the
nation; between 95 and 105 degrees from the central Plains to South
Dakota and southern Minnesota; 95 to 105 degrees over the Great
Basin and interior valleys of California, New Mexico and southwest
Texas; and between 105 to 120 degrees in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
