<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ForeignRepairs     07-06 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foreign Repairs,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Backs Rule Allowing U.S. Airliner Repairs Abroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is supporting a rule
allowing U.S. airlines to use foreign repair shops, but some members
of Congress are concerned safety might be compromised.
   Aircraft and parts manufacturers and some domestic carriers
support the foreign repair rule, which went into effect last
December. They say it promotes good trade relations, enhances safety
by making more repair facilities available, and, in the long run,
saves U.S. jobs.
   The rule allows U.S. airlines to fly any of their planes to any
country for repairs as long as the facility is certified by the
Federal Aviation Administration.
   Several foreign governments pushed for the rule change after the
FAA started to crack down on airlines that were violating a 1949 law
prohibiting foreign repair of airliners used in domestic service.
   Two bills in the House would rescind the new rule and reimpose
the former prohibitions, with some exceptions for foreign-made
planes and parts used by U.S. airlines. Maintenance bases set up by
U.S. airlines abroad also would not be affected since they are
regulated as domestic facilities.
   ``I believe that allowing maintenance of U.S. domestic aircraft
by foreign concerns raises both problems of accountability and
serious questions of FAA's ability to stay on top of a rapidly
changing industry,'' said Rep. Norman Mineta, D-Calif., sponsor of a
bill to rescind the rule.
   Mineta told a House Public Works and Transportation aviation
subcommittee hearing last week that the growth of foreign repair
stations will tax the FAA's limited number of inspectors abroad.
   Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., said the measure threatens the
livelihood of people who work in 4,000 domestic repair facilities.
   ``It's no secret that many U.S. airlines will jump at the chance
to lower their maintenance costs by taking advantage of low wages
abroad,'' said Synar.
   But the FAA said there is no evidence this is happening.
   ``There has been no signficant change in the way U.S. airlines
are having maintenance work performed by foreign repair stations
under the new rule,'' the agency said in a report to Congress.
   ``There is no fundamental difference between domestic and foreign
repair stations other than geography,'' FAA associate administrator
Anthony J. Broderick said in congressional testimony.
   Broderick said the global nature of the air transportation
industry prompted the more liberal rule. He said the FAA would take
``no shortcuts'' in certifying foreign repair facilities and would
not certify more than it can monitor with FAA inspectors.
   The agency watches over 200 certified repair facilities abroad.
The domestic and foreign facilities range from small companies doing
limited work on individual aircraft parts to large plants that do
complete overhauls of large passenger jets and engines.
   The Commerce Department also testified in support of the new
rule, saying the United States enjoys a large positive balance in
repair station work done for foreign airlines in the United States.
   ``In the view of our trading partners, the proposed legislation
is discriminatory and invites retaliatory action,'' warned Linda F.
Powers, deputy assistant Commerce secretary.
   Robert Peel of the Association of European Airlines said the
association's 21 airline members did $29 million worth of repair
work on U.S.-registered airliners last year but spent $84 million at
U.S. repair stations.
   At least two major airlines _ United and American _ have joined
their union workers in saying they would like to see restrictions on
foreign repairs.
   Among reasons given for opposing the new rule are that foreign
mechanics are not subject to drug testing, that personnel at the
facilities would not be certified by the FAA and that language
differences would hinder communications and safety.
   ``The lure of being able to perform routine maintenance and
repairs for any U.S. registered aircraft could lead to a
proliferation of newly (certified) foreign repair stations and an
expansion of many existing foreign facilities,'' said James M.
Guyette, United vice president for operations.
   The FAA says it has received 81 applications for foreign repair
station certification, 78 of them in Europe and three in the
Pacific. One Pacific application has been approved, and 12 European
and two other Pacific stations are being considered for
certification, the FAA said.
   It said planned increases in foreign-based inspection personnel
will allow full surveillance of the additional facilities if they
are certified.
   John J. Kerrigan of the Transport Workers Union called the rule
``the single most important threat to the future of aviation
maintenance in this country.''
   The union, which represents 18,000 mechanics, joined American
Airlines in opposing the 1988 rule change.
</TEXT>
