<FIRST>r i PM-Burma-Rice     07-06 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma-Rice,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burma's Soaring Rice Price Provokes Fears of Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of rice is rising beyond the
means of many in Burma and shortages could provoke renewed calls for
democratic reform in the country, diplomats say.
   The military government, however, has assured the people that
supplies of the staple are plentiful.
   Last year rising prices of food _ particularly rice _ helped draw
mass support in Burma for months of protests demanding an end to
more than a quarter century of one-party rule and authoritarian
repression.
   The government's inability to stem price increases this year
could once again stir open defiance of the government despite
September's bloody crackdown on pro-democracy protests in which
thousands died, diplomats say.
   More than 10,000 people attended a pro-democracy rally Wednesday
in the Burmese capital of Rangoon in defiance of martial law, which
prohibits gatherings of more than five people.
   It was the largest protest since last year's protests.
   ``It is a constant theme for the government now to talk about
lowering (rice) prices, but they continue to rise,'' a Western
diplomat said from Rangoon Wednesday, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   ``If people cannot afford the price of rice they are going to get
unhappy and start looking for someone to blame again.''
   The price of rice in Rangoon has doubled in the past year, the
diplomat said. A 110-pound bag that cost the equivalent of $44 a
year ago now fetches at least $88, he said. Prices are even higher
elsewhere in the country, he said.
   Despite huge raises for government employees, many people are
experiencing difficulty purchasing essentials such as rice.
   Buying rice is a constant theme of conversation in Burma, the
diplomat said.
   ``People used to greet each other by asking `what have you
eaten?', well now they say `what did you eat with?''' said one
Rangoon housewife. ``If you say you ate with your hands it means
that you had rice, if you say you used a spoon it means you had to
make do with rice soup.''
   And if wage increases have done little to alleviate the problems,
diplomats warn they may spur inflation.
   In a broadcast on state-run radio Sunday, the government blamed
the sudden rise in rice prices on hoarding of stocks by the wealthy
following reports of shortages. They also blamed the increases on
transportation difficulties during the monsoon season.
   ``No one is really sure how much rice there is in the country,
that is why people are hoarding _ they don't know if there is going
to be enough to get them through the monsoon season,'' one diplomat
said.
   With dissatisfaction growing, opposition groups are planning to
rally on anniversary dates of last year's bloody unrest, the
diplomats say.
   ``Right now the attitude is that if the government can't provide
rice, then it can't provide anything, so what good is it?'' one
said.``Rice is really the bottom line in Burma, its even more
important than press freedom or anything else like that.''
</TEXT>
