<FIRST>r w PM-ConsumerComplaints     07-06 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consumer Complaints,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fewer Complaints Filed Against Phone, Mail Businesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who shop by phone or mail order are
finding less to complain about, according to the Council of Better
Business Bureaus.
   Store shoppers, on the other hand, were a little less satisfied
in 1988 than they were the previous year, the council said in a
report Wednesday.
   According to a compilation of figures supplied by the nation's
180 Better Business Bureaus, ``ordered product sales'' prompted
58,200 complaints, compared to 68,500 in 1987, dropping from first
to third in the ranking of complaints against sellers.
   Ordered products consist of items, including subscriptions,
ordered by mail or telephone.
   ``I don't know of a specific action or a specific program, but
what I would suggest is there has been a renewed emphasis on
customer service,'' said Connie Heatley, a public relations
executive with the New York-based Direct Marketing Association in
New York.
   Retail stores prompted 65,900 complaints in 1988, moving to No.
1, compared with 65,200, or second place, the year before.
   Home furnishings accounted for the highest complaints, 12,500, in
the retail category.
   Service firms were the second-highest source of complaints, at
58,600, compared with 59,350 in 1987, when they ranked third. Auto
service firms are excluded from that category.
   Home improvement and remodeling companies ranked fourth,
receiving 46,000 complaints, compared with 45,750 the previous year.
Auto, truck and recreational vehicle dealers were at the bottom of
the list both years, with 31,000 complaints in 1988 and 26,750 in
1987.
   In a separate category, the council said customer requests for
assistance in resolving problems numbered 3.4 million, 50 percent
higher than in 1987.
</TEXT>
