<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     07-06 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>ANC To Open Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The African National Congress, an outlawed
South African anti-apartheid group, is planning to open an
information office here.
   The Pentagon has listed the ANC as a terrorist organization in
its ``Terrorist Group Profiles,'' although the State Department has
questioned that listing.
   ``We need to establish ourselves strongly in this city,'' Dumi
Matabani, a South African who has been representing the ANC from his
home here the past eight years, said Wednesday.
   Matabani said an office would be opened before the end of the
year, once funding and space for the facility have been organized.
Matabani is registered with the Justice Department as a foreign
agent representing the ANC for lobbying and information purposes.
   The ANC, founded 75 years ago, was outlawed by South Africa in
1960 and its leader, Nelson Mandela, was jailed. The group began a
sabotage campaign one year later, claiming it had no alternative
against the government.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>FCC Gives Waiver to Capital Cities@ABC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission has given
a permanent waiver to Capital Cities@ABC from rules that
could have required the firm to sell multimillion-dollar radio and
television stations in New York, Los Angeles, Chicago and San
Francisco.
   The commission granted Cap Cities@ABC's request that it be
allowed to own WABC-TV, WABC-AM and WPLJ-FM in New York City;
WLS-TV, WLS-AM and WYTZ-FM, Chicago; KABC-TV, KABC-AM and KLOS-FM,
Los Angeles; and KGO-TV and KGO-AM, San Francisco.
   Four months ago, the FCC loosened cross-ownership rules that
prohibited a company from owning both a radio station and a
television station in the same television market.
   The commission said it would look favorably upon waiver requests
involving radio and television station combinations in the largest
25 television markets in the country. In a 3-0 ruling made public
Wednesday, the FCC said Cap Cities@ABC had shown the stations were
located in four of the five largest markets in the country.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>State Department Concerned About SWAPO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials are worried about reports that
Namibia's guerrilla movement tortured prisoners, according to the
State Department.
   Some of the 150 people freed after years of imprisonment said
many others were tortured and beaten to death while held in
underground pits in neighboring Angola.
   They said they were among thousands of dissidents imprisoned by
the South-West Africa People's Organization (SWAPO) during its
guerrilla war for independence from South Africa.
   The State Department has been in the forefront of pushing for
independence for the territory. Elections are scheduled in November.
Several freed prisoners estimated SWAPO still holds more than 2,000
detainees.
   Guerrilla leaders say they held just 201 dissidents and have
released them all.
</TEXT>
