<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--SickTortoises     07-06 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Sick Tortoises,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Menace Threatens Desert Tortoises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOJAVE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mysterious respiratory illness threatens
to kill half the region's desert tortoises, the latest menace for an
animal already under attack by ravens and man's encroachment on the
desert.
   ``The poor things are under a lot of pressure from all
directions,'' said John Borneman, western regional representative
for the National Audubon Society.
   ``Off-road vehicles, habitat loss, dumping in the desert, the
ravens, and now this. At some point it's going to be more than they
can take.''
   Biologists theorize that the tortoises caught the illness from
others taken from the desert by visitors and kept as pets, only to
be returned to the 400-square-mile region with diseases caught while
domesticated.
   John Brode, a state Department of Fish and Game biologist in
Sacramento, said the illness could wipe out 10 percent to 50 percent
of the desert tortoise population.
   ``It's like a cold _ a runny nose,'' he said. ``All we know is
that it seems to be a viral infection and it's very serious. There's
very little chance of recovery. ... They could become extinct.''
</TEXT>
