<FIRST>r a PM-NotSoDucky     07-06 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Not So Ducky,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Things Aren't Just Ducky for Resident Mallards at Water Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some savvy ducks have found their version of
Florida's vacation paradise at a water amusement park, but the
management wants the little visitors to go back from whence they
waddled.
   ``They just hang out _ use the Lazy River ride, mooch food and
eye all the pretty women,'' said Richie Fontanez, a lifeguard at the
Wet 'n Wild theme park, where the resident mallard population has
reached more than 30.
   ``The big problem is what goes in a duck comes out a duck.''
   On Wednesday, the park started an eviction attempt. The plan was
to relocate them about 15 miles east, to the town of Bithlo.
   But that was easier said than done.
   For eight hours, the ducks waddled and fluttered just out of
range of a small arsenal of nets and baited wire traps set up by
Orange County Animal Control officers and environmentalists.
   But by the end of the day, only one had been nabbed _ by Cindy
Westra, co-founder of Back to Nature, a wildlife rehabilitation and
education center near Chuluota in neighboring Seminole County. She
lured it with bread crumbs and soft words.
   ``They're greedy little beggars. The park has now become a very
convenient meal ticket for them,'' said Carmen Shaw, the center's
other founder. She and Westra volunteered to help capture the
gentle, migratory birds.
   Nobody knows where they came from, but they've been living at the
park's lake about six years. There are about six times as many ducks
now as there were originally.
   Once the duck roundup is over, the birds will be taken by car to
a Bithlo ranch, where they will be introduced to more mundane
aquatic pleasures on a local lake.
   ``They'll be safer on the east side of Orange County,'' said
Shaw. ``That area of the county has less development and is less
polluted.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
