<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-North-Chronology     07-06 1147</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North-Chronology,1120</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-North-Analysis Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0439</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of key events in the
Oliver North Iran-Contra case, from his indictment to sentencing:
   1988=
   March 16 _ North, former Reagan National Security Adviser John M.
Poindexter, former Maj. Gen. Richard Secord and Iranian-American
arms dealer Albert Hakim are indicted on charges including
conspiracy to divert Iranian arms-sales profits to the Contras.
   March 18 _ North announces his retirement from the Marine Corps,
says he may subpoena ``the highest ranking officials in our
government.''
   June 6 _ U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell orders separate
trials for the four defendants; independent counsel Lawrence E.
Walsh, the next day, says North will go first.
   Nov. 7 _ One of 16 criminal counts against North, fabricating a
document, is dismissed.
   Nov. 21 _ Gesell says that if North stands trial, the court will
have little control over the testimony of witnesses ``acquainted
with high security matters.'' He appeals to President Reagan to
decide whether the government will allow the trial to take place.
   Nov. 29 _ Gesell refuses to dismiss two of the central charges
against North, conspiracy to defraud the government and theft of
government property. He dismisses one, wire fraud.
   Dec. 1 _ Reagan rules out a North pardon but says ``duty
requires'' his administration to block release of secret documents
North wants for his trial.
   Dec. 12 _ Gesell tells North he can't use 3,500 secret documents,
that he can use more than 300, roughly the same number planned to be
introduced by the prosecution. The decision removes a major obstacle
to the trial going forward.
   Dec. 30 _ North subpoenas Reagan and President-elect Bush as
defense witnesses. Gesell, after Bush is sworn as president the
following month, rules he won't be called. He postpones a decision
regarding Reagan.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1989</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 5 _ Prosecutors ask Gesell to dismiss conspiracy and theft
charges, citing North's ``insistence on introducing classified
information in his defense'' and the Reagan administration's refusal
to release material the judge ruled North would need. Gesell later
dismisses those counts.
   Twelve felony counts remain, including lying to Congress in 1985
and 1986 about his efforts on behalf of the Contras and lying to the
attorney general about the National Security Council's role in
diverting money from the Iran arms sales.
   North also is accused of illegally accepting a $13,800 security
system at his home from co-defendant Richard Secord, converting to
his own use at least $4,300 in traveler's checks from Contra leader
Adolfo Calero, and conspiring to defraud the government of tax
revenue by using a tax-exempt foundation to funnel money to the
Contras.
   Jan. 31 _ Jury selection begins.
   Feb. 8 _ The Justice Department interrupts North's trial, urging
new safeguards to prevent him from making surprise disclosures of
classified information. Gesell denies the request.
   Feb. 9 _ A jury of nine women and three men is selected.
   Feb. 10 _ The Justice Department seeks again to delay North's
trial. A federal appeals court panel denies the request.
   Feb. 12 _ Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist grants a delay until
the full Supreme Court can consider the Justice Department's
objections to the release of classified material by North's defense.
   Feb. 15 _ The Justice Department issues guidelines designed to
guard against disclosure of certain classified material by North.
   Feb. 16 _ The Supreme Court lifts its stay.
   Feb. 21 _ The trial opens with prosecutor John Keker portraying
North as a liar who ``places himself above the law'' and defense
lawyer Brendan Sullivan calling him a patriotic Marine who obeyed
the orders of his commander-in-chief.
   March 8 _ Fund-raiser Carl Channell testifies that North once
said of his work for the Contras: ``I don't care if I have to go to
jail for this; I don't care if I have to lie to Congress.''
   March 15 _ Former National Security Adviser Robert McFarlane
testifies that Reagan approved a secret arrangement under which
Honduras got military aid for supporting the Contras.
   March 21 _ Security consultant Glenn Robinette testifies that
North let Secord pay for a security fence at his home and then tried
to cover up the deal after he left the White House.
   March 23 _ Fawn Hall, North's secretary at the White House,
tearfully testifies that he was a tireless and selfless boss and
their shredding of Iran-Contra documents ``was no big deal.''
   March 28 _ Former Attorney General Edwin Meese III testifies
administration officials were worried about impeachment of Reagan
after they discovered the Iran-Contra link.
   March 31 _ Gesell rejects North's request that he order Reagan to
testify, saying there is no proof the former president authorized
North to commit crimes.
   April 6 _ The defense introduces an admission of facts, agreed to
by the government, stating that George Bush, as vice president, met
with Honduran President Suazo to tell him of expedited aid. The
document says the aid was in return for Honduras' help to the
Contras.
   North takes the stand, saying he was merely a Marine following
White House orders.
   April 7 _ North concedes he lied to the House Intelligence
Committee at an Aug. 6, 1986, meeting at the White House at which he
denied providing assistance to the Contras.
   April 12 _ North testifies he thought he was protecting Reagan
when he altered Iran-Contra memos before investigators from the
Justice Department could get a look at them.
   April 13 _ North leaves the stand; the defense rests.
   April 18 _ Prosecutor Keker, in a hard-hitting summation, says,
``North and McFarlane were following Adolf Hitler's old strategy,
which is the victor will never be asked if he told the truth.''
   April 19 _ In an emotional closing argument, Sullivan says North
became a ``sacrificial lamb'' in the Reagan White House and was
fired to spare the former president political harm.
   Bush tells reporters at the White House that ``my conscience is
clear'' about the Iran-Contra affair.
   April 21 _ The jury begins deliberations.
   May 4 _ North is convicted of falsifying and destroying
documents, accepting an illegal gratuity and aiding and abetting in
the obstruction of Congress. He was acquitted of five other counts
of lying to or obstructing Congress, of lying to Meese, of illegally
converting traveler's checks to his own use and of conspiring to
defraud the IRS.
   June 30 _ Gesell denies a mistrial motion filed by the defense on
grounds that juror Tara Leigh King had falsely denied in a
questionnaire that she or her relatives had ever been involved in a
court proceeding or criminal investigation.
   July 5 _ Gesell sentences North to a suspended prison term and a
$150,000 fine for his role in the Iran-Contra affair. North is
placed on two years' probation and ordered to perform 1,200 hours of
community service administering a new program to help inner-city
youth avoid involvement in drugs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
