<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-States     07-06 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-States,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fla. Governor Calls For Special Session on Abortion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Abortion-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bob Martinez said he wants a special session of the
Legislature to adopt new abortion restrictions, but Gov. Mario Cuomo
said he would defend New York's liberal abortion laws despite this
week's Supreme Court ruling.
   ``I don't believe we ought to wait until 1990 to deal with a
difficult subject,'' Martinez said Wednesday. ``It's not something
that's going to go away. It's something that must be dealt with.''
   In Baton Rouge, the Louisiana Legislature went into special
session Wednesday but Gov. Buddy Roemer said there wasn't enough
time to add abortion to the agenda.
   Louisiana already blocks the use of state money and facilities
for abortions, and lawmakers have passed a bill that would make
abortion a crime if the U.S. Supreme Court overrules Roe vs. Wade,
the 1973 case that legalized abortion.
   Martinez, a Republican and abortion opponent, endorsed the
Supreme Court ruling that upheld a Missouri law restricting
abortions and invited other states to follow suit. He also said he
was pleased with the ruling because it appeared to reinforce states'
rights.
   ``I think here in Florida we will try and develop a policy for
the state of Florida and not interpret what other states may do with
the ruling the U.S. Supreme Court issued,'' Martinez said. ``Clearly
I believe the unborn ought to have more rights than they have right
now.''
   Martinez said the special session would come no later than a
previously scheduled one in October that was called to consider
growth management and transportation.
   Currently, Florida allows abortions during the first six months
of pregnancy, and in the final three months only to protect the
mother's life. State Medicaid money will pay for abortions only when
the mother's life is threatened.
   The state's parental consent law, which is not enforced because
of a pending lawsuit, is one of the strictest in the country, said
Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla. It requires unmarried minors to receive the
permission of their parents, a guardian or a judge to have an
abortion.
   ``It also pleased me that we have a parental-consent law pending
before the Florida Supreme Court, and certainly the opinion of the
United States Supreme Court ... goes straight to the heart of the
parental-consent law requirements,'' said Martinez, who met with
pro-life activists Wednesday to discuss plans for a special session.
   New York also allows abortions during the first 24 weeks of
pregnancy and after that if a woman's life is in danger.
   Although Cuomo says he personally opposes abortion, he has
budgeted Medicaid funds for abortion each year. He said he would do
so again in next year's budget despite the ``inevitable attempt by
some legislators to deny fairness to poor people because the Supreme
Court follows a lower standard.''
   ``We think we have a better way and a fairer way,'' the
Democratic governor said. ``Yes, we have been different. I'm proud
of those differences. From a New Yorker's point of view, we do it
better.''
   Cuomo, a Roman Catholic, also said he would oppose any attempt to
forbid abortions from being performed in public hospitals. But he
would not say what he would do if presented with a bill requiring
minors to get parental consent for abortions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
