<HEAD>Drug Store Owner Sends 15,000 Cigarettes up in Flames</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pharmacist set fire to 15,000 cigarettes
and challenged others to kick the habit.
   ``Today ... we made a promise we would quit selling cigarettes,
and today has come,'' Kenneth Henderson said Wednesday.
   Bystanders cheered as the United Drug Center owner tossed a match
in a trash can that had a painted message challenging others to quit
smoking.
   Henderson had vowed to quit selling cigarettes on NonDependence
Day, a day set aside by the American Lung Association to encourage
smokers to quit.
   He estimated the cigarettes were worth $1,000.
   ``Lost revenue is not a consideration in my decision,'' Henderson
said. ``I don't think it will be something we can't live with.''
