<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     07-06 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Charges Government with Harassing Lawmaker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leading opposition party today
charged the government with political harassment after intelligence
agents and police tried to forcibly detain one of its lawmakers.
   The Agency for National Security Planning tried to detain Lee
Chul-yong of the opposition Party for Peace and Democracy for
questioning on grounds he had knowledge of a fellow lawmaker's trip
to North Korea.
   Under South Korean law, failure to report another's illegal visit
to the communist North is a crime. Lee said he knew nothing about
the trip by National Assemblyman Suh Kyung-won until he read about
it in newspapers.
   Three agents approached Lee when he arrived in Pusan, southeast
of Seoul, on business late Wednesday.
   News reports said the agents tried to apprehend Lee in the
airport VIP lounge, saying they had orders to ``courteously escort''
him back to Seoul.
   Lee refused and a scuffle occurred before Lee left hurriedly with
an aide, news reports said. The agents followed Lee into downtown
Pusan and tried unsuccessfully again to take him into custody, the
reports said.
   When Lee returned to Seoul, the agents were on the same plane and
additional agents and about 30 police were at the airport, news
reports said.
   Agents boarded the plane and requested Lee disembark, which he
again refused, the reports said.
   Opposition party members met Lee and whisked him from the airport
to the home of Kim Dae-jung, leader of the party.
   The party said members would not cooperate with questioning
without a court order. It charged the government with ``a
sophisticated political scheme to degrade'' its image.
   The intelligence agency is looking into the illegal trip to North
Korea by Peace and Democracy lawmaker Suh Kyung-won, who is in jail
charged with violating national security law.
   The party announced today it would protest what it called
``harassment and political suppression'' with Park Seh-jik, director
of the Agency for National Security Planning, accusing the
intelligence agency of exceeding its authority.
   Pang Chae-myung, a business partner of Suh, was arrested
Wednesday night for failing to report Suh's visit to authorities. He
was the ninth person to be charged in the case.
   The Seoul government maintains that contact with North Korea must
be made only through official channels and that the north remains
intent on spreading communism throughout the divided peninsula.
   The Korean peninsula was split into the communist north and the
capitalist South in 1945 at the end of World War II and the two
nations remain bitter enemies.
</TEXT>
