<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-06 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off Sharply Against Yen, Tokyo Stocks Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar ended sharply lower against the
Japanese yen today while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
rose moderately.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 113.77
points, or 0.34 percent, ending the day at 33,423.48.
   The dollar finished trading at 138.90 yen, down 1.30 yen from
Wednesday's close of 140.20 yen. It opened at 138.30 yen and inched
up while fluctuating between 137.85 yen and 139.10 yen.
   Traders said the dollar fell following its decline on overseas
markets overnight, mainly due to expectations that U.S. interest
rates would fall as a result of a slowdown in the U.S. economy.
   Market players were inclined to get rid of the dollar on
expectations of a further shift toward easy credit by the U.S.
Federal Reserve's policy-making committee, said a trader with the
Bank of Tokyo. The committee met Wednesday and will meet again today.
   Dollar-selling sped up following remarks of a high-ranking U.S.
Treasury Department official that the U.S. government was still
concerned about the dollar's high level against the yen, he said.
   On the stock exchange, the index's early rise following buying by
investment trust companies caused optimism in the market, said Kenji
Ishizuka, dealer with Daiwa Securities.
   ``The yen's strength against the dollar largely encouraged
investors' buying incentives,'' he said.
   ``In addition, a majority of market players are expecting the
United States will take action to ease its monetary policy,'' he
said. Expectations of lower interest rates are a stock buying
incentive.
   But many participants remained on the sidelines ahead of Friday's
release of the U.S. jobless rate for June, by which they believe the
U.S. monetary authority will determine its stand, Ishizuka said.
</TEXT>
