<FIRST>r a PM-CoalStrike     07-06 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Fines Union, but Doubts Effectiveness of Penalty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABINGDON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An exasperated judge fined the United Mine
Workers an additional $720,000 for using convoys to slow coal
shipments, but he doubted the penalties would work.
   ``It's all just sort of whistling Dixie,'' U.S. District Judge
Glen Williams said Wednesday. ``This order is being flouted,
flaunted, openly disobeyed.''
   Williams said he believes the UMW leadership is orchestrating the
tactic against Pittston Coal Group Inc.
   UMW District 28 President Jackie Stump called the fines
excessive. He also said it was difficult to stop people from joining
the convoys.
   ``A lot of them are saying, `We pay taxes on the roads. If we
want, we'll drive on them,''' he said.
   Scattered violence was reported Wednesday, which marked the start
of the fourth month of a strike against Pittston by 1,900 UMW miners
in Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky. Wildcat strikes also have
been reported in several states since June 12, when thousands of
union miners walked off the job in support of the striking Pittston
miners.
   In McClure, state police said a dynamite explosion damaged a
machinery warehouse owned by Pittston at the base of Hazel Mountain.
No injuries were reported in the blast, and authorities said it was
uncertain whether the explosion was strike related.
   Pittston President Michael Odom said that 20 feet from the
explosion site, company employees found 25 to 30 sticks of dynamite
tightly wrapped with tape. Odom said the wrapped dynamite failed to
detonate, but traffic had to be rerouted for hours while police
explosives experts removed the bundle.
   ``It makes me more firm in my resolution that I'm not going to
yield to terrorists,'' Odom said.
   Union officials could not be reached for comment in the district
office or in the hotel where they have been staying.
   A miner's windshield was smashed as he drove to work at a Peabody
Coal Co. mine near Morganfield, Ky., where UMW members have been on
a wildcat strike this week, authorities said.
   And coal trucks entering a Peabody mine near New Lexington, Ohio,
were stopped at gunpoint for the second time this week, although no
shots were fired either time.
   Odom said a ``rolling blockade'' of hundreds of cars and trucks
continued to clog the main coal hauling road Wednesday. ``They're
out there in full force, ignoring the court order,'' he said.
   Nearly every working day during the past three weeks, the
bumper-to-bumper convoys have tied up traffic on roads connecting
Pittston's processing plants with its supply mines.
   On June 26, Williams declared the union in contempt of court for
orchestrating the tactic two days the previous week and fined the
UMW and two officers $240,000.
   Williams said he will increase the daily fine to $550,000 for
further violations of the convoy ban.
   UMW attorney Mike Passino said the union will appeal the fines,
which now total $960,000.
   U.S. Secretary of Labor Elizabeth Hanford Dole, meanwhile, met in
Washington with UMW president Richard L. Trumka, who ``did not
request any action from her,'' Dole spokeswoman Johanna Schneider
said. She said the talks would continue and were fruitful.
</TEXT>
