<HEAD>Lawyers Appeal Against Saudi Arms Dealer's Extradition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to FIX typo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for jailed Saudi financier and
arms dealer Adnan Khashoggi have asked the Swiss to block a U.S.
request to extradite him so he may stand trial on fraud charges, a
Justice Ministry spokeswoman said.
   Khashoggi is charged in a U.S. indictment with helping ousted
Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos and his wife Imelda conceal
assets allegedly plundered from their homeleand.
   Ministry spokeswoman Ursula Riedel said it would be at least two
weeks before Swiss authorities reach a decision on whether to
extradite Khashoggi, who has been in custody since April 18.
   If authorities approve the extradition request, Khashoggi would
then have 30 days to take his appeal to the Swiss supreme court, the
Federal Tribunal.
   This could mean the former billionaire spending his 54th birthday
on July 25, and possibly many weeks more, in his small jail cell in
the Swiss capital.
   Ms. Riedel and Khashoggi's Swiss lawyer, Ralph Zloczower, both
declined to give details of the appeal against extradition, which
was submitted Tuesday.
   Khashoggi, the Marcoses, five other people and a California bank
were indicted in October by a U.S. District Court in New York.
   The indictment accuses the Marcoses of stealing more than $100
million from the Philippine treasury and using the money to buy real
estate and expensive art objects in New York.
   The U.S. government alleges Khashoggi posed as the owner of some
of the assets to conceal the Marcos' ownership. He is charged with
racketeering, conspiracy, obstruction of justice and mail fraud.
   Racketeering alone carries a penalty of up to 20 years in prison.
