<FIRST>r a PM-North-Ollie     07-06 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North-Ollie,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ollie Folks Don't Like Ollie North's Sentence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Awilda cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLLIE, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If it were up to folks in Ollie, Oliver North
wouldn't have been placed on two years' probation or fined $150,000
for Iran-Contra crimes.
   ``They shouldn't have given him anything. Hell, he should run for
president. He's the only one who's got any sense,'' Awilda Davis
said Wednesday while nursing a beer at the Old Ollie Inn, which she
used to own.
   ``They pardoned Nixon for what he did. Why can't they pardon
North?''
   A federal judge in Washington on Wednesday sentenced the
45-year-old former White House aide to suspended terms of three, two
and one years for three felony convictions by a jury two months ago.
   In addition to the fine, North also was ordered to devote 1,200
hours to a new program to help District of Columbia youths avoid
involvement with drugs.
   Like Ms. Davis, several other Ollie residents felt the former
Marine lieutenant colonel's sentence was too harsh, even though he
could have been sent to prison for 10 years.
   Ed Horras said North was ``the fall guy'' for the Reagan
administration when the Iran-Contra affair became public more than
two years ago. Horras said he would feel the same way even if the
town didn't share North's first name. The town of 220 residents
invited North to the ``Ollie Big Days'' celebration two years ago,
but he declined the invitation.
   North has contended that in the Iran-Contra affair _ in which
U.S. arms were secretly sold to Iran and profits were diverted to
the Nicaraguan rebels _ he only acted on behalf of Reagan
administration superiors.
   Horras believed him.
   ``I think he's a scapegoat,'' he said. ``If one man was able to
do that, what else is going on that we don't know about?''
   Ollie Mayor Dave Gentry said North was fortunate to receive the
suspended sentence.
   Now that North has been sentenced, Gentry expects fewer visits by
reporters and television news teams.
   ``It will probably be a little drabby now that that's not going
on anymore,'' Gentry said.
   One person who might not mind a return to normalcy is Ollie
Postmaster Bill Northup.
   ``During the Iran-Contra hearings, we got requests every single
day for postmarks for seven solid weeks. I guess we sent out about
4,000 across the country, even to Alaska and Hawaii,'' Northup said.
   ``But things have cooled off. I'll be looking for more (requests)
in the next few weeks because of the sentencing, but by and large I
think things will drop off.''
</TEXT>
