<DOCNO> AP890706-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0513EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-06 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Sharply for 4th Day, Tokyo Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell sharply today against the
Japanese yen for the fourth consecutive day while the Tokyo Stock
Exchange's key index rose moderately.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 113.77 points, or 0.34
percent, closing at 33,423.48.
   The dollar closed at 138.90 yen, down 1.30 yen from Wednesday's
close of 140.20 yen. It opened at 138.30 yen and ranged from 137.85
yen to 139.10 yen.
   The dollar now has fallen 5.05 yen in four trading days.
   Traders said speculation accounted for today's fluctuations as
investors tried to push the currency below the 138 yen mark.
   Daiwa Bank trader Mitsuhiko Kinugasa said most market players
were inclined to reduce their dollar holdings in anticipation that
the U.S. Federal Reserve Board might move toward easier credit.
   The Fed's policy-making committee met Wednesday and was to meet
again later today.
   ``The move toward easy credit would lead to interest rate cuts,
and would make the interest rate gap between the European currencies
and the dollar even narrower,'' Kinugasa said.
   Central banks of European nations, including West Germany and
France, raised their discount rates in concert last week.
   Lower U.S. interest rates make the dollar less attractive to
foreign investors.
   Kinugasa said, however, many investors avoided major moves before
Friday's announcement of the U.S. jobless rate in June, which will
influence the Fed's decision on whether to cut interest rates.
   On the stock exchange, the yen's strength against the dollar
reassured Japanese investors, said Kazuhiro Nomura, a dealer with
New Japan Securities Co.
   He said expectations of an easier credit policy in the United
States were the major buying incentive for Japanese investors.
   Trading was inactive, with first section volume estimated at 550
million, down from Wednesday's 650 million. Among the gainers were
construction and real estate issues.
</TEXT>
