<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0531EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DrugKilling     07-06 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Killing,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Brothers Arrested For Slaying Of Teen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry neighbors chased two crack users who used a
meat cleaver and baseball bat to kill an 18-year-old man in front of
his mother and sister after he forced them from his building,
authorities said.
   The four-block chase by six men ended in front of a police
station, where the two were arrested on second-degree murder
charges, police said.
   Hermenio Perez, 29, and his 26-year-old brother, Jose, went to
visit a woman who lived in the building early Wednesday and smoked
crack in her apartment, said police Inspector Joseph DeMartino.
   A resident of the building confronted Hermenio Perez, who was
smoking crack at the time, and told him to leave. The dispute turned
into a fistfight involving both brothers and Michael Taylor,
authorities said.
   The brothers left the building, promising to return. Police were
summoned, but arrived after the brothers had left.
   Police said the Perezes returned a short time later outside the
building. One was carrying a cane and a knife, the other had a meat
cleaver and a baseball bat, DeMartino said.
   Taylor and a group of residents confronted the brothers again and
a second altercation began.
   During the melee, Hermenio Perez struck Taylor with the meat
cleaver, and Jose Perez hit him with a baseball bat, DeMartino said.
   Taylor died in front of his mother and sister, DeMartino said.
   Two other people were treated and released at North Central Bronx
Hospital for minor injuries, police said.
</TEXT>
