<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0637EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     07-06 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Drops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major currencies in
choppy European trading early today amid speculation that the U.S.
Federal Reserve would lower interest rates. Gold prices fell in
Europe.
   After dropping in nervous early dealings, the dollar recovered
some ground in late morning trading and some traders talked of the
currency being oversold Wednesday in New York.
   Dealers said the market would look to the U.S. employment data
scheduled for release Friday for clues about the pace of U.S.
economic growth.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell for the fourth consecutive day to a closing 138.90
Japanese yen, down from 140.20 yen at Wednesday's close. Later, in
London, it edged back up to 139.10 yen.
   Other dollar rates in Europe compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.8900 West German marks, down from 1.8907
   _1.6210 Swiss francs, up from 1.6195
   _6.4095 French francs, down from 6.4125
   _2.1340 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1495
   _1,366.60 Italian lire, down from 1,380.50
   _1.1905 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1909
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6205 from $1.6155 late
Wednesday.
   Gold bullion opened in London at $384.40 a troy ounce, down from
$385.50 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $384.30.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $383.20, down from $384.50 bid
late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $5.38 to a closing bid of
$384.71.
   Silver bullion fell in London to $5.37 a troy ounce from $5.38
bid late Wednesday.
