<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0654EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AmericanHomecoming     07-06 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-American Homecoming,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stolar Returns to Hometown He Last Saw 58 Years Ago</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abe Stolar went to a baseball game to soak up some
long-missed Americana and watched his native town's Cubs, a team
that hasn't won a World Series during the 58 years Stolar lived in
the Soviet Union.
   ``It's beautiful here. It should be a painting,'' Stolar said
Wednesday night at Wrigley Field.
   The 77-year-old Stolar and his Soviet-born wife, Gita Rozovskaya,
arrived in Chicago on Tuesday from Israel, where the family settled
earlier this year after a 14-year battle to leave the Soviet Union.
   The Stolars joined U.S. Sen. Paul Simon and his wife, Jeanne, at
a game between the Cubs and San Diego Padres. Simon, D-Ill., met
Stolar during a 1980 trip to Moscow and was instrumental in securing
his release.
   ``This is much more comfortable, the Soviets just have benches at
events like this,'' said Stolar.
   Stolar was told by a reporter that the Cubs haven't won a World
Series since he left town. ``It'll come some day, don't worry,''
said Stolar.
   Having lived most of his life in the Soviet Union, Stolar admits
he's not much of a baseball fan. So why take in a ballgame on his
second day back in the United States?
   ``It's America,'' Simon said of the sport.
   Earlier Wednesday, Simon joined Stolar on a visit to the West
Side Chicago neighborhood where he grew up before his family pulled
up stakes and emigrated to the Soviet Union in 1931.
   ``I didn't expect anything,'' Stolar said of his sentimental
journey to Humboldt Park. ``That's what keeps me young. Everything I
get is a gift.''
   Spanish has replaced the Yiddish and Polish that once filled the
neighborhood's tenements.
   But Stolar found the soda fountain where as a teen-ager he mixed
ice cream concoctions, the third-floor apartment where he heard
adults passionately debate socialism and the high school where he
acted in a play.
   ``It all looks strange and new to me'' said Stolar, who found his
childhood home replaced by a garbage-strewn lot, ``but somehow it
feels like home.''
   Stolar plans to tour the city today. On Tuesday, he leaves
Chicago, the first stop on a 12-city trip to meet with Jewish-rights
leaders.
   Stolar's parents emigrated in 1910 from Russia to Chicago, where
he was born two years later.
   But in 1931, disillusioned by the Great Depression and drawn back
to their homeland by reports that the Bolshevik Revolution had
created a workers' paradise, the family headed east.
   Stolar's father was killed in the Stalinist purges, and his
mother and sister died after being sent to concentration camps in
Siberia.
   Stolar himself was wounded serving in the Soviet Army during
World War II, worked for Radio Moscow as a translator and announcer
and later married and had a son of his own, Michael.
   He was increasingly disillusioned with life in the Soviet Union,
but for years there was virtually no chance of emigrating.
   In 1974, prompted by concerns about his son's future and eased
U.S.-Soviet relations, Stolar applied for an exit visa.
   Stolar was disappointed several times in his effort to get his
family out. He became a cause celebre for several U.S.-based emigre
organizations, and dined with President Reagan in Moscow during last
year's summit.
   In March, Stolar finally left the Soviet Union with his wife, his
son and daughter-in-law, and their two children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890706-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0736EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-NewPosts     07-06 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-New Posts,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>New US Ambassador Named, Ministry Changes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese legislators today named a new ambassador
to the United States and replaced the ministers of labor and
chemical industry in an unusual mid-year shuffle.
   The National People's Congress' steering committee made the
appointments during a special session called to study and affirm the
ruling Communist Party's crackdown on the pro-democracy movement.
   The cabinet changes did not appear linked to the crackdown that
ousted party leader Zhao Ziyang.
   The evening television news said Zhu Qizhen, vice foreign
minister, was appointed ambassador to Washington to replace Han Xu,
who has held the post four years. The report said Han's term was up.
   Han, along with China's other ambassadors, was recalled to
Beijing last week for what the Foreign Ministry said was a regular
meeting, but Western diplomats said such recalls were not regular.
   Zhu, 61, speaks English fluently and formerly headed the
ministry's American and Oceanic Affairs Department.
   His appointment came as Chinese-U.S. relations continued to
worsen with the Foreign Ministry rejecting a U.S. protest over
soldiers' spraying gunfire at American and other foreign diplomatic
housing a few days after the army cleared central Beijing of
protesters, killing hundreds.
   The United States charged in its protest Monday that soldiers
staged an alleged sniper attack from the diplomatic compound so they
could deliberately target American and other diplomats' apartments.
   No one was hurt in the incident.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said Assistant Foreign Minister
Liu Huaqiu met today with U.S. Ambassador James Lilley and gave him
a note saying China ``categorically rejects the U.S. Embassy's
groundless accusation.''
   ``It is entirely futile for the U.S. Embassy to attempt to exert
pressure on the Chinese government by making a big fuss about an
incident which has already been resolved,'' the note said.
   Xinhua said Labor Minister Luo Gan, 53, who was appointed last
year, was replaced with Ruan Chongwu, a Moscow-educated party
veteran who was minister of public security from 1985-88.
   Ruan, 56, also was deputy secretary of Shanghai's party committee
in the early 1980's under Jiang Zemin, the new national party chief.
He has since last yeasr been vice minister in charge of the State
Science and Technology Commission.
   Xinhua did not mention Luo in its brief report on Ruan's
appointment, and gave no reason for the change. However, Hong Kong's
New Evening Post newspaper said Luo already had been given a new
post as secretary-general of the State Council, China's cabinet.
   China faces a serious problem of stagnant or declining labor
productivity. Productivity climbed in the early 1980's when senior
leader Deng Xiaoping enacted reforms that allowed worker to be given
incentive pay.
   But continued tight control over job changes, overstaffing and
inflation have counteracted some of the early gains, and many
workers spend hours of their workday drinking tea and playing chess.
   Gu Xiulian, until recently governor of the eastern province of
Jiangsu, was appointed minister of chemical industry, Xinhua said.
   She replaces Qin Zhongda, 65, who resigned, it said.
   Gu, 52, is a member of the party Central Committee, and was
China's first female governor. She was trained in metallurgy and
electrical mechanics.
   Xinhua said both new ministers were nominated by Premier Li Peng.
</TEXT>
