<FIRST>r a PM-AgentOrange     07-06 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agent Orange,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>$12 Million Distributed in First Year of Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agent Orange fund has dispensed $12 million
to thousands of Vietnam veterans, their families and support
organizations, and up to $60 million more will be handed out in the
next year, overseers of the fund say.
   The fund was created in 1984 when seven chemical companies agreed
to pay $180 million to settle a class-action lawsuit brought by
veterans and their families who alleged injuries from exposure to
the chemical during the war.
   ``We're moving very quickly. We're ahead of where I thought we
would be at this time,'' said Dennis Rhoades, director of the Agent
Orange Class Assistance Program, a social-service fund created to
distribute some of the money.
   By June 30, $11.8 million in cash was distributed during the
fund's first year, according to an annual report Wednesday. The
report said 6,039 veterans or their survivors received $9.5 million;
the rest went to 13 organizations.
   The program administered by U.S. District Judge Jack B. Weinstein
is expected to distribute some $300 million in all by the end of
1994, including as much as $60 million during the next 12 months,
the report said.
   Agent Orange, a herbicide widely used by American forces to
destroy ground cover during the Vietnam War, contained the highly
toxic chemical dioxin.
   In their lawsuit, veterans said exposure to Agent Orange caused
cancer and other illnesses, as well as birth defects in their
children.
   Distribution of the money in the fund was held up by challenges
for four years until the U.S. Supreme Court a year ago refused to
hear appeals.
</TEXT>
