<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru   07-06 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0472,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>News Censorship in Sri Lanka to Cover Foreign Media</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with gov't willing to hold talks
with India on troop withdrawal. Pickup 4th graf `The censorship...'; SUBS
14th graf `It has...' with 2 grafs with details. Picup 15th graf, `Tamils
comprise...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today extended tough
censorship laws to foreign media and said security forces can shoot
Sinhalese radicals engaging in violence or putting up
anti-government posters.
   ``No news whatsoever can go out of this country without being
censored,'' Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratna told a news
conference. ``If you cannot conform to that, please leave the
country.''
   ``I will cancel your visas and deport you if you violate the
censorship,'' he told reporters, who included several foreign
correspondents. ``If I decide to cancel a visa, no appeals will be
considered.''
   The government also said today that talks with India about
withdrawing Indian troops should be held in Sri Lanka. The 40,000
troops were invited to Sri Lanka nearly two years ago to enforce a
peace plan, but the Colombo government wants them out by the end of
the month.
   The censorship laws, which ban reporting on the radical Sinhalese
movement, went into effect this morning. The ban was announced
Wednesday and, initially, foreign media organizations were exempted.
   Wijeratna said the move is part of a crackdown on the radicals,
who have been trying to overthrow the government for two years.
   The government, controlled by the island's Sinhalese majority,
says the radicals are behind a 4-week-old strike by transport
operators, which has crippled the economy of this troubled Indian
Ocean island nation.
   ``We will not allow the government to be displaced by gun-toting
criminals,'' Wijeratna said. ``Our armed forces and police have been
given wide powers to deal with all form of subversion in the most
ruthless manner.''
   He said this included shoot-on-sight orders on those indulging in
violence or putting up anti-government posters. All public meetings
and trade union rallies have also been banned, he said.
   The government blames Sinhalese militants for at least 3,500
killings since they launched an anti-government campaign in July
1987 to protest peace overtures being made to separatist Tamil
rebels.
   The Sinhalese militants said too many concessions were being
given to the minority Tamils, who have been fighting since 1983 for
an independent nation on the island's northern and eastern sectors.
   Since May, the government has been holding talks with the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the most powerful rebel militia.
The Tigers rejected the 1987 overtures and carried on the war for a
Tamil homeland, but last month they agreed to cease hostilities
against the government and negotiate a settlement.
   However, they continue to fight the 40,000 Indian soldiers
deployed on the island to help end the Tamil insurrection. The New
Delhi government has refused to stop fighting the rebels until they
surrender their weapons.
   India has also not agreed to Colombo's requests to pull out the
soldiers by July 29, the second anniversary of their landing in Sri
Lanka, saying a hasty withdrawal could lead to even greater ethnic
violence.
   India has suggested that negotiations be held for a gradual
pullout. On Tuesday, Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi offered to
discuss a timetable.
   ``If India wants to sit down and talk about the troop withdrawal,
they will have to send somebody to talk to President (Ranasinghe)
Premadasa, who is handling the issue personally,'' Wijeratna told a
news conference today.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
complain of discrimination by the Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent
of the population and control the government and military.
   At least 9,000 people have been killed in the Tamil insurrection.
</TEXT>
