<FIRST>r a PM-MissilesScrapped     07-06 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missiles Scrapped,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last of Pershing 1A Missiles to Be Scrapped</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Event scheduled for noon EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARNACK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army technicians strapped rocket sections
to reinforced stands for the destruction today of the nation's last
Pershing 1A and the first-ever elimination of an entire class of
nuclear weapons.
   Officials at the Longhorn Army Ammunition plant planned to fire
the two sections of the unarmed, 5,500-pound ballistic missile in
horizontal position today. After consuming their solid fuel, the
sections were to be crushed.
   The operation comes under terms of the Intermediate-range Nuclear
Forces treaty signed in 1987 by President Reagan and Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev.
   The INF treaty requires elimination of 859 American
intermediate-range and shorter range missiles and 1,752 similar
Soviet missiles within three years.
   A 10-member Soviet inspection team was to monitor today's
destruction of the 169th and last Pershing 1A. Hundreds of larger
Pershing 2 missiles and ground-launched cruise missiles are also
being destroyed under the treaty.
   The Soviets began destroying several classes of similar missiles
a year ago.
   Nuclear warheads are removed beforehand from the missiles marked
for destruction, which have a range of 300 to 3,400 miles.
   The destruction of the Pershing 1A is being handled by Morton
Thiokol Inc., which built many of the Pershing motors.
   In September, then-Vice President Bush made a campaign stop of
the first missile destruction at Longhorn, hailing the event as
``the day we began to reverse the arms race.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
