<FIRST>r a PM-Hamlet'sDagger     07-06 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hamlet's Dagger,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hamlet's Dagger Hits Theatergoer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patricia Spahic knows too well what it means to
suffer the slings and arrows of outrageous fortune.
   During a fight scene in the final act of the Three Rivers
Shakespeare Festival's production of ``Hamlet'' Wednesday night, a
dagger sailed into the third row and hit Mrs. Spahic. The blade
glanced her forehead, leaving a cut.
   ``It was almost like a setup,'' Mrs. Spahic's daughter, Mary Beth
Spahic, 30, of Ambridge, said today.
   ``You couldn't imagine you'd be struck with anything falling from
a play. Yet everything that was happening was so close to the
audience _ smoke and a trap door slamming _ that you also question
why somebody wouldn't get hurt.''
   Mrs. Spahic, 63, of Ambridge, was treated at a hospital and
released.
   ``It was just a slice, a gash. It drew blood,'' said Miss Spahic,
wo sat beside her mother at the 560-seat Stephen Foster Memorial
theater and spoke for her today. ``She's not upset or anything, but
I don't think she'll be laughing today.''
   The mishap occurred during the fight in which Hamlet and Laertes
both die. As Hamlet drew his dagger, it slipped his grasp.
   Richard McMillan, who played Hamlet, immediately stopped the show
and asked if there was a doctor in the house as the lights came up.
A physician rushed to the woman's side and helped the stage crew
escort her to an ambulance.
   The play resumed within minutes.
</TEXT>
