<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0949EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-EasternEurope     07-06 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Eastern Europe,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eagleburger Says Reform Pace Depends on East Europeans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger
said today that while the United States and other Western
governments intend to assist Poland and Hungary in developing
free-market economies, the pace of reform depends primarily on the
East Europeans themselves.
   ``In the last analysis, the decisions are going to have to be
made in Warsaw and Budapest,'' Eagleburger said in a
government-sponsored telecast to Europe as President Bush prepared
for a visit next week to the two Soviet bloc capitals.
   ``The president will be bringing some support,'' Eagleburger
said. ``How much and what kind I will leave until he gets there.''
   The State Department official said the U.S. purpose was to help
the Polish and Hungarian economies adopt a free-market system and to
place decisions in the hands of private individuals instead of the
communist governments.
   But Eagleburger seemed to indicate U.S. support would be
conditioned on changes by the Polish and Hungarian governments.
Reform, he said, ``has to be done basically by the peoples and
governments involved.''
   He also cautioned that reform should proceed at a measured pace,
without explaining what potential perils he foresaw.
   The U.S. interest in helping is that economic change will ease
the divisions between East and West in Europe and make further U.S.
and Soviet troops reductions there possible, Eagleburger said.
   Bush last month proposed cutbacks to equal levels of 275,000
troops, as well as reductions in tanks, artillery and other
non-nuclear weapons. Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev earlier
made his own dramatic proposals for cutbacks.
   On related issues, Eagleburger said U.S. policy calls for the
reunification of West Germany and East Germany into one nation, and
he predicted the U.S. Senate would follow the lead of the House and
approve easier credit terms for Hungary.
</TEXT>
