<FIRST>u a PM-LoweLawsuit     07-06 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lowe Lawsuit,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Part of Lawsuit Against Rob Lowe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today dismissed part of a lawsuit
accusing Rob Lowe of enticing a teen-age girl into sexual antics on
videotape.
   The girl's mother, Lena Arlene Wilson, had sued the heartthrob
actor under a Georgia law involving the seduction of a minor
daughter, and she also alleged that Lowe intentionally inflicted
emotional distress on her family.
   U.S. District Judge G. Ernest Tidwell, who heard arguments last
week on Lowe's request that the lawsuit be thrown out, agreed to
dismiss the claim of emotional distress, saying the suit did not
offer enough facts to warrant the allegation.
   But the judge refused to dismiss the claim for damages for
seduction.
   The lawsuit stems from a videotape Lowe purportedly made in his
hotel suite while in Atlanta last summer for the Democratic National
Convention.
   The tape _ widely circulated on Atlanta's party circuit and shown
electronically censored on TV news _ apparently shows Lowe, Ms.
Wilson's daughter, Jan Parsons, and another woman in sexual
escapades.
   In May, Ms. Wilson sued, contending Lowe enticed her daughter,
then 16, into having sex with another woman while Lowe videotaped
them.
   Edgar Neely III, an attorney for Lowe, had argued that the
lawsuit should be dismissed because only a custodial parent may sue
under Georgia law. Neely said the girl's parents are divorced, and
her father has custody.
   But J. Hue Henry, Ms. Wilson's attorney, said that Miss Parsons
was living with her mother at the time and that the tape humiliated
the family and strained Ms. Wilson's relationship with her daughter.
   Lowe, 25, is the star of such films as ``St. Elmo's Fire'' and
``About Last Night.''
</TEXT>
