<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     07-06 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christians and Syrians Blast Residential Areas; Four Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese Christian and Syrian army gunners
blasted Beirut's segregated residential suburbs with thunderous
barrages of shellfire today. Police said four people were killed and
eight wounded.
   The armies ignored a joint appeal for a cease-fire by France and
the Soviet Union. The fighting ended a two-day lull that came after
Lebanese Moslem forces reopened land crossings dividing the
capital's Christian and Moslem sectors.
   Police said Syrian troops attacked a ship cruising off the
Christian port of Byblos. The troops have enforced a 16-week
blockade to prevent the Christians from getting arms supplies.
   ``The ship is cruising back and forth three miles off Byblos with
shells falling around it,'' said a police spokesman, who cannot be
named under standing regulations. He said he did not have details of
the ship's identity, owners or cargo. Byblos is 20 miles north of
Beirut.
   The mainly Christian Lebanese army accused the Syrians of
provoking the battle with early morning shelling of residential
centers in the 310-square-mile Christian enclave where a million
people are trapped.
   A spokesman for Maronite Gen. Michel Aoun said his gunners
responded ``only against Syrian artillery and rocket emplacements.''
But howitzer rounds also rained on areas that do not harbor
batteries.
   The spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, called on
residents of Moslem west Beirut to stay away from areas around
Syrian artillery.
   The bombardment caught people in the morning rush hour.
   Panicking motorists honked their horns hysterically and sped in
all directions. Pedestrians dove for cover and shopkeepers hurriedly
lowered their shutters against flying shrapnel.
   Rockets flew overhead, and artillery blasts shook both sectors as
the city streets emptied.
   The police spokesman said four people were killed and eight
wounded, bringing the toll to 401 killed and 1,546 wounded since
fighting began March 8 between Aoun's mostly Christian troops and
allied Syrian and Druse forces.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and President Francois
Mitterrand of France appealed Wednesday for a cease-fire to be
``rigorously respected'' by all Lebanese factions.
   Syria is Moscow's chief Arab ally. Paris, which ruled Lebanon
until its independence in 1943, traditionally supports the
Christians but has assumed a neutral role in the latest fighting.
   In a joint statement ending a visit to France by Gorbachev, the
two leaders expressed support for an Arab League initiative to
settle the 14-year civil war but also said their countries can help
``notably in the framework of the United Nations Security Council.''
   France and the Soviet Union are among the five permanent members
of the council. Britain, China and the United States are the others.
   Gorbachev and Mitterrand said they are ``convinced that Lebanon
must remain sovereign, independent, united, with its territorial
integrity respected.''
   Aoun has pledged to drive out the 40,000 Syrian troops in
Lebanon, charging they have violated their 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate by siding with the Moslems. But his 20,000
troops are outnumbered 4-to-1 by those of Syria and allied Lebanese
Moslem militias.
</TEXT>
