<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0506,0741</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Drenches East Coast for a Second Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with third person missing in Delaware,
rain records in N.J., Georgia storm stranding motorists; PICKS UP 12th
graf pvs, `Near Alexandria ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain continued for a second day today on the already
saturated East Coast, and flash flood watches were posted in seven
states.
   Thunderstorms produced large hail and strong winds in Minnesota
late Wednesday. Winds gusted to 62 mph at International Falls and
blew over vehicles and downed trees at Pelican Lake. The storms
weakened early today.
   The rains in the Northeast were remnants of Tropical Storm
Allison, which came ashore last week and dumped up to 20 inches of
rain in Texas and Louisiana.
   Wednesday's storms were blamed for at least two deaths.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms extended from Florida and the
central Gulf Coast to New England early today, with rain most
prevalent from central Virginia to coastal New England.
   Flash flood watches were in effect in North Carolina, Virginia,
West Virginia, Maryland, Pennsylvania, New Jersey and New York.
   Two people drowned and a third person was missing today in
Delaware, where up to 10 inches of rain drenched the state. More
than 450 people were forced to evacuate their homes. Rainfall
amounts included 9.52 inches at Claymont and 6.63 at Wilmington, the
highest 24-hour total for any July day in 95 years of recordkeeping.
   Rainfall records also were broken throughout New Jersey,
including Newark, which logged 2.45 inches of rain.
   Rain washed out track beds and reduced Amtrak service between
Washington and New York City to one track. The hardest hit area was
between Wilmington and Philadelphia, where rain fell at up to 3
inches an hour, said Amtrak spokeswoman Cliff Black.
   In Philadelphia, three workers were injured at the Naval Shipyard
when a tarpaulin tore open and sent them plunging 40 feet to the
deck of an aircraft carrier, a shipyard spokesman said. The three
were bailing rainwater out of the tarp.
   A driving thunderstorm stranded hundreds of motorists in Cobb
County, Ga., overturning mobile homes and flooding streets. Police
today said crews worked past midnight to free the drivers, hours
after the rain ended.
   Near Alexandria, La., 56 residents in Rapides Parish were
evacuated by Wednesday night as officials warned of backwater
flooding.
   A few showers dampened western New Mexico and southeastern
Arizona today.
   Record high temperatures for the date Wednesday were set in
Wyoming, North Dakota, Nebraska, Florida and Colorado, where at
least seven communities broke the 100-degree mark.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
northern Minnesota across northern Wisconsin to upper Michigan;
along the East Coast from southern and central New England across
much of New York state through Florida; and over Alabama and
Mississippi and much of Louisiana, Tennessee, Kentucky and West
Virginia.
   Predicted highs: in the upper 80s and in the low 90s from
northern New England across the lower Great Lakes, from the South
Carolina coast across Florida, over the lower Mississippi Valley,
northern Minnesota and the upper Missouri Valley; in the 90s over
the remainder of the Mississippi Valley, the remainder of the
Plains, from southern Montana across New Mexico, over the Great
Basin and the central Pacific Coast; 100 degrees and higher from
western Montana across Utah and central California: from 115 to 120
over the Desert Southwest; and in the 80s over much of the rest of
the nation.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 49 degrees at Yellowstone
Park, Wyo., to 96 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 74 foggy; Boston 65 rain; Buffalo 67 fair;
Charleston, S.C., 78 fair; Cincinnati 71 fair; Cleveland 68 fair;
Miami 74 fair; New York 69 foggy; Philadelphia 70 drizzle;
Pittsburgh 67 foggy; Portland, Maine, 65 rain; Washington 73 showers.
   _Central: Bismarck 72 fair; Chicago 74 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 77
fair; Denver 71 fair; Des Moines 68 fair; Indianapolis 73 hazy;
Kansas City 72 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 77 fair; Nashville 71
foggy; New Orleans 76 foggy; St. Louis 77 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 77 fair; Anchorage 52 partly cloudy; Las Vegas
87 fair; Los Angeles 65 foggy; Phoenix 93 fair; Salt Lake City 67
fair; San Diego 64 foggy; San Francisco 55 fair; Seattle 58 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 66 fair; Toronto 63 fair.
</TEXT>
