<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-BusPlunge 5thLd-Writethru a0514 07-06 0978</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Bus Plunge, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0514,1002</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police: Palestinian Forces Bus Into Ravine, 14 Killed, 27 Hurt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE death toll, five Americans injured, quotes
from witnesses, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABU GHOSH, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian shouting ``Allahu Akbar''
grabbed the steering wheel of a crowded passenger bus today and
forced it into a deep ravine where it burst into flames, police
said. Fourteen people were reported killed and 27 injured, including
five Americans.
   Police Commissioner David Kraus said other victims were believed
still trapped inside the bus, which was gutted by flames and lay on
its roof down a slope off the Tel Aviv-Jerusalem highway.
   ``Allahu Akbar,'' or ``God is great,'' has become a battle cry of
the nearly 19-month-old Palestinian uprising.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir called the incident ``a shocking
disaster, the fruit of a disgusting mind, hate-filled. We have
reached the height of madness, a product of flowing hatred
(engendered) by endless incitement.''
   ``It doesn't matter much if this is a result of an organized plan
or a result of the atmosphere some groups create,'' he said on army
radio. ``I think we will find a way to take care of incidents like
this.''
   An Arab passenger believed to have grabbed the steering wheel was
arrested. He was at Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital, where director
Avi Israeli said he was treated for head and chest injuries.
   Police said the man would be questioned about his motive after he
recovered. They said he was from the occupied territories but was
not carryng an identification card.
   A reporter saw rescuers remove 17 body bags from the bus scene,
but it was uncertain if they contained full or partial remains.
   Other bags containing victims' belongings also were brought out
of the ravine, including glasses, shoes, canteens, a purse and
wallets, and a Book of Psalms.
   At least five of the injured were Americans, officials at
Hadassah Hospital said. They did not identify the American victims
by name.
   It was the worst such incident since March 11, 1978, when
Palestinian guerrillas from the PLO's Fatah faction infiltrated
Israel from the sea and hijacked a bus on the coastal highway.
Thirty-three people were killed and 82 were wounded.
   Angry Israelis called a popular radio talk show and demanded the
death penalty for terrorists.
   The bus driver, interviewed from his hospital bed on army radio,
said a bearded Arab man of about 25 approached him suddenly and
grabbed the wheel.
   ``I thought he wanted to ask me something, like everybody does on
the way. But he jumped on the steering wheel, shouted ``Allahu
Akbar'' and pulled it with all his strength to the right,'' said the
driver, Moshe Elul.
   Elul said he tried with all his strength to turn the wheel back
to the left ``but he simply sat down and put his legs on the front
dashboard to give him support, and that's how he dragged us down.''
   ``I woke up when the bus started to turn really sharply to the
right,'' said Victor Assal, 23, of Bethesda, Md. ``I saw people
screaming up front. All of a sudden the ground turned 90 degrees.
The first thing I did was grab for my gun. Then I lost
consciousness.''
   Assal, who emigrated to Israel last year and now serves in the
army, said he was on his way to visit his mother in Jerusalem when
the bus overturned.
   Today's crash occurred at 11:40 a.m. The red-and-white bus of the
state-run Egged company, one of many that makes the 45-minute run
between Tel Aviv and Jerusalem daily, broke through a steel barrier
on a straight section of the four-lane highway near this Israeli
Arab village, about seven miles west of Jerusalem.
   Witnesses said the bus, which seats about 50 people, was full.
The number of passengers could be higher, however, since people
often stand on the ride.
   A witness identified only as Reuven said on Israel radio that he
pulled the driver from the bus and the driver said: ``How did he do
this to me?''
   An army rescue team was brought in, and dozens of motorists left
their vehicles to climb into the ravine and recover victims, some
scaling down on ropes. Orthodox students in black hats and long
coats rushed from a nearby Jewish seminary to help.
   ``I ran across the road and saw bodies strewn all down the
ravine,'' said Yitzhak Cohen, 44, a businessman who was driving past
when the crash occurred.
   He said he heard a young female soldier in the bus screaming,
``Save me, save me!,'' and he helped her crawl out of the bus
through a window.
   It was unclear how quickly the bus caught fire. The gutted
vehicle was resting on its roof at the ravine's bottom, and army
teams brought by helicopter were assisting in the rescue.
   Injured victims were being taken out of the ravine by small Huey
helicopters and transferred to a larger CH-53 chopper that landed on
the roadway. They were being evacuated to hospitals.
   Police roped off the roadway, but traffic was being rerouted on a
side road through Abu Ghosh.
   Daniel Mordechai, a 48-year-old carpenter from Ramle, said he
arrived moments after it happened.
   ``At first there was a small fire like a camp fire. Then there
was a huge explosion. We didn't want to get too close to the bus
because we were afraid of getting hurt. So we helped those who were
blown out of the bus,'' he said.
   The crash came five weeks after a lone Arab wielding a knife
fatally stabbed two elderly Jews and injured three in downtown
Jerusalem.
   The murderer, Nidal Zaloum, 22, of the West Bank town of
Ramallah, was sentenced in June to life in prison for the attack. He
had shouted ``Allahu Akbar!'' when he attacked his victims,
witnesses said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890706-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Obit-Kadar 2ndLd-Writethru   07-06 1102</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Kadar, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0502,1139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary's Longtime Communist Leader Dead at 77</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Nagy legally rehabilitated,
media programming, Pickup 5th graf `Kadar was...' Subs grafs 12-13 `He
died...last month.'' with 3 grafs to CONFORM. Pickup 14th graf `Kadar's
change...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY18</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Janos Kadar, who took power after the
Soviets crushed the 1956 revolt and steered Hungary through relative
prosperity until moderates forced him out during hard times, died
today. He was 77.
   Kadar's death came as the Supreme Court canceled all charges
against former Premier Imre Nagy and his associates who led the 1956
uprising and were executed under Kadar on charges of high treason.
   The decision signified Nagy's legal rehabilitation.
   Kadar, the communist who led Hungary for 32 years until last year
and who ultimately came to symbolize resistance to democratic
change, died this morning after ``a prolonged, grave illness'' the
state-run MTI news agency said.
   The agency said the ruling Communist Party had ``with profound
sorrow'' informed its members and the Hungarian people of
``comrade'' Kadar's death.
   MTI said funeral arrangements would be announced later. It was
considered unlikely he would be buried before President Bush's visit
next week.
   Hungarian television broadcast a half-hour documentary on his
life this morning, and two Budapest radio stations canceled all
programming containing rock 'n' roll music and light entertainment.
   Kadar was hospitalized Monday with pneumonia and severe breathing
and circulatory problems.
   He was first reported gravely ill in April and in May lost his
post as honorary party chairman as well as a seat on the party's
Central Committee, which wrote him a letter criticizing mistakes
during his lengthy rule.
   Since he was replaced by Karoly Grosz in May 1988 as party
general secretary, Kadar's political legacy has come under fierce
attack and the communists have moved rapidly to embrace democratic
change, promising contested elections and a multiparty system.
   After guiding Hungary in the 1970's to relative prosperity and
freedom dubbed ``goulash communism'' in the West, Kadar came to be
seen as an impediment to further reform in the 1980s.
   He will perhaps be most remembered for his 1962 statement to a
rally in the industrial town of Csepel: ``Those who are not against
us are with us.''
   By the mid-1980s, Hungary's economy was in a tailspin and the
Soviet Union was undergoing a political rebirth under Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   Kadar fell out of favor in ruling circles.
   In a published response May 10 that MTI said was Kadar's last
public statement, the former leader admitted ``mistakes'' but said:
``My actions were guided by good intentions.''
   In apparent reference to the 1958 execution of Nagy and hundreds
of others after the 1956 revolt, Kadar said in the letter, ``I hope
... that future generations will assess more objectively the results
and errors of the past 30 years.''
   Nagy's remains, initially placed in an unmarked grave, were
reburied in a government-sanctioned ceremony June 16 that drew
hundreds of thousands of mourners marked his de facto political
rehabilitation.
   Kadar's change in fortunes was typical of a long career that
began in 1931 when he joined the illegal Communist Party as a
19-year-old from a peasant background, with only eight years of
schooling.
   Kadar was jailed and seemingly forgotten after a party purge in
1951 but was rehabilitated after the downfall of his Stalinist
rival, Matyas Rakosi.
   While in power, Kadar was conciliatory and ruthless by turns.
   In an interview with The Associated Press in 1965, he made a
prophetic comment: ``You have strummed a string to the effect that,
when the monolithic unity of the Communist countries is ended, what
is left?''
   Kadar was born May 26, 1912, in the Adriatic port of Fiume, which
was renamed Rijeka and became part of Yugoslavia when the
Austro-Hungarian Empire broke up.
   He advanced through Communist Party ranks to Central Committee
membership in May 1942, having spent more than three years in prison
on various political charges.
   After the communist takeover in 1948, Kadar became interior
minister in Rakosi's Stalinist regime but it was never clear whether
he controlled the feared political police.
   Rakosi kept a jealous eye on Kadar's progress and had him
arrested in 1951 on charges of espionage and treason. When Stalin
died in 1953, Rakosi's grip on power began to slip. Kadar was freed
and rehabilitated the next year.
   Growing discontent led to Rakosi's ouster in July 1956, but
dissatisfaction continued and a popular uprising began within three
months. Tens of thousands of students filled the streets, demanding
a free press, withdrawal of Soviet troops and a multiparty politics.
   Kadar became party leader a few days later, left the capital and
announced that he had established a rival government to that of
Premier Nagy.
   On Nov. 3, he asked the Kremlin to help end the revolt.
   Red Army forces moved in and Kadar instituted two years of
repression. Nagy and his associates were executed in June 1958.
   Less than four months after Nagy's death, Kadar embarked on
economic reform that brought growing prosperity and increasingly
cordial ties with the West.
   A reticent man who liked chess and reading, Kadar has been
described as a ``sad, ascetic man'' with ``an intense face.'' A
dedicated hunter, he told The AP hunting trips with Soviet leader
Nikita Khrushchev ``were no diplomatic pretexts for me.''
   ``If you enter a wood even as much as a meter, speech stops,'' he
said. ``You don't make a noise. You don't talk in the woods. There
is silence. That is why I like it.''
   Kadar played a shadowy role in the short-lived Czechoslovak
liberalization of 1968. It was said that he opposed intervention in
Czechoslovakia, but Hungarian soldiers joined the Soviet-led
invasion.
   His reforms in the 1970's foreshadowed the modernization
Gorbachev now is pursuing in the Soviet Union: less central
planning, more competition and weeding out or streamlining of
unprofitable state concerns.
   Economic problems increased, however. By the late 1980's,
inflation was 18 percent and the foreign debt $18 billion, the
highest per capita in the Soviet bloc. Large price increases and
other austerity measures fed discontent and the perception that
Kadar was largely to blame.
   Eight months after Grosz replaced Kadar, parliament legalized
independent political movements.
   And this year, the party decided the 1956 revolt was a popular
uprising, not the counterrevolution it had been called for 33 years.
On June 16, Nagy's remains were reburied with honor.
   In a serialized interview with the weekly Magyarorszag, Kadar
said: ``Nagy's tragedy is my own personal tragedy as well.''
   He is survived by his wife, Maria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
