<FIRST>r w PM-ArabLeague     07-06 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arab League,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab League Declares Election Plan Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Politics Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arab League today declared that Israel's
plan for elections in the occupied territories was dead and urged
the United States to abandon support for the initiative.
   The league's envoy, Clovis Maksoud, said he would meet Friday
with State Department officials and ask the United States to support
the convening of an international conference to bring about peace
talks between Israel and its Arab neighbors.
   Maksoud said at a news conference that the decision by Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir to accede to demands by his hard-line
supporters had rendered useless his proposal for elections among the
1.7 million Palestinians under Israeli occupation in the West Bank
and the Gaza Strip.
   The Shamir plan ``was devised as a public relations gimmick to
defuse public outrage against Israel's inhuman and illegal
measures'' in crushing the 18-month Palestinian uprising, Maksoud
said.
   ``I hope the U.S. administration is sufficiently jolted by this
rude rebuke of its support for its protege to undertake a
long-overdue and profound reassessment'' of its support for the
Shamir plan.
   The next step should be for the United States to ``remove its
protective shield'' from the Shamir government and join European
countries and the Soviet Union in supporting an international peace
conference.
   Maksoud said he hopes President Bush's upcoming trip to Europe
will ``sensitize him to the support of U.S. allies for an
international conference and make him more willing to distance
himself from the intransigent excesses of Israel.''
   Shamir's election plan should now be turned into a referendum
among Israelis to determine whether a majority supports the
right-wing prime minister, Maksoud said.
   The envoy also said an attack Thursday by an Arab who plunged an
Israeli bus into a ravine reportedly killing 14 people ``was
testimony to the exasperation'' of Palestinians living under Israeli
occupation.
   Maksoud said that while such acts are not authorized by the
leadership of the Palestinian uprising and ``are not to be condoned,
at times they have to be understood.''
</TEXT>
