<HEAD>Mayor: Call Out the Guard to Clean Up Garbage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With garbage piling up on the
streets, the mayor of this debt-ridden city wants the National Guard
called out to clean up the mess.
   But a spokesman for Gov. James R. Thompson said that's not likely
to happen.
   East St. Louis has had only sporadic garbage pickup for months.
Mayor Carl E. Officer said the desperately poor Mississippi River
city of 55,000 cannot afford to pay its garbage collector.
   ``Several years ago, the National Guard came into East St. Louis
and assisted us on a cleanup,'' Officer said Wednesday. He said he
expected ``a positive response'' from Thompson on sending the Guard
into East St. Louis.
   But David Fields, a spokesman for Thompson, said that is not an
appropriate use of soldiers, and Guard spokesman Maj. Bob Arnett
said the National Guard has never been called for garbage duty in
East St. Louis.
   ``You can't send the National Guard to every city that needs its
garbage picked up,'' Fields said.
