<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Earthquakes     07-06 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Earthquakes,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Tremors Strike Central Japan for 7th Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of tremors struck an area southwest of the
capital today, the seventh day of quakes that have burst water pipes
and shaken the tiles off roofs in a seaside tourist town, officials
said.
   The Meteorological Agency said 2,506 tremors, including a quake
measuring 4.3 on the Richter scale and 66 others felt by citizens,
were recorded off the peninsula in the first 20 hours of the day.
   They brought to 11,286 the number of tremors reported in the area
since Friday. They were focused at depths of 2.5 to 3.1 miles under
the seabed and about four miles northwest of Ito, a seaside town 60
miles southwest of Tokyo, the agency said. Police said no casualties
or significant damage were reported.
   In Ito, four cases of burst water pipes, 14 cases of roof tiles
or stones falling off buildings or walls, and some ground cracks
were reported, said Setsuo Koizumi, a city official.
   Quakes on Wednesday included one measuring 4.9 on the Richter
scale that also caused some minor damage, officials said.
   A 13-member subcommittee of the government's Coordinating
Committee for Earthquake Prediction, met in an emergency session
Wednesday and called for a close watch to determine the potential
for a major earthquake.
   ``The tremors are believed to have been caused by magma movements
in the volcanic activity developing undersea off the peninsula since
the fall of 1978. The seismic levels in the current series of
tremors are considerably strong when compared to the previous ones
reported in the same area almost every year during the past
decade,'' said Kiyoo Mogi, a University of Tokyo professor who heads
the subcommittee.
   Mogi said in a telephone interview that in the same general area,
nearly 17,000 tremors, including some 290 felt by citizens, occurred
over a one-month period that began in late July last year.
   The Richter scale measures the magnitude of a quake at its
epicenter. An earthquake of 5 is capable of causing considerable
damage in populated areas.
</TEXT>
