<SECOND>PM-PLO-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0493,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Spokesman Says Likud Decision Closes Door to Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Arab League comment in Washington,
moves up background. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
newly announced hard-line conditions for dealing with the
Palestinians have closed the door to peace, PLO spokesman Ahmed
Abdul-Rahman said today.
   He said the nearly 19-month-old uprising of Palestinians in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip would be ``escalated
because this is the only answer to intransigence.''
   The Palestine Liberation Organization spokesman said Shamir had
also ``closed the door in the face'' of President Bush and Secretary
of State James A. Baker III, ``the only ones working for peace.
   ``These efforts now face total failure,'' he said.
   In Washington, the Arab League declared Israel's election plan
dead and urged the United States to abandon support for the
initiative.
   Clovis Maksoud, the league's envoy, said he would meet Friday
with State Department officials and ask Washington to support the
convening of an international conference to bring about peace talks
between Israel and its Arab neighbors.
   ``I hope the U.S. administration is sufficiently jolted by this
rude rebuke of its support for its protege to undertake a
long-overdue and profound reassessment'' of its support for the
Shamir plan, Maksoud said.
   In a speech Wednesday, Shamir ruled out several peace options
considered to be attractive to the Palestinians.
   He said elections in the occupied territories for Palestinians
who would then negotiate with Israel on autonomy could be held only
after the uprising had been crushed.
   He also said Palestinian Arabs living in East Jerusalem would not
be allowed to vote in any elections and vowed to continue building
settlements in the territories.
   Shamir's new tough stance subdued a challenge to his leadership
of the right-wing Likud bloc.
   Abdul-Rahman said Shamir's speech had ``endangered'' the chances
for peace. ``There is a complete rejection of American and
Palestinian efforts to bring about peace.''
   He said the Palestinian leadership would meet within the next few
days to consider their position in the light of Shamir's speech.
   ``We will be contacting the American side to hear what they are
going to do,'' Abdul-Rahman said.
   He also said the Palestinians would ask the five permanent
members of the U.N. Security Council to take steps to convene an
international conference on the Middle East ``now that Shamir has
blocked the American initiative which was the only initiative going
and which had Soviet support.''
</TEXT>
