<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Terrorist     07-06 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Terrorist,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Held In Connection With Bombing Plots Against Israeli, U.S.
Targets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have arrested a Lebanese
student on suspicion of plotting to bomb Israeli and American
targets in West Germany, law enforcement officials said today.
   Erwin Hoesl, an investigator for the Bavarian Criminal Office in
Munich, said the 21-year-old suspect is a ``fanatical'' Shiite
Moslem and that investigators uncovered the alleged plot ``just in
time'' before any attacks could be carried out.
   According to Hoesl, the suspect was apparently under contract
with Arab terrorist organizations in the Middle East. He was
arrested June 22 in a raid on his apartment in Darmstadt, 20 miles
south of Frankfurt. Many American military facilities are located in
both cities.
   Bavarian authorities declined to reveal the suspect's name but
said he has been a physics student at Darmstadt Technical University.
   The Munich-based Sueddeutsche Zeitung newspaper, however,
reported the suspect's first name and the first letter of his last
name, Bassan M.
   It said he has lived in Darmstadt since 1985 and that
investigators found instructions for making a bomb in his apartment.
   Police said no explosives were found.
   An earlier Bavarian police statement said the June 22 raid on the
student's apartment turned up evidence that bombing attacks were
planned on certain Israeli and American targets, which it did not
identify.
   Police said documents were found ``that indicate he scouted out
Israeli and American establishments for Middle East contractors''
for possible bombing attacks.
   The newspaper report said the suspect was allegedly helping to
set up ``imminent'' bombing attacks in Munich, 180 miles southeast
of Darmstadt, on the office of Israel's airline, El Al; the Israeli
Trade Center; and the city's Jewish community center.
   The newspaper added that ``an English-language list of Israeli
and Jewish religious establishments in the Federal Republic (West
Germany)'' were found during the raid in Darmstadt.
   The paper said the ``contractors are not in this country and
therefore not reachable by German police.'' Bavarian police declined
to say who had hired the suspect.
   Authorities in September 1988 intercepted several photos that
were to be sent to Beirut showing Israeli offices in Munich and
accompanied by an Arab-language text, officials said.
   ``After months of work in cooperation with Hesse state police,
Bavarian authorities were able to identify the suspect,'' the
statement added.
</TEXT>
