<FIRST>r a PM-DomesticPartners     07-06 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Domestic Partners,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Domestic Partner' Bill Takes Effect</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new municipal ordinance recognizing
unmarried couples _ gay or heterosexual _ appeared headed for the
November ballot after two clergymen turned in more than 27,000
signatures for repeal.
   Registrar Germaine Wong said 18,000 signatures are needed to get
the measure on the ballot. She said it will take at least five days
to verify the signatures.
   The ordinance, which was passed last month and took effect
Wednesday, permits unmarried couples to register their partnerships
at City Hall for a $35 fee.
   The ordinance grants visitation rights to partners of hospital
patients, and bereavement leave for city employees whose partners
die. A task force is considering whether the ordinance also entitles
unmarried partners of city employees to full health coverage.
   In their petition, opponents of the measure said it ``abitrarily
redefined the time-honored and hallowed nature of the family, flying
therewith in the face of some of society's most precious values.''
   The petition for a repeal vote was submitted by the Rev. Charles
McIlhenny, a pastor at the First Orthodox Presbyterian Church, and
Rabbi Lionel Feldman. The petition drive also was backed by several
Roman Catholic parishes.
   Both men refused to comment when they dropped off a box full of
signatures at the city clerk's office Wednesday.
   The action drew a sharp response from supporters of the ordinance.
   ``If the right wing wants to put something on the ballot, they
can go ahead,'' said Jean Harris, aide to city Supervisor Harry
Britt, author of the measure. ``We have 60 percent of the people in
San Francisco backing us.''
   San Francisco expects about 900 couples annually to register as
``domestic partners.''
   There was no fanfare Wednesday to mark the new law, in part
because sign-up forms and explanatory brochures were not ready.
People who showed up to enroll were turned away, but officials said
the forms should be ready today.
   The real kickoff will probably take place in August to allow gay
organizations time to round up couples to take part in a mass
signup, Harris said.
</TEXT>
