<FIRST>u a PM-GayRoommates     07-06 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gay Roommates,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Court Says Homosexual Lovers Can Be Considered Family</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BELLAFIORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocaited Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York's highest court ruled today that a
partner in a long-term homosexual relationship can take over the
couple's rent-controlled apartment when the lover who signed the
lease dies.
   In a 4-2 ruling, the Court of Appeals ordered a lower court to
reconsider its decision to evict a New York City man from a
rent-controlled apartment he shared for a decade with his now-dead
lover.
   In doing so, the court expanded the definition of a ``family'' as
it applies to New York's rent-control laws. The word is crucial
because state law says only ``family members'' may take over
rent-controlled apartments when the tenant of record dies.
   The court said that the definition should include adults who show
long-term financial and emotional commitment to each other, even if
they don't fit the traditional meaning of a ``family.''
   Today's decision is the first time any top state court in the
nation has recognized a gay couple to be the legal equivalent of a
family, according to American Civil Liberties Union lawyer William
Rubenstein, who argued the case.
   ``Today's decision is a ground-breaking victory for lesbian and
gay men,'' Rubenstein said. ``It marks the most important single
step forward in American law toward legal recognition of lesbian and
gay relationships.''
   The ruling comes amid growing fears within the gay community
about housing discrimination because of AIDS. It's especially
important in New York City, which has the greatest number of AIDS
cases in the nation and a tight housing market.
   Rubenstein said the ruling would also apply to unmarried
heterosexual partners and poor families who can't afford to
formalize their relationships.
   ``We conclude that the term family ... should not be rigidly
restricted to those people who have formalized their relationship by
obtaining, for instance, a marriage certificate or an adoption
order,'' Judge Vito Titone wrote.
   Furthermore, Titone said that state rent-control law protections
against sudden eviction ``should not rest on fictitious legal
distinctions or genetic history, but instead should find its
foundation in the reality of family life.''
</TEXT>
