<FIRST>r a PM-HeirAgreement     07-06 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heir Agreement,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youth Convicted in Adoptive Parents' Murders Collects from Estate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINERAL POINT, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man who pleaded no contest to
killing his adoptive parents and brother in 1983 collects money from
their estate for rent, living expenses and schooling because the
couple died without a will.
   An agreement recently made public shows that the man, who changed
his name from Peter Zimmer to Anton Jovan Collier, is the
beneficiary of a trust that pays for his apartment, gives him $100 a
week spending money and pays for college or vocational school.
   It requires him to attend school full time until 1992 or until he
earns a bachelor's degree, live in the apartment and not commit a
felony.
   The agreement, which Collier signed in 1987, bars him from
contacting Zimmer relatives or traveling to Wisconsin, Illinois,
Arizona or California. He forfeits the trust if he violates any
portion of the settlement.
   Collier, who was 14 when his parents and brother were slain in
1983, was sent to a juvenile institution after pleading no contest.
   Hans Zimmer, 48, was found shot to death in family's rural
Mineral Point home. His wife, Sally, 44, and son, Perry, 10, were
stabbed up to 20 times.
   Because Collier's parents had no will, the probate court
recognized him as sole heir of the $177,000 estate. He filed an
inheritance claim before being released from the detention home in
1987.
   Relatives contested his claim but later agreed to a settlement on
the condition it be kept confidential.
   But a state appeals court ruled that the settlement was public
information under Wisconsin law, and the agreement became public
last week.
   Collier's case was cited by lawmakers last year to win passage of
a law preventing juvenile killers from inheriting their victims'
estate.
   Collier's whereabouts were not disclosed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
