<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i BC-Gorbachev-Excerpts     07-06 0826</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gorbachev-Excerpts,0892</SECOND>
<HEAD>Excerpts from Gorbachev Speech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Excerpts from the speech by Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Thursday to the Council of Europe,
from an English-language translation provided to reporters:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>On European unity:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A truly unique chance is opening (for Europeans) to play a role
in building a new world, one that would be worthy of their past, of
their economic and spiritual potential.
   It also is the specific feature of the situation in Europe that
it can cope with all this, live up to the expectations of its
peoples and do its international duty at the new state of world
history, only by recognizing its wholeness and by making the right
conclusions.
   Europe experienced more than once the attempts at unification by
force. But it also experienced noble dreams of a voluntary
democratic community of European peoples.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   On Europe's different social systems:=
   The idea of European unification should be collectively thought
over once again ... I know that many people in the West perceive the
main difficulty in the existence of two social systems.
   Yet the difficulty lies elsewhere _ it lies in the rather
widespread belief, or in the political objective, that overcoming
the division of Europe means overcoming socialism.
   But this is a course for confrontation, if not something worse.
There will be no European unity along these lines. The fact that the
states of Europe belong to different social systems is a reality.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>On the changing political order:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The social and political order in some particular countries did
change in the past, and it can change in the future as well. But
this is exclusively a matter for the peoples themselves and their
choice.
   Any interference in internal affairs, any attempts to limit the
sovereignty of states _ both friends and allies or anybody else _
are inadmissible.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>On the defense of socialism:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   For all our present shortcomings and lagging behind, we know full
well the strong points of our social system which result from its
essential characteristics.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>On outmoded stereotypes:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   In the meantime, less true than in the past, it is precisely on
the basis of outmoded stereotypes that the Soviet Union continues to
be suspected of hegemonistic designs and of the intention to
decouple the United States from Europe.
   There are even some people who are willing to put the U.S.S.R.
outside of Europe.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>On the superpowers:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union and the United States are a natural part of the
European international and political structure.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>On Europe's negative aspects:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Let us not forget that the metastases of colonial slavery spread
around the world from Europe. It was here that fascism came into
being. It was here that the most destructive wars started.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>On a blueprint for a common European home:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   I do not claim to carry a finished blueprint of that home in my
pocket. What we have in mind is a restructuring of the international
order existing in Europe that would put common European values in
the forefront and make it possible to replace the traditional
balance of forces with a balance of interests.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>On force:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The philosophy of the concept of a common European home rules out
any likelihood of an armed clash and the very possibility of the use
or threat of force.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>On NATO:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   If it becomes clear that NATO countries are ready to join us in
negotiation on tactical nuclear weapons, we could, naturally in
consulting with our allies, carry out without delay further
unilateral reductions in our tactical nuclear missiles in Europe.
   The need to convene within the next 18 to 24 months a second
Helsinki-type meeting is coming to the fore with ever increasng
urgency.
   It is time for the present generation of leaders of the European
countries, U.S.A. and Canada to discuss, in addition to the most
immediate issues, how they contemplate future stages of progress
toward a European community of the 21st century.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>On East-West cooperation:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The following projects, for example, are equally urgent both for
the East and West of Europe:
   _ A trans-European high-speed railway.
   _ A common European program on new solar-energy technologies and
equipment.
   _ Processing and storing nuclear waste and enhancing the safety
of nuclear power stations.
   _ Additional fiber optics channels for transmitting information.
   _ An all-European satellite TV system.
   _ An international thermonuclear experimental reactor.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>On the European Economic Community:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   We are far from underestimating the emergence in the next few
years of a single European market ... coming up is a trade and
economic agreement between our country and the EC. We attach
substantial significance to this act.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>On the environment:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The common European home will have to be environmentally clean
... major ecological problems have long ago transcended national
confines. Setting up a regional ecological security system is
therefore an urgent task ... elaborating a long-term continental
ecological program could be a first step.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
