<FIRST>r i AM-SpoletoFestival     07-06 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spoleto Festival,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Premiere of Garcia Marquez Book on Spoleto Stage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPOLETO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian critics Thursday gave glowing
reviews to the world premiere of a stage version of Gabriel Garcia
Marquez's ``No One Writes to the Colonel.''
   The play was written and directed by an Argentine and interpreted
by a Venezuelan theater company.
   The debut Tuesday night was sold out despite torrential rains in
Spoleto, an Umbrian town north of Rome. ``Colonel'' is the only
foreign-language prose work in the 32nd annual Festival of Two
Worlds.
   A version of the festival is also held each year in Charleston,
S.C., and Melbourne, Australia.
   Argentine Carlos Gimenez and several collaborators wrote the
screenplay for ``Colonel'' in 1971. According to Italian newspapers,
the text was approved by Garcia Marquez. The cast is from the
Rajatabla Theater Company of Caracas.
   ``Gimenez's adaptation faithfully reflects the double nature,
realistic and symbolic, of Garcia Marquez's narrative,'' wrote Renzo
Tian of the Rome daily Il Messaggero.
   ``From this contrast expressed with intense simplicity, the play
acquires a vivid dramatic force ... this is animated by a group of
vigorous interpreters headed by Jose Tejera, who plays the taciturn
colonel, Aura Rivas, his bitter wife, and supporting roles by Daniel
Lopez, Annibal Grun, Mimi Sills and Erich Wildpret.''
   The 1961 novel by the Nobel Prize-winning Colombian writer tells
of a forgotten civil war hero in the imaginary Latin American town
of Macondo. The colonel waits in poverty and solitude for a pension
that will never come. His last possession of value is a prize
fighting cock, which he refuses to sell.
   The Spoleto festival runs through July 16 and includes operas,
dance, theater, music, art exhibits and films.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
