<FIRST>u a PM-FiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0500 07-06 0848</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0500,0866</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Knocks Out Power in Utah; Disrupts Air Traffic</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with two fires Utah, California contained
this morning; containment predicted for largest Gila forest fire; minor
revisions in some other fire acreage; CORRECTS number of new firefighters
at Bridger-Teton this morning to 200 sted 100. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM BUERKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A wildfire spread to a utility transmission line, blacking out a
sweltering Utah town, and a wind-whipped forest fire sent smoke
billowing 10,000 feet over the Utah-Colorado line, restricting air
travel.
   Major fires burned out of control in six states today.
   In New Mexico, the state's biggest blaze covered 6,500 acres and
40 fresh lightning fires popped up, including a 400-acre blaze that
threatened ranch buildings near the Arizona line.
   Dying winds and cool night weather helped firefighters battle
several brush fires burning on more than 4,000 acres in Southern
California.
   The blackout in Utah began Wednesday afternoon when a Utah Power
&amp; Light Co. maintenance truck caught fire. Flames spread to 70 acres
of grass and small trees, toppled four wooden transmission towers
and knocked out a 230,000-volt line.
   Electricity was restored to many communities within hours, but
the 20,000 residents of St. George, the state's hot spot Wednesday
with a high of 108 degrees, remained without power this morning.
   ``A lot of people have gone out of town, to Mesquite, Nevada, or
places where they have power, or to places in the mountains where
it's cooler,'' said Barbara Mathews of the Washington County
sheriff's office.
   Officials this morning said that the fire was contained and they
hoped to have it under control this afternoon.
   Four other fires raged out of control on more than 11,000 acres
in eastern Utah, where temperatures were around 100 degrees and
humidity levels below 5 percent.
   A 7,000-acre blaze roared past fire lines in the Flume Canyon
Wilderness Study Area 20 miles west of the Colorado line. It belched
so much smoke that the Federal Aviation Administration closed an air
route.
   The fire also burned over a natural gas pipeline and ignited gas
seeping from a small leak, but the operator managed to cut off the
flow in time to prevent any serious damage, said Dan Lewis, a
spokesman for Northwest Pipeline Co.
   Some 275 firefighters battled the fire with two tanker planes and
two helicopters, said Mary Plumb of the Bureau of Land Management.
Containment was expected this weekend, she said.
   A fire on more than 2,600 acres in Uinta Canyon moved to the
northeast despite aerial attacks by seven tankers and three
helicopters and ground assaults by 400 firefighters, said BLM
spokesman Ray Tate. ``It should burn for several days despite our
best efforts,'' he said.
   A third blaze 23 miles west of Duchesne, which was nearly
extinguished on Tuesday, roared out of control on more than 850
acres because of wind. A fourth fire in Indian Canyon between
Duchesne and Price covered 900 acres.
   In western Colorado, a grass fire scorched 900 acres and
destroyed a home before being declared 75 percent contained this
morning. Crews also nearly contained a stubborn fire that burned
2,100 acres near Dinosaur National Monument.
   In Southern California, 340 firefighters struggled against an
800-acre fire southeast of San Diego that cut off telephone service
to two small communities and threatened homes. Four firefighters
suffered minor injuries.
   ``What's giving us the most difficulty is that they can only
reach the fire with hand crews because the terrain is very steep,''
said California Department of Forestry spokeswoman Dolores Fremter.
   Three other blazes blackened more than 3,000 acres in Riverside
County. The largest burned 1,300 acres of brush near Lake Elsinore
before being contained this morning.
   A person loading abandoned cars onto a flatbed truck caused a
spark that started the fire, said Tim Spann of the Forestry
Department. ``That's how dry it is out here,'' he said.
   In New Mexico, about 1,000 firefighters and support workers
battled a fire that grew an additional 500 acres to 6,500 acres
Wednesday in Gila National Forest, said Forest Service spokesman
Mary Zabinski. Rain kept the fire from growing further this morning,
and containment was expected by Friday.
   But the storm also brought lightning that caused 25 new fires in
the Gila forest and 15 elsewhere in New Mexico. One fire spread over
400 acres and threatened ranch buildings on federal-owned Owl Canyon
near the Arizona line.
   More than 100 firefighters battled a lightning fire in Georgia
that has burned at least 750 acres of the Okefenokee Swamp. John
Hart, a Forest Service spokesman, said below-normal rainfall and
water levels hampered efforts to fight the blaze, which apparently
broke out late last week.
   More than 200 fresh firefighters were joining the battle today
against a 2,200-acre blaze in Wyoming's Bridger-Teton National
Forest. Offficials said they were having trouble finding
firefighters.
   ``The availability of crews seems to be somewhat depleted, with
the number of fires in Colorado and so forth,'' said Ed Christian, a
spokesman for the forest. The fire started July Fourth, apparently
from fireworks.
</TEXT>
