<FIRST>u w PM-NuclearProbe     07-06 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Probe,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Inspectors, FBI Probe NY Nuclear Site For Waste Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents and a team of Energy Department
specialists experts today entered a federal nuclear fuel facility in
upstate New York to investigate possible violations of environmental
and safety rules, the department said.
   Dennis C. Vacco, the U.S. attorney for the Western District of
New York, said the FBI agents on the site, about 50 miles south of
Buffalo, were looking for evidence of possible criminal violations
of federal laws governing hazardous waste storage.
   Deputy Energy Secretary Henson Moore said the investigation was
the first of 17 such probes by Energy Department specialists over
the next year at federal nuclear facilities. The Energy Department
took over operation of the New York state-owned plant in 1980.
   Last month, FBI agents raided an Energy Department nuclear
weapons plants in Colorado in search of criminal violations of waste
storage laws. DOE employees were not allowed to participate in that
raid, and Moore said last week that the resulting bad publicity had
triggered a new effort to cooperate in such probes.
   Moore said ``there is currently no evidence'' of waste-handling
violations at the New York facility, known as the West Valley
Demonstration Project.
   Christina Sankey, a department spokeswoman, said the plant has
been operated since 1966 and currently is being decommissioned and
decontaminated. The facility, which reprocessed nuclear fuel for
power plants during the 1970s, contains an unspecified amount of
low-level, high-level and other categories of radioactive waste.
   Ms. Sankey said the investigation could last several weeks. She
said the Environmental Protection Agency also was participating in
the investigation.
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins announced late last month that
he had created ``tiger teams'' of department specialists to assess
environmental compliance at all department nuclear facilities,
including the nuclear weapons plants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
