<FIRST>r a PM-PrisonDads     07-06 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prison Dads,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Court Strips Prison Dads of Parental Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York's highest court ruled unanimously
today that prisoners serving long sentences can be stripped of their
parental rights if they fail to find a relative to care for their
children.
   ``Put simply, relegating a child to foster care until he or she
is no longer a child is not a viable plan ... and, more importantly,
it deprives the child of that quality of `permanency' found by the
Legislature to be so essential to proper growth and development,''
wrote Judge Fritz Alexander of the Court of Appeals.
   The 7-0 ruling means that Willie Bethea, serving two 25
years-to-life murder sentences, cannot block the adoption of his
13-year-old son and 9-year-old daughter. The ruling also affects
another inmate, identified in court papers only as Gregory F., and
his sons, ages 9 and 8. Gregory F. is serving 10-to-20 years for
armed robbery.
   In both cases, foster parents sought to adopt the children.
   ``I don't believe I lost,'' said Ruth Cassell, Bethea's lawyer.
``You're screwed if you're an inmate.''
   She said she had not yet read the decision or decided whether to
appeal.
   In 1983, the Legislature gave inmates a say in whether their
children could be adopted. Before that, they had no parental rights.
However, inmates were expected to maintain contact with their
children and plan for their futures.
   While the Court of Appeals noted that the Bethea and Gregory F.
had regularly visited with their children, it also said they had
been unable to find family members to care for the youngsters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
