<FIRST>u a PM-CrimeVictims     07-06 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crime Victims,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repeal of Crime Victims Law Approved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Texas Senate today voted without debate
to repeal a three-week-old law that lets police withhold crime
victims' names from the press and public. The 24-0 vote sent the
bill to the House.
   The law, which took effect June 14, created a storm of protest in
the news media.
   Republican John Leedom, the Senate sponsor of the law, also
sponsored the repeal. He said the law had been ``misapplied to such
an extent that many law enforcement officers are not furnishing
(information) _ that was not the intent.''
   The law amended the Texas Open Records Act to allow authorities
to withhold information that might identify victims of felonies such
as aggravated assault, robbery and murder.
   Supporters had said it would protect victims from being pestered
by alarm salesmen and security companies.
   As the uproar grew against the law, Gov. Bill Clements added
repeal to the agenda of the special legislative session.
   George Irish, publisher of the San Antonio Light and a
representative of a First Amendment and freedom-of-information
coalition of seven Texas news organizations, argued for repeal in
testimony submitted in writing.
   He said the law creates a ``potentially dangerous situation for
citizens far more devastating than the temporary harassment by
unscrupulous sales personnel.''
   ``Perhaps the most disturbing result of the law has been the
blackout of information disclosing the identity of the victim in a
child kidnapping case,'' Irish said. ``It is exactly the fact that
information is dispersed about a kidnapping which often leads to
solving the case.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
