<DOCNO> AP890706-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Bomb     07-06 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Bomb,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Abnormality Found in Seas Where Hydrogen Bomb Lost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No abnormalities have been found in samples of fish
and seaweed taken from the area where a hydrogen bomb fell off a
U.S. aircraft carrier 24 years ago, the Science and Technology
Agency said Thursday.
   The findings were contained in a preliminary report. Agency
official Kimihiko Oda said the agency still was analyzing water
samples taken from the deep sea, and a final report would be
available by the end of July.
   He said samples were taken in the fishing grounds nearest to the
area where an A-4 Skyhawk plane carrying a one-megaton H-bomb
accidentally rolled off the carrier Ticonderoga on Dec. 5, 1965. The
bomb fell into the sea about 80 miles from a small island off
Okinawa, in southern Japan.
   Japan did not become aware of the accident until May, when it
began its tests.
   The agency also analyzed data from annual surveys taken in many
places in Japan and offshore for the past 21 years to check on
radioactive fallout from nuclear tests by China, the Soviet Union,
the United States and France, Oda said, and no abnormalities were
found.
   Still to be analyzed are water samples collected from a depth of
14,850 feet by a vessel of the Maritime Safety Agency, Japan's coast
guard.
   Oda said no samples were taken from the 15,840-foot-deep seabed
where the bomb sank because the survey's aim was to find whether the
accident affected Japan's people and the marine environment.
   Last month, William Arkin of the Washington-based Institute for
Policy Studies, which released declassified U.S. Navy documents on
the accident, said there was little danger the bomb would detonate,
although the 33 pounds of plutonium it contained could threaten the
environment as it deteriorates.
</TEXT>
