<FIRST>u w PM-MedalofFreedom     07-06 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medal of Freedom,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Honors Five With Top Civilian Award</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today awarded the nation's
highest civilian award, the Presidential Medal of Freedom, to Gen.
James H. Doolittle, public servants C. Douglas Dillon and George
Kennan, former Sen. Margaret Chase Smith and comedian Lucille Ball.
   Miss Ball's award was accepted posthumously by her husband, Gary
Morton.
   Bush praised the five as American heroes.
   ``You have left an indelible mark as you have enriched this
nation, and America is grateful,'' he said.
   Doolittle, 92, the aviation pioneer and retired Air Force general
who made history by leading the first U.S. air strike on Japan
following the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor, was described by the
president as ``the master of the calculated risk'' and a
``trailblazer in modern aviation.'' In the 1960s he was an executive
in the private aerospace industry.
   Bush said Kennan, 85, was ``truly a visionary'' on U.S.-Soviet
relations. In addition to writing extensively on that subject, he
served in the State Department as head of the policy planning staff
and as counsel, and later was ambassador to the Soviet Union from
1952 to 1953 and ambassador to Yugoslavia in the early 1960s.
   Mrs. Smith, 91, the former Republican senator and congresswoman
from Maine, gained fame for her speech denouncing the tactics of
1950s anti-communism crusader Sen. Joseph McCarthy of Wisconsin. She
served in Congress under six presidents, beginning with Franklin
Roosevelt in 1940.
   Dillon, 79, former ambassador to France and undersecretary of
state in the 1950s and Treasury secretary from 1961 to 1965, was
praised by Bush for his contributions to Latin America and Western
Europe policy as well as tax policy.
   Bush called Miss Ball, 77, ``the first lady of television'' and
said, ``She was like everyone's next door neighbor, only funnier.''
She died April 26 after a lifetime in entertainment, remembered
mostly for one of television's all-time most popular shows, ``I Love
Lucy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
