<DOCNO> AP890706-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-AIDS-World     07-06 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-World,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Cases Up 10,000 Worldwide; Kenya Total Soars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of cases of AIDS reported to the World
Health Organization totaled 167,373 by July 1, marking an increase
by more than 10,000 from the previous month, according to WHO
statistics released Thursday.
   The WHO estimates the actual number is more than twice as high
and at least 1 million new cases are expected worldwide by 1993.
   Updates from Kenya, more than doubling the previous figure, and
from the United States made up most of the newly reported cases
registered by the WHO as of July 1.
   So far, 149 countries or territories have reported at least one
case. Twenty-eight countries, mainly in Asia, advised the WHO they
had no cases.
   Kenya reported 5,949 cases by March 31, or 3,217 more than the
previous total dated June 30, 1988, while the United States listed
95,561 cases, an increase by 2,842 between May 9 and May 31.
   Updates from Burkina Faso, Burundi, and Zambia also contributed
to the overall rise in reported AIDS cases in Africa by more than
5,000 to 29,906.
   Among the world's more populous countries, Uganda has the highest
AIDS rate with 26.3 cases per 100,000 inhabitants. It has the
second-highest total with 6,772 cases listed in January.
   Brazil, with 6,421 cases, has a rate of 1.9; France has a rate of
4.2 and the fourth-highest total worldwide, 6,409. European updates
during June included Italy, from 3,494 to 3,773 and West Germany,
from 3,086 to 3,324.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
