<DOCNO> AP890706-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Baker     07-06 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worry About Cambodia Grows as Vietnamese Withdrawal Nears</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and
pro-Western nations of Southeast Asia pressed hard for Vietnamese
withdrawal from Cambodia, but as it nears, their nervousness about
what happens next is almost palpable.
   Vietnam says all its military forces will be out of Cambodia by
the end of September, after nearly 11 years. What will replace
Vietnamese occupation has dominated discussions here this week among
Secretary of State James A. Baker III and foreign ministers from the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
   The best result would be a negotiated settlement between the
three resistance factions and the Hanoi-sponsored government, laying
the groundwork for peace in Cambodia for the first time in a
generation.
   The worst would be a power vacuum, with each contending party
trying to fill it through the use of force, because the strongest
resistance army is the brutal Khmer Rouge.
   Hundreds of thousands of people were executed or died of
starvation while the Khmer Rouge ruled Cambodia from the end of the
Indochina war in April 1975 to the Vietnamese invasion of December
1978. Some estimates say more than 1 million perished.
   France, once the colonial power in Indochina, has taken the
diplomatic initiative as the Vietnamese withdrawal approaches,
inviting the Cambodian factions to peace talks in Paris in two weeks.
   It plans to follow the talks immediately with an international
conference involving the ASEAN members Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia,
the Philippines, Singapore and Thailand.
   Also attending would be the United States, Soviet Union, Britain,
China and France, the five permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council.
   The Cambodian issue was the glue that kept the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations together over the past decade, and some
delegates to the meeting in Brunei wondered whether it could
continue after a settlement.
   American officials seem undecided about whether the French acted
precipitately. Renewed civil war could result if the initiative
fails, but the French view that decisive action is required also
could be a catalyst for peace negotiations.
   To Baker, the requirements for a durable settlement are clear.
   He said in a speech Thursday it should include a cease-fire;
cessation of foreign military aid to all factions; an interim
coalition government led by Prince Norodom Sihanouk, the former
Cambodian head of state, and an international force to monitor free
elections.
   All the delegates are aware, however, that the problem in
Cambodia goes beyond ordinary factionalism.
   They are aware that history may not judge them kindly if the
result of their long diplomatic effort is the return of the Khmer
Rouge to power. China also could be expected to share in the
criticism because of its role in arming the Khmer Rouge.
   Baker spoke for delegates when he said Thursday that the goal of
transforming Cambodia from ``a battlefield to a marketplace''
requires ``our resolve and our unity of purpose, now more than
ever.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Gedda is based in Washington and has
covered foreign affairs for The Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
