<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--UrbanDolphin     07-06 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Urban Dolphin,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dolphin Swims North Up Hudson River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wayward dolphin has left the East River and
steadily moved north up the Hudson River instead of heading back to
the ocean, indicating it may be sick, researchers said.
   The bottle-nosed dolphin was last spotted near West Point on the
Hudson, at least 40 miles north of Wards Island in the East River,
where it lingered for more than a week, the Okeanos Ocean Research
Foundation said Wednesday. The animal was first spotted June 20 in
the East River.
   Marine biologists had planned to try herding the dolphin from the
East River to open waters by playing recorded sounds of killer
whales underwater. But those plans were canceled Saturday when the
dolphin moved north.
   ``Such aberrant movement up the East River and Hudson River may
indicate that the animal was sick prior to entering the East River,
and its condition is not improving,'' Okeanos said in a news release.
   Okeanos said the animal may not survive in the Hudson River, so
it is considering capturing it with nets or a hoop capture line.
Capture is a last resort since the stress could kill the dolphin.
</TEXT>
