<FIRST>r i AM-Europe-Governors     07-06 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europe-Governors,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Governors Discuss Trade Program With Common Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. governors met Thursday with
officials of the European Community to learn how their states can
gain from the trading bloc's plans to create a single market in late
1992.
   ``We're out to find markets for goods and products that are
produced in our respective states,'' said Virginia Gov. Gerald
Baliles, chairman of the National Governors' Association.
   ``At the same time, we're interested in presenting our states as
places to do business for other companies,'' he told a news
conference at the European Community headquarters in Brussels.
   Baliles and the governors of Iowa, Washington, New Jersey, Utah,
Vermont, Kentucky and Puerto Rico held discussions at the European
Commission, the executive body of the 12-nation Common Market.
   The governors met with officials at the 16-nation North Atlantic
Treaty Organization and the U.S. Mission to the Common Market. They
were scheduled to meet Friday with members of the European
Parliament, the trading bloc's legislative body.
   Frans Andriessen, foreign affairs chief for the European
Commission, the community's executive body, said the governors
talked mostly about the plans to eliminate by late 1992 the many
trade barriers separating the dozen EC nations. The idea is to form
a European-wide market in which people, goods, services and money
can move freely.
   Andriessen said the officials discussed the opportunities the
single market ``will create for people inside and outside the
European Community and the irreversibility of the process and the
implications it will have for external relations.''
   Baliles said the governors want to hold further discussions with
EC officials.
   American states, he said, ``are vulnerable to foreign competition
_ that was once very remote ... We have lost our economic
insularity. We are affected by events, places and people beyond our
borders.''
   Vermont Gov. Madeleine Kunin said, ``A large percentage of the
jobs in our respective states ... are very heavily dependent on
decisions now being made and will continue to be made by the
European Community.''
   Iowa Gov. Terry Branstad noted the United States and the Common
Market are at odds over a number of agricultural issues, including
the trading bloc's costly farm subsidy program.
   He described the community's ban on meat from U.S. cattle treated
with growth hormones as ``an improper and unfair barrier to free
trade'' in beef.
   Andriessen responded that the community's restrictions were
non-discriminatory, applying to not only foreign meat exporters but
also European farmers.
   ``It is unacceptable that one country takes unilaterally
retaliation measures which in our view are not compatible with
international rules,'' he said.
   On Jan. 1, the Common Market imposed a ban on hormone-treated
beef. The United States refused to comply and instead slapped stiff
duties on a variety of European products.
   In May, both sides agreed to allow U.S. ranchers who want to
export untreated beef to do so. They will have to submit to a
certification process drawn up by European officials. In return, the
United States agreed to reduce its retaliatory tariffs.
   Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton arrived with the delegation but had to
return home for state business, officials said.
</TEXT>
