<FIRST>r a AM-PieFight     07-06 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pie Fight,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cafe Owner Sues, Seeking Secret Pie Recipes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's a pie fight at the Club Cafe.
Smack-dab in the middle of the gooey mess is the recipe for peanut
butter-cream pie and 13 other flavors.
   Long famous for its pastries, Club Cafe changed hands in the
spring. Chief pastry baker Mary Hampton Allen soon walked out,
citing differences with the new owner.
   She took with her the secret recipes for the famous pies.
   The new owner, Robert McNanna, hired another baker, but he says
the pies just aren't the same.
   So he's suing. The lawsuit in Hot Springs Chancery Court seeks to
force Ms. Allen to divulge the ingredients and the methods she used.
The lawsuit says the cafe ``could not continue without the ability
... to make and produce the various types and kinds of pies for
which it had become famous.''
   A court hearing is scheduled July 25.
   ``It's all in her head, she never wrote anything down,'' says Ms.
Allen's attorney, Steven D. Oliver. ``It's something she just
developed over the years. A pinch of this, a pinch of that.''
   McNanna contends that Ms. Allen promised to share her cooking
secrets.
   ``The recipes were my main concern. She said that she would teach
somebody how to bake them before she left. You never know what might
happen. She could get in a car wreck or something.''
   Pies have been big business for Club Cafe _ the restaurant sells
about 300 per week, by the slice. During Thanksgiving and Christmas,
sales quadruple.
   Club Cafe pies were first baked by Ms. Allen's relatives. She is
34 and virtually grew up at the cafe. The family operated the cafe
until forced to sell the majority of the stock to McNanna, according
to Oliver.
   Ms. Allen has filed a lawsuit of her own, attempting to regain
control of the cafe because she says McNanna is behind on mortgage
payments.
</TEXT>
