<FIRST>u w PM-US-Israel     07-06 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Israel,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Criticizes Terms Set by Shamir for Palestinian Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department today criticized the tough
terms set by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and his Likud
coalition for an election among Palestinian Arabs, but said it still
supports the plan.
   ``Partisan declarations, particularly if they appear to be more
restrictive or impose conditions, do not advance the process,''
spokesman Richard Boucher said of the steps taken by the Israeli
leader Wednesday in Tel Aviv under pressure from more hard-line
members of the political party.
   But the U.S. official stressed that the plan for elections among
Palestinian Arabs on the West Bank and in Gaza has the endorsement
of the Israeli Cabinet and the Bush administration and still
provides ``the most realistic way to advance the peace process.''
   Boucher called on Palestinians to accept the proposal and to open
talks with Israel `'to flesh out the details of the initiative and
to make elections and negotiaqtions work.''
   The election would choose Palestinian leaders to negotiate
temporary, local self-rule with Israel. After five years, Israel,
Palestinians, Egypt and Jordan would hammer out an overall
settlement.
   The conditions set Wednesday by Shamir did not represent any
change in the Israeli leader's position. And the Bush administration
is in accord with one of th major terms _ no Palestinian state to be
established on Israeli-held territory.
   Still, approval of the terms appeared to bind them more tightly
to any negotiations that might be held. They included a statement
that Israel would not give up territory and that Jews could keep
settling on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Ahmed Abdul-Rahman, spokesman for the Palestine Liberation
Organization, said in Tunis that the conditions approved by Shamir
and the Likud closed the door to peace.
   The PLO official said the nearly 19-month-old uprising by
Palestinians against Israeli control would be ``escalated because
this is the only answer to intransigence.''
   But the State Department, through spokesman Boucher, said it was
basing its policies on the plan approved in May by the Israeli
Cabinet and not by ``domestic Israeli politics.''
   The statement suggested a U.S. view that Shamir had compromised
with hard-liners in his party without really changing the proposal
itself.
