<FIRST>r a AM-MalpracticeAppeal     07-06 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malpractice Appeal,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court: New Malpractice Trial After Doctor Saves Juror in Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH EDWARDSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge should have declared a mistrial when
a doctor accused of malpractice apparently saved the life of a juror
in front of the rest of the jury, an appeals court ruled Thursday.
   The jury may have been ``subliminally influenced'' by Dr. Ho Woon
Lee's performance when he administered aid to the stricken juror,
even though they found Lee liable for damages in a malpractice
lawsuit, the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court ruled
unanimously. Supreme Court is New York state's trial-level court.
   Former patient Brayno Reome sued Lee because a drain had been
left in his leg after amputation surgery.
   During a recess in the Cortland County trial, a juror suffered
what appeared to be a heart attack or stroke. Lee ``administered aid
including a blow to the chest,'' according to the court.
   The other jurors were removed before an ambulance arrived.
   When the jurors returned, the judge told them the trial would
continue with an alternate juror. The next morning, the judge said
that the ill juror had not been admitted to the hospital and that he
was apparently fine.
   ``The likely conclusion to be drawn by the jurors was that Lee
had competently administered emergency medical care, possibly saving
their fellow juror's life,'' the court said in a decision by Justice
Paul Yesawich.
   The jury awarded Reome $3,500 for medical expenses and $10,000
for pain and suffering. Reome, a retired house painter, had
complained of pain for the nine months he remained Lee's patient in
1983 and 1984 before the drain was discovered and removed by another
doctor.
   The appeals court said the ``unconscionably low award suggests
that the jury was subliminally influenced to view Lee favorably at
(Reome's) expense.''
   A judge's instructions couldn't remove the ``favorable bias that
Lee's admirably humanitarian efforts created,'' the court said as it
sent the case back to Supreme Court for a new trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
