<FIRST>r a AM-SmokingBan     07-06 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smoking Ban,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sweeping Ban on Smoking Becomes Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BELLAFIORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo has signed a law that gives
the nation's second-largest state one of the most sweeping sets of
restrictions on smoking in public places and at work.
   The law will prohibit smoking in auditoriums, elevators,
gymnasiums, food stores, shared taxicabs and limousines. Smoking
will be restricted to certain areas in restaurants, bowling alleys,
bingo halls, hospitals, theaters, indoor arenas, banks, waiting
areas and restrooms.
   ``The Clean Indoor Air Act will, we hope, save lives,'' said
Cuomo at a bill-signing ceremony Wednesday.
   In the workplace, smoking will be prohibited in a work area at an
employee's request. Non-smoking areas will have to be provided in
employee cafeterias, lunch rooms and lounges to meet employee
demand, up to 70 percent although more would be possible.
   Smoking in theater viewing areas, libraries, museums and mass
transit has long been prohibited in New York.
   The smoking law wouldn't apply in bars, hotel rooms, conventions,
private residences, private limousines, private automobiles, private
parties, tobacco stores and private boxes at indoor arenas, such as
luxury boxes at sports stadiums. Violators will be subject to fines
of up to $1,000.
   Businesses could also get an exemption if they could prove the
smoking ban would create a financial hardship.
   The law takes effect in early January except for the workplace
provisions, which take effect in early April.
   Some 41 other states have some sort of smoking restrictions, but
only Minnesota has a statewide law that's tougher than New York's,
according to the Washington D.C.-based Tobacco Free America Project.
California, the nation's largest state, has a patchwork of statewide
laws that are collectively weaker than New York's new statute, the
group said.
   Only Illinois, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Alabama,
Louisiana, Wyoming and Missouri have no form of statewide smoking
restrictions. Officials at the Tobacco Free America Project said
they believed the New York law would help them win over the rest of
the nation.
   The drive to restrict smoking has come amid scientific findings
that non-smokers could still contract lung and heart disease from
breathing other people's smoke.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
