<FIRST>u w PM-Iran-Contra     07-06 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>PR Executive Sentenced for Misusing Foundation to Aid Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A public relations executive who raised private
money to arm the Nicaraguan Contras was sentenced to two years'
probation today for illegally using a tax-exempt foundation for the
fund-raising effort.
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Harris sentenced Richard Miller on
his guilty plea to conspiring to defraud the government by using the
foundation to finance the covert arms-supply operation when direct
U.S. military aid to the anti-leftist rebels was banned by Congress.
   Harris also directed Miller to perform 120 hours of community
service. He could have received up to five years in prison and a
$250,000 fine.
   Miller and Carl ``Spitz'' Channell, who is scheduled to be
sentenced Friday by Harris, each entered guilty pleas to the
conspiracy charge nearly two years ago and cooperated with
independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh's investigation of the
Iran-Contra affair.
   They were the first defendants convicted as a result of Walsh's
investigation.
   In pre-sentencing remarks, Miller told the judge, ``I let my
guard down. It may have been blind patriotism, but that's no
excuse.'' Caught up in a cause he believed in, he said, ``I turned a
blind eye to the excesses of others and I crossed the line myself.''
   The guilty pleas by Miller and Channell were the basis of a
charge that former White House aide Oliver L. North conspired with
them to illegally use the National Endowment for the Preservation of
Liberty to raise donations for a non-tax-exempt purpose.
   The foundation, headed by Channell, used White House briefings
and meetings with then-President Reagan to help raise $10 million
from donors who included Texas billionaire Nelson Bunker Hunt.
   North was cleared of the tax conspiracy charge by a jury that
convicted him May 4 of trying to cover up the Iran-Contra affair and
illegally accepting a home security system.
   North was fined $150,000 on Wednesday by U.S. District Judge
Gerhard A. Gesell and ordered to perform 1,200 hours of community
service.
   Miller testified that North let him take 10 percent of the
private donations as his cut for raising money. Miller said North
gave him lists of weapons the Contras needed to use during his
meetings with potential donors.
</TEXT>
