<FIRST>r w AM-Fascell-Venezuela     07-06 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fascell-Venezuela,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Urges Restraint in Venezuelan Currency Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Foreign Affairs
Committee says Venezuela's investigation of a foreign exchange
scandal is causing some American corporations to re-examine their
investments in the country and to withdraw top executives.
   Chairman Dante Fascell, D-Fla., in a letter to Venezuela's
ambassador here, said: ``At a time when economic growth is a
priority, it would be a shame to see foreign corporations
discouraged from investing in Venezuela or decide to curtail their
operations.''
   ``I do not wish to interfere in any way in domestic affairs or in
the judicial system in Venezuela; nor can I comment on the merits of
the case,'' Fascell said in his June 13 letter to Ambassador Simon
Consalvi.
   ``As a friend of Venezuela, however, I do wish to bring to your
attention the problems this case is causing for foreign business,''
he said. ``Some American corporations have removed their top
executives and are re-examining their investments in your country.''
   Fascell said that he has been told by executives of major
American corporations that a Venezuelan judge has issued arrest
warrants for several people, including American executives, ``on
charges of fraud in obtaining preferential foreign exchange.''
   ``I understand the charges involved do not permit those accused
to be granted bail,'' Fascell said. ``The executives involved claim
they and their corporations are innocent.''
   Replying, Ambassador Consalvi said his government ``does not
welcome any discouragement to the presence of foreign businesses and
investment,'' and in fact welcomes them.
   But he said the government, operating under a system of
separation of powers, respects ``the independence of the judicial
system.''
   He also noted that Venezuela acted in March to abolish the
multiple exchange rate system.
   Investigators in Venezuela have been examining allegations that
billions of dollars in illegal profits were skimmed from a now
disbanded office set up to distribute U.S. dollars at favorable
exchange rates for essential imports.
   The investigators have been quoted in published reports as saying
that some $2.4 billion of the $30 billion involved may have been
touched by fraud.
</TEXT>
