<FIRST>r a AM-GeterGroup     07-06 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Geter Group,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Geter Helps Form Group To Fight Unjust Convictions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former engineer who spent 16 months in prison for
a crime he didn't commit has helped start a foundation to clear
people who are wrongly convicted of crimes.
   Lenell Geter, cleared of armed robbery charges by the Dallas
County district attorney's office in 1984, said the national
non-profit group Justice Denied Research Inc. will start
investigating cases later this month.
   A former E-Systems engineer, Geter told The Dallas Morning News
on Tuesday that his wife and their two daughters moved to Columbia,
S.C., last August because ``my ordeal changed things.''
   ``I could never overcome the fears I had,'' Geter, 31, said.
``There were always strange things that were happening. For the most
part, people greeted me real well.
   ``But those who showed no remorse to what happened to me became a
threat to me and my family.''
   Geter, now a social worker in South Carolina, declined to be more
specific. He will become chairman of the advisory board for the new
foundation.
   James Humphreys Jr., a Dallas private investigator given much of
the credit for Geter's release from prison, will examine many of the
cases, foundation officials said.
   The 1983 conviction of Jerry Wanzer for aggravated sexual assault
on an 8-year-old girl will be Humphreys' first case.
   A civil rights group described Wanzer's conviction and 25-year
prison sentence in 1986 as an example of ``gross racial injustice.''
But the U.S. Supreme Court refused to hear Wanzer's appeal in April
1987.
   ``The one thing I hope the foundation would do would be to
exonerate a person or persons who are incarcerated unjustly,'' Geter
told the newspaper.
   Geter said the foundation will seek cases in which substantial
evidence can be obtained to prove applicants' innocence, with
emphasis on defendants who could not afford thorough investigations
and whose court-appointed attorneys mounted an inadequate defense.
   ``Oftentimes, when an indigent person enters the judicial system,
he goes in with the minimum investigation and is later convicted,''
Geter said.
</TEXT>
