<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1502EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-BlackCatholics Bjt   07-06 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Catholics, Bjt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC Priest Says Black Americans Need Church Within Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Catholic priest who was suspended for
establishing a temple in defiance of church authorities said
Thursday he wants to establish a separate rite for black Americans
but is content to let someone else lead it.
   ``We don't want one Imani Temple,'' the Rev. George A. Stallings
said Thursday, three days after Cardinal James A. Hickey suspended
him for holding the renegade church service at Howard University Law
School. ``We want several hundred of them, several thousand.''
   But despite his determination to fly in the face of his church
authorities and his sudden national celebrity, Stallings says he
views himself a parish priest at heart.
   ``The only role that I see for myself is pastor of a local parish
community that is under the heading of an African-American Catholic
rite,'' said Stallings, who is black.
   Stallings, 41, says a new rite is needed with a black leadership
and clergy because the Roman Catholic Church is hopelessly mired in
its own white, European perspective. It's a charge that church
officials deny.
   Most other rites are ethnic churches within the Eastern Rite,
such as Maronite and Ukrainian churches. They have considerable
autonomy in ritual and discipline, but still accept the pope.
   Stallings also says that the church has ``has put its emphasis on
maintenance rather than mission,'' missing the opportunity to fill
many of the inner-city churches that were once filled with white
ethnics who have fled to the suburbs.
   ``I have been to cities where the church was closed,'' said
Stallings. ``Black protestants came in and took over, and now
they're packed to the gills.''
   Stallings proved Sunday he could pack a church, although critics
say he many of those were curiosity seekers and the crowds will
dwindle at Imani, Swahili for ``faith.''
   The service combined the traditional Catholic Mass with African
ritual and the foot-stomping, hand-clapping style of the traditional
black protestant church.
   Stallings' public act of defiance means he is now banned from
performing sacraments. According to a spokesman for Hickey,
Stallings's decision to ignore the cardinal's authority is hindering
his own stated effort to establish a new rite. Under church rules, a
request for a new rite would first go to Hickey.
   ``The difficulty is not that he tried those channels and is
blocked,'' said Rev. William Lori, Hickey's secretary. ``The
difficulty is that he has spurned those channels.''
   But Stallings says the church hierarchy, despite a number of
black bishops, is institutionally blind.
   ``It is difficult if not almost impossible for one ethnic or
cultural group to define or to decide what is good for another
ethnic group,'' he says. ``It is always necessary for those ethnic
groups to get a seal of approval from the white male power group.''
   At stake in the Stallings battle are 2 million black American
Catholics, a minority of both black people _ some 30 million in
America _ and American Catholics as a whole _ 54 million.
   According to church figures, there are 300 black priests and 13
black bishops. Of the 17,000 Catholic parishes, 1,200 are
predominantly black.
   Church officials say they are gaining rather than losing blacks,
although no one could immediately provide figures.
   ``I don't hear a hue and cry for breaking away,'' said Auxiliary
Bishop John H. Ricard of Baltimore, chairman of the bishops'
committee on black Catholics of the National Conference of Catholic
Bishops.
   ``The father's argument that there is racism in the church has
been acknowledged,'' Ricard said, adding ``there is a crying need
for our church to meet the social and economic needs of
African-Americans.''
</TEXT>
