<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1503EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>b w PM-Bush1stLd-Writethru a0614-a0616-a0620-a0624   07-06
0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush 1st Ld-Writethru, a0614-a0616-a0620-a0624,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Deflects Gorbachev Call for Talks on Short-Range Weapons</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material throughout. Combines previous</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today deflected Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's call for swift negotiations over short-range
nuclear weapons, noting that NATO leaders agreed not to entertain
such talks until an accord had been reached on conventional forces.
   ``I don't want to get off track'' by reopening the issue of
short-range nuclear forces that Western leaders agreed to in
Brussels in May, Bush said.
   In a nationally televised session with foreign reporters designed
to set the stage for his European journey on Sunday, Bush said he
hoped to use his visits to Poland and Hungary to nudge both
Communist-controlled countries toward democracy.
   He insisted he wasn't trying to stir up trouble in Gorbachev's
backyard, saying, ``That is not what 1989 diplomacy is about.'' At
the same time, Bush called on East Germany and other less open
Warsaw Pact nations to ``come along with the flow.''
   He said he looked forward to a Europe that ``is whole and free.''
   ``Our challenge is to help create the conditions under which the
Hungarians and Poles can recover economically and make the
transition ...,'' he said of his pending visits to two nations in
the throes of extraordinary political and economic change.
   Bush also said he is happy that former Marine Lt. Col. Oliver
North did not draw a jail term for Iran-Contra crimes. He
sidestepped a question of a possible pardon, noting that the former
White House aide is appealing his conviction on three charges.
   North on Wednesday was given a suspended sentence and a $150,000
fine, and was ordered to perform 1,200 hours of community service in
an anti-drug program.
   Bush fielded questions in the Executive Office Building across
the street from the White House. His audience consisted largely of
foreign reporters, although American journalists were permitted to
ask questions, as well.
   The president's two stops in Eastern Europe will precede an
economic summit meeting in Paris and a follow-up visit in the
Netherlands.
   He said he hoped the summit would deal with worldwide
environmental concerns and make a contribution toward
non-inflationary growth.
   Bush's reply to a question about Gorbachev's proposal appeared
carefully worded.
   ``The answer is to please read carefully what happened in
Brussels,'' he said. ``To look at the united NATO position and to go
forward ... with the agenda at hand. That will be the message. I
don't want to get off the track by reopening the short-range nuclear
forces package,'' he said.
   In a speech earlier in the day in Strasbourg, France, Gorbachev
offered to make additional and rapid cuts in his country's nuclear
arsenal if NATO accepts negotiations on tactical nuclear weapons.
   The speech seemed designed in part to increase pressure on the
United States to depart from an agreement with its allies on an
issue that dominated the NATO summit in May.
   The NATO agreement calls for negotiations to reduce short-range
nuclear missiles only after an East-West agreement has been reached
to reduce conventional forces and reductions are actually underway.
   ``I see no reason to stand here and try to change a collective
decision taken by NATO,'' the president said today.
   In his response to Gorbachev, Bush added, ``we welcome unilateral
cuts on his side, certainly.''
   Bush said he was untroubled by Gorbachev's rejection of the
American call for the withdrawal of Soviet troops from Poland.
   ``We're not trying ... to make things more difficult for him,
just as when he goes to France and Germany, I don't think he's
trying to make things more difficult for us,'' he said.
   ``My trip over there is not to ... try to drive wedges between
the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe,'' Bush said. ``That is not what
1989 diplomacy is about.''
   ``We're not going to be there trying to raise tensions,'' he
added of his trip to Poland.
   He said he wanted to ``extend to them whatever help we can'' and
help that country move toward more reform and more openness.''
   He noted he could not impose his wishes on the internal affairs
of the governments of Poland and Hungary, but made clear that he
hopes his visit will assist a trend toward openness.
   Both countries have undergone dramatic political reforms in
recent months, including the admission of Solidarity union leaders
into the Polish parliament under unusually open elections.
   ``In Poland and Hungary, our strong support for the democratic
course these nations have chosen will be clear,'' he said. ``Their
efforts are not only a new beginning in their own countries, but can
be the beginning of an historic process of European reconciliation,
of ending the artificial division of Europe.
   ``We want to help these countries toward an alternative future, a
democratic alternative and help create a Europe that is whole and
free,'' he said.
   Asked whether he has preconditions for better relations with East
Germany, Bush said, ``Yes I do see preconditions: a little more
democracy, a little more freedom, a little more openness.''
</TEXT>
