<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1700EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FetalDisposal     07-06 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fetal Disposal,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Strikes Down Fetal Disposal Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has struck down a 1987
Minnesota law requiring dignified and sanitary disposal of aborted
or miscarried fetuses, saying the law could interfere with a woman's
right to have an abortion.
   By elevating the status of a fetus to that of a person or a human
body, the law creates a psychological burden similar to those found
unconstitutional in other states, Judge David Doty said in a
decision released last Friday.
   Doty also said the law was unclear about how to dispose of fetal
remains.
   ``It appears substantially likely that the statute is so vague
that persons charged with enforcement of the statute are left free
to react to their own preferences, thereby trapping those who desire
to be law-abiding and acting without fair notice of the conduct that
is considered unlawful,'' Doty said.
   The judge noted that lawmakers drafting the law had been unable
to agree on what type of disposal would be considered dignified.
   ``Some legislators stated that group burial or cremation would
not be dignified while others assumed that a dignified burial or
cremation need not be individual,'' he wrote.
   Disposal of fetal remains became an issue after fetal parts
allegedly were found in a dumpster behind a clinic and displayed by
anti-abortion activists.
   The law was scheduled to go into effect Aug. 1, 1987, but Planned
Parenthood of Minnesota and Dr. Mildred Hanson filed a lawsuit in
July of that year attempting to block it. Restraining orders
previously issued by Doty kept the law from being enforced.
   Planned Parenthood argued that the law suggested to women that an
abortion is to be equated with taking a human life, which would
interfere with their right to an abortion by making the abortion
decision psychologically more disturbing.
   The state said the law would not unduly interfere with a woman's
abortion decision.
   The state argued that it was not equating fetal remains with a
dead person but was acknowledging that a fetus is different from
other human anatomical tissues because it has the potential to
develop into a human being. Doty rejected that argument.
   He also said that requiring individual treatment of fetuses could
increase the cost of an abortion by at least $40.
   ``Although to many seeking an abortion a $40 increase may seem
insignificant, but for a woman on welfare or for an unemployed
teen-ager, this additional cost may put the cost of an abortion
beyond reach and become a direct burden,'' Doty said.
   Minnesota Attorney General Hubert H. Humphrey III said Wednesday
that a decision on an appeal has not yet been made. However, he
said, ``I assume we will appeal that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
