<FIRST>r i AM-Angola     07-0ola,0482
^Angolan Guerrilla Ch6 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>^AM-Angief Says Both Sides Violate Cease-Fire</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan guerrilla leader Jonas
Savimbi said Thursday his forces and government troops both have
violated a June 24 cease-fire, but he said this should not stop
talks to end the war.
   Savimbi, leader of UNITA, the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, signed an agreement with the Luanda
government June 22 in Gbadolite, Zaire, to begin peace negotiations.
   The agreement included a truce in the 14-year guerrilla war.
   But Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos has suspended the
peace talks because of guerilla violations of the cease-fire.
   ``That there have been attacks froavimbi's decision to accept the Gbadolite
agreement has earned
him a legitimacy he did not know during the war. He was photographed
at the Zaire summit with several African leaders whose governments
had called his guerrillas puppets of South Africa.
   And although Ivorian President Felix Houphouet-Boigny had quietly
supported Savimbi's calls for national reconciliation in the former
Portuguese colony, the Angolan guerrilla leader had never appeared
publicly in the Ivory Coast before Thursday's news conference.
   In the past, the guerrilla leader arranged to fly reporters into
his stronghold in southeastern Angola.
   Savimbi agreed to absent himself from direct participation in the
peace negotiations, but he made it clear suggestions he go into
exile are out of the question.
   He said if exile had even been suggested he would not have
attended the summit.
   ``I do not think there are any grounds for discussing exile or
integration because it is not going to happen at all,'' Savimbi said.
   He said his movement's goal remains free national elections,
which dos Santos rejects, and suggested Africa learn from the
democracy process in some Eastern European countries.
   ``We do not think that the one-party system is good,'' Savimbi
said. ``Africa also is going to make progress. You see what is
happening in Poland and Hungary ... let us just do it now,'' he said.
</TEXT>
