<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     07-06 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian-Syrian Shelling Kills 5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christians and Syrians broke a two-day
lull in their long artillery war Thursday and traffic dissolved in a
din of blaring horns as shells rained on Beirut during the morning
rush hour.
   Police said five people were killed and 13 wounded, bringing the
total to 402 dead and 1,551 wounded since the battle began March 8
between Christian army units and a Moslem alliance of Druse
militiamen and Syrian soldiers.
   Panicky motorists sped away in all directions and pedestrians
rushed to bomb shelters to escape shells and rockets that began
falling at 8 a.m. on Moslem west Beirut and on the city's eastern
sector, where Christians live.
   Vegetable vendors abandoned their stalls and sought refuge in
building entrances when a shell crashed into the main street of
Karakon, a Druse district of west Beirut.
   The whoosh of rockets, thunder of shells and wail of ambulance
sirens filled the air across the battered city. Steel shutters
slammed down on shops and banks.
   As abruptly as it began, the battle subsided at 9:30 a.m. and
settled into what has become a daily pattern: the intermittent thud
of shells fired by the Syrians at the Christian-held coast north of
Beirut.
   Lakhdar Ibrahimi, assistant secretary-general of the Arab League,
drove into west Beirut from Syria just before the shooting stopped,
to meet with Lebanese leaders about how to end one of the worst
episodes in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   He spent 90 minutes with acting Premier Salim Hoss, who heads a
Moslem cabinet vying for power with that of Gen. Michel Aoun,
commander of the Christian forces fighting the Syrians and Druse.
   Ibrahimi, an Algerian, refused to speak with reporters after
conferring with Hoss and crossed the city's sectarian dividing line
to meet with Aoun in the shattered presidential palace at Baabda, a
Christian suburb.
   Police said Syrian howitzers in north Lebanon opened fire briefly
at about noon on a small freighter carrying food supplies to Byblos,
a Christian-run port 19 miles north of Beirut, but the ship docked
without damage.
   A spokesman for Aoun's command said the Syrians provoked
Thursday's battle by firing before dawn at towns in the
310-square-mile Christian enclave north and east of Beirut.
   Before the latest artillery duel began, Presidents Mikhail S.
Gorbachev of the Soviet Union and Francois Mitterrand of France
urged that both sides observe a cease-fire and said arms deliveries
to warring Lebanese factions should be halted.
   They issued a joint statement during Gorbachev's visit to France.
   On Wednesday, press reports said Syria had demanded Aoun remove
medium-range missiles, capable of reaching Damascus, that his forces
were said to have received from Iraq.
   Asked whether such missiles had been delivered, Aoun's spokesman
said Thursday: ``If so, then their withdrawal is linked to the
Syrian pullout from Lebanon.'' He refused to elaborate.
   Syria has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon under a peacekeeping mandate
issued by the Arab League in 1976, the year after the civil war
began. Early in the 4-month-old artillery war, Aoun said the Syrians
were an occupation force and he was fighting a ``war of liberation.''
</TEXT>
