<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     07-06 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Palestinians Die, More Arrests In West Bank Sweep</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Bus, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13-year-old Palestinian boy was shot and
killed in the Askar refugee camp in the occupied West Bank on
Thursday when soldiers on patrol opened fire, Arab reports said.
   The teen-ager was identified as Aiman Badran, and doctors at
Al-Ittihad Hospital in Nablus said he was dead on arrival with a
bullet in the head.
   The army spokesman's office said it had no information about the
case.
   No major clashes were reported in the camp on Thursday, and it
was not known why the soldiers opened fire, Arab reporters in Nablus
said.
   Also Thursday, two Palestinians died of wounds suffered in
earlier clashes with Israeli troops, and soldiers took 16 Arabs into
custody in continuing security sweeps in the occupied West Bank.
   One of the victims was identified as 18-year-old Hassam Hamad of
the Khan Yunis refugee camp in the occupied Gaza Strip. He was shot
in the head on Wednesday in a stone-throwing confrontation with
soldiers and died at Tel Hashomer Hospital near Tel Aviv, the army
said.
   The other victim was identifed as 30-year-old Awni Sawalhah of
the West Bank village of Assira Shamaliya, who died at Hadassah
Hospital in Jerusalem, family members said.
   Sawalhah, an ambulance driver for the Friends of the Patients
Society, was transporting the body of a Palestinian killed in a
clash with soldiers on June 18 when troops opened fire on his
ambulance, hitting him in the lower back, hospital officials said.
   The society, an Arab charitable organization, filed a formal
protest with the army over the shooting.
   The three deaths raised to at least 546 the number of
Palestinians killed since the uprising against Israeli rule in the
occupied territories began 19 months ago. Twenty-three Israelis also
have died.
   The toll of Israelis was likely to rise after police released the
names of victims in Thursday's bus crash.
   At least 14 people were killed and 27 injured after a bus plunged
off the Tel Aviv-Jerusalem highway when a Palestinian grabbed the
steering wheel and forced it off the road, police said.
   Most of the casualties are believed to be Israelis, but the
injured include at least 7 Americans, a Canadian and a Spanish woman.
   An army sweep of the Jalazun refugee camp near the West Bank town
of Ramallah resulted in the arrest of 16 suspected leaders of the
uprising, the army said.
   The arrests raised to about 300 the number of Palestinian
activists taken into custody in search-and-arrest operations that
began last Sunday.
   The army has said the detainees were suspected of membership in
``popular committees,'' which organize Palestinian resistance, and
``strike forces,'' which enforce strikes and boycotts called by the
underground leadership of the uprising.
   The army announced it demolished three houses and sealed three
others Thursday to punish Palestinians accused of attacks on
Israelis or on Arabs suspected of collaborating with Israel.
   The houses were in the areas of Nablus, Jenin and Qalqilya in the
West Bank, the army said.
</TEXT>
