<FIRST>r w AM-KoreaMarch     07-06 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea March,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thirty Americans to Join Korean March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 30 Americans are planning to participate
in a peninsula-wide peace march in Korea, according to organizers
who said Thursday the event could spark retaliation from South
Korean government leaders.
   The Americans will meet 100 people from 16 countries, then divide
up for simultaneous marches through South Korea and communist North
Korea, according to organizers.
   ``We feel a special responsibility to participate in this
historic march because it is the presence of 43,000 U.S. troops in
South Korea that is the primary obstacle to overcoming the cruel
division of Korea, which is a legacy of World War II and the cold
war that followed,'' said Channing Liem, former South Korean
ambassador to the United Nations and now a U.S. citizen.
   Jihoon Lee of the Young Koreans United said many fear that those
marching through South Korea may be ``violently suppressed,'' given
the ``current repressive climate.''
   Lee and Liem pointed to the recent arrest of hundreds of leading
student and trade union activists after a visit by South Korean
clergyman Moon Ik Hwan to North Korea.
   The peace march is part of the International Peace and
Reunification Study Tour of Korea. Participants will travel through
many towns, villages, and cities to talk with residents and visit
their workplaces, schools, and community centers.
   Besides the estimated 30 Americans, other participants will come
from Australia, the Philippines, Latin America, Africa, Europe and
the Asia-Pacific Region for the July 20 event.
   A demilitarized zone dividing Korea originally was created as
part of a temporary truce agreement. Organizers said marchers will
call for a permanent peace pact.
   In the past, the South Korean government has mobilized prevented
marchers supporting reunification from reaching the zone, Lee said.
   Whit Hutchison, a Methodist minister and educator, said the march
should call attention to the international power politics being
played in that country.
   ``For the entire period of my life, Americans have been deeply
implicated in a divided and militarized Korea,'' said Hutchison.
   Susan Bailey of the People's Anti-War Mobilization, also
criticized the role of the United States in Korea. Last year, Bailey
was arrested during a visit to South Korea and deported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890706-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1734EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     07-06 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Says Moon Must Be Released as Condition for Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PYONGYANG, North Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior government official said
Thursday that stalled talks with South Korea cannot resume unless
Seoul frees a dissident clergyman who was jailed for visiting North
Korea.
   ``The South Korean authorities must release the Rev. Moon
Ik-hwan,'' Chon Kum Chol, vice chairman of the Commission for the
Reunification of the Fatherland, said at a news conference. ``If he
is released, all the talks will be resumed between the North and the
South.''
   Chon also said future talks could be jeopardized if South Korea
arrests Im Su-kyong, a 20-year-old student who also defied a Seoul
ban on travel to North Korea to attend an international youth
festival.
   He said that if Miss Im, like Moon, is arrested upon her return,
``it will b will be a great challenge and we will regard it as a
great obstacle to North-South dialogue.''
   Moon, a leading critic of the South Korea government of President
Roh Tae-woo, was detained after a visit to North Korea in March in
which he held lengthy talks with North Korean President Kim Il Sung
on possible Korean reunification.
   Chon said the South Korean National Security Law, which bans
unauthorized trips to North Korea, is ``the worst evil law.''
   The two nations, divided since 1945, resumed direct talks last
fall, with seven meetings of lawmakers discussing steps toward a
non-aggression pact and other tension-easing measures.
   Talks also were held early this year on preparing for a meeting
of the two nations' prime ministers and on organizing a joint team
for the 1990 Asian Games in Beijing.
   But North Korea suspended the parliamentary talks in February to
protest the annual U.S.-South Korean ``Team Spirit'' military
maneuvers, and the other talks were called off in April after Moon's
arrest.
   Chon accused the South of ``raising a frantic anti-communist,
anti-North clamor'' after the Moon trip and said the Roh government
had made no proposals for reunification.
   ``Confrontation between the North and the South is now quite
acute,'' he said.
   Chon said North Korea had proposed Red Cross talks on Aug. 15 on
reuniting divided families. He did not list the Red Cross talks,
last held in 1985, among the dialogues that will be affected by the
Moon case.
   Chon also indicated that North Korea would be willing to hold
meaningful talks with the United States if the joint military
maneuvers are suspended.
   ``Everything depends on the United States,'' he said. ``If they
show a change in attitude, we may be willing to reciprocate.''
   North Korea says the presence of 43,000 U.S. troops in South
Korea is the main obstacle to easing tensions. It has proposed a
phased withdrawal of U.S. troops by 1991, to be accompanied by a
reduction of both North and South Korean forces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890706-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1831EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-LennonFilm     07-06 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lennon Film,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Film Found in Late Beatle's Rolls Royce Still a Mystery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SURREY, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exhaustive research has failed to
clear up the mystery of a home movie found under a seat in John
Lennon's psychedelic Rolls Royce.
   As a result, officials at the Transportation Museum of British
Columbia have released the uneven, heavily spliced film, shot in
1970 in the Beacon Hill area of Boston.
   ``What we can do now is let it go to the public,'' said museum
development officer Fred Davies. ``With positive identification of
people (in the film), then maybe we'll get some more information.''
   The biggest mystery is ``how did the film get into John Lennon's
Rolls Royce?'' Davies said Wednesday. ``That is the magic question.''
   The 28-minute home movie shows several young men and women in
their late teens or early 20s smoking a hookah, or water pipe,
followed by several surreal images of a church, a television cartoon
show and numerous wine bottles.
   ``Maybe they're trying to depict what happens after you smoke
this thing, who knows,'' Davies mused while showing the film to
reporters.
   Another highlight is footage of a total eclipse of the sun as
seen in New England on March 7, 1970, along with a peace
demonstration attended by the young people and Boston police
equipped with riot gear.
   The 8mm color movie was found in November under a passenger seat
in the late Beatle's 1965 Phantom V Rolls Royce, which Lennon had
painted with flowers, scrolls and zodiac signs.
   Vancouver millionaire Jim Pattison bought the car for $2.3
million at an auction in 1985 and brought it to British Columbia for
display at the Expo 86 world's fair. Pattison later donated the
vehicle to the province, and it has become the top attraction and
publicity generator for the museum.
   Museum researchers have failed to turn up more information on the
film, and Davies suggested that the filmmaker and participants might
be keeping quiet to preserve their reputations.
   ``We've had a few dead ends,'' he said. ``Maybe 20 years later
they might be senators or presidents of corporations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
