<DOCNO> AP890706-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1832EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Legislature     07-06 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Legislature,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Legislature Rejects Another Candidate for Senior Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet legislature on Thursday refused to
confirm the first deputy chairman of the nation's highest court
because he was an official in the period before ``perestroika,''
Tass reported.
   The official news agency said the Supreme Soviet voted against
Sergei I. Gusev by a count of 162-127, with 73 abstentions, because
he ``was a prominent figure in the judicial system in the period
before perestroika'' _ President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's program of
political and economic restructuring.
   ``Gusev's excessively emotional remarks also seemed to have
played a negative role,'' Tass added, without elaborating.
   There has been a substantial turnover in senior government and
Communist Party personnel since Gorbachev began his policy of
restructuring. The latest step has allowed the legislature to vote
on Cabinet and other senior level posts.
   Gusev, who assumed the number two spot on the Soviet Supreme
Court in 1979, was the latest in a string of senior officials whose
nominations have been turned down.
   The legislature confirmed five incumbent Cabinet members, the
news agency said.
   The parliament suspended its consideration of government
nominations Thursday because Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov was leaving
for Romania. He and Gorbachev are to attend a meeting of the Warsaw
Pact consultative committee.
   While turning down Gusev, the legislature approved the
nominations of two junior members of the Supreme Court, Aleksandr M.
Filatov, 66, who had held the post of deputy chairman since last
December, and Robert G. Tikhomirnov, 61, who has been sitting on the
21-member court since April 12, 1984.
   The Cabinet nominees who were approved were:
   _ Vladimir M. Velichko, 52, minister of heavy machine-building.
Velichko has held that post since July 20, 1987, and has been a
member of the Communist Party Central Committee since March 6, 1986.
   _ Mikhail I. Shchadov, 62, coal minister. He has held his post
since Dec. 15, 1985, and has been a member of the Central Committee
since March 6, 1986.
   _ Nikolai Lamayev, 60, minister of the chemical and oil refining
industries. Tass did not report when he took office.
   _ Vladislav G. Kolesnikov, 64, minister of electronics
industries. He has held his post since Nov. 18, 1985, has been a
member of the Central Committee since March 6, 1986, and has served
on the Central Committee Commission on Socio-economic Policy since
October.
   _ Oleg G. Anfimov, 52, minister of electro-technical industries.
Tass provided no further information on him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
