<DOCNO> AP890706-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1836EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     07-06 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Set to Crush Extremists with Censorship; Shoot on Sight Orders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This report was submitted to a government censor, but no changes
were made.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government extended tough
censorship laws to foreign media Thursday and gave security forces
shoot-on-sight powers in moves to crush Sinhalese extremism.
   All public meetings and trade union rallies have been banned in
the crackdown, Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratna told reporters.
   The latest victims of the militant left-wing extremists are seven
people killed Wednesday, including three men accused of supporting
the government and two Moslems whose bodies were left hanging from a
coconut tree, police said.
   The government blames the extremists for the deaths of at least
3,500 people in southern Sri Lanka, where they have fought for two
years to overthrow the government. Most victims are government
officials or supporters of Prime Minister Ranasinghe Premadasa's
governing party.
   ``We will not allow the government to be displaced by gun-toting
criminals,'' Wijeratna told reporters. ``Our armed forces and police
have been given wide powers to deal with all forms of subversion in
the most ruthless manner.''
   He said this includes powers to shoot on sight people involved in
violence or putting up anti-government posters.
   The government says the extremists, from the People's Liberation
Front, also instigated a four-week strike by transport workers that
is crippling the economy.
   On censorship, Wijeratna told reporters, ``I will cancel your
visas and deport you if you violate the censorship.''
   Foreign journalists initially were exempted from laws banning
reports on the radical Sinhalese movement that went into effect
Thursday morning.
   But Wijeratna said: ``No news whatsoever can go out of this
country without being censored. If you cannot conform to that,
please leave the country.''
   Local journalists who violate the laws will be jailed, he said.
   Militant Sinhalese began killing government supporters in July
1987 to protest peace overtures to Tamil rebels fighting since 1983
for an independent homeland in the northeast.
   Tamils are a mainly Hindu ethnic group and say they are
discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who are mostly Buddhists and
comprise 75 percent of this island nation's 16 million people.
   Since May, the government has been holding peace talks with the
biggest Tamil rebel group, which initially rejected peace overtures
under a 1987 accord sponsored by neighboring India, but agreed last
month to a truce.
   However, the rebels continue to fight 40,000 Indian soldiers
deployed on the island to end the insurrection. New Delhi has
refused Colombo's request to withdraw its troops, saying the rebel
truce is a ruse and that they will continue fighting once Indian
troops withdraw.
   New Delhi also says a hasty pullout would lead to greater
bloodshed in the northeast, where 9,000 people, mostly Sinhalese,
have been killed.
   On Tuesday, Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi offered to discuss
a timetable for a gradual withdrawal.
   Wijeratna told reporters Thursday that his government will not
send an envoy to New Delhi. ``If India wants to sit down and talk
about the troop withdrawal, they will have to send somebody'' to
Colombo, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
