<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev-Walesa     07-06 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Walesa,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Says He Would Like to Meet Gorbachev</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa says he would
accept any invitation to meet with Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, an opposition daily reported Thursday.
   The newspaper printed the remark one day after Gorbachev told a
news conference in Paris that he saw ``no obstacle'' to meet
eventually with representatives of the independent union. There
might be ``a possibility of a meeting with this organization
recognized by the Polish people,'' Gorbachev said.
   Asked by Gazeta Wyborcza whether he would accept such an
invitation, Walesa replied: ``I would go immediately.''
   Gorbachev visited Poland a year ago and made no contact with the
then-banned union. Solidarity was declared legal again in April.
   Adam Michnik, editor of the mass-circulation Gazeta Wyborcza and
a Walesa adviser, has developed a deep interest in Gorbachev's
reform policies, and senior Solidarity activists have started to
follow Soviet events as well.
   During a visit to Paris in October for a human rights conference,
Walesa had a long talk with Soviet human rights activist Andrei
Sakharov, like himself a Nobel Peace Prize winner.
</TEXT>
