<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--GatorPunch     07-06 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Gator Punch,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fisherman Nearly Hauled in by Gator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLIDAY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A backyard fisherman reeling in a bluegill
stepped into a lake to free the fish from a clump of weeds and was
nearly hauled in himself by a 7-foot alligator.
   ``I punched him on the top of the head, punched him real hard,
and he let go. In fact, my fist is swollen,'' said William Barger,
who suffered two gashes in his left thigh.
   ``I think when I stepped down in the water, he had just been
laying there and the first thing he saw was my leg,'' said the
6-foot-2, 230-pound Barger. The gator ``just popped up out of the
water and grabbed me by the leg. If he had grabbed my ankle or
wrist, he probably would have taken it right off.''
   After Tuesday's attack, three Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish
Commission officers and a trapper went to the mobile home park,
captured the gator and a 9-foot alligator nearby and killed them,
said Capt. J.R. Doxey, commission regional supervisor.
   Barger expects to be laid up for about a week.
</TEXT>
