<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 2026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NuclearProbe     07-06 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Probe,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Inspectors, FBI Probe Nuclear Site For Waste Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST VALLEY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators made a surprise
visit to a former nuclear fuel plant Thursday as part of a
nationwide probe of environmental and safety problems at nuclear
facilities, officials said.
   FBI agents and the federal Department of Energy's ``tiger team''
of environmental specialists descended on the upstate New York plant
looking for evidence of possible violations of federal laws
governing hazardous wastes, according to Dennis C. Vacco, the U.S.
attorney in Buffalo.
   They would probably be at the site for several weeks, officials
said.
   Vacco said the investigation was not specifically concerned with
nuclear wastes, which is the main type of waste handled at the West
Valley Demonstration Project.
   ``There is no current information of any problem in handling
nuclear wastes,'' he said. ``We're looking at pure hazardous
wastes.''
   ``Pure'' wastes are non-nuclear, chemical wastes.
   Vacco would not elaborate on possible problems or the nature of
the wastes, but people familiar with the plant said the
investigation may involve the storage of chemicals used when the
plant was still operating in the 1970s.
   West Valley, about 50 miles south of Buffalo, is a former nuclear
fuel reprocessing facility that is currently being decommissioned
and decontaminated. Thousands of gallons of liquid radioactive waste
stored in decaying underground tanks are being solidified into
cement drums and glass logs.
   Raymond Vaughn, of the West Valley Committee on Nuclear Waste, a
citizens group that opposes the storage of wastes at the site, said
he was not familiar with any chemical waste problems.
   ``It must be the old chemicals that were used in reprocessing,''
he said. ``The chemicals they use (now) are relatively innocuous.''
   He said toxic chemicals were used in reprocessing in the past,
and some may have been stored at the site.
   Deputy Energy Secretary Henson Moore said Thursday in Washington
that the West Valley investigation was the first of 17 such probes
by Energy Department specialists over the next year at federal
nuclear facilities.
   The Energy Department took over operation of the New York
state-owned plant 50 miles south of Buffalo in 1980. The government
is spending $800 million to clean up the facility.
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins announced last month that he
had created ``tiger teams'' of specialists to assess environmental
compliance at all Energy Department nuclear facilities, including
the nuclear weapons plants.
   The West Valley investigation is the first assignment of that
special team, according to Christina Sankey, a department
spokeswoman.
   In addition to reviewing the handling of wastes, the team will
also assess administrative and managerial procedures, Ms. Sankey
said.
   ``It was a surprise to us,'' said Micki Andrus, a West Valley
spokeswoman. ``We knew of Admiral Watkins' plan but didn't know they
would be coming here first.''
   Ms. Andrus said several investigators met with project managers
Thursday afternoon and that more members of the investigating team
were to arrive Friday.
   She said operations at the facility were not affected by the
investigation, which is expected to take four to six weeks.
</TEXT>
