<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--ChannelExplosion     07-06 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Channel Explosion,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storage Tank Along Ship Channel Explodes, One Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chemical storage tank along the Houston Ship
Channel exploded Thursday, killing one worker and sparking a fire,
authorities said.
   Investigators were still trying to determine the cause of the
explosion in the upper level of a 50-foot metal storage tank. No
other injuries were reported, and no evacuation was necessary, Fire
Department spokesman Mike Warnke said.
   The Oxide Inc. tank, which contained a form of glycol monomer,
exploded while the victim was working on the tank, Warnke said.
   ``He was working near the top of the tank and was blown off by
the explosion,'' Warnke said. ``It's possible that the explosion
could have been related to his work, but we don't know yet. There
was also a thunderstorm moving through the area at the time.''
   Warnke said the tank was partially filled with liquid chemicals
and the remainder was filled with vapor, but the level was not known.
   The name and age of the victim were not immediately available.
</TEXT>
