<FIRST>r a AM-DomesticPartners     07-06 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Domestic Partners,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Domestic Partnership Law May Be Headed for Ballot</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gay Roommates, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the day it was scheduled to take effect,
the city's new domestic partnership law was suspended because a
petition to take the issue to voters appeared to be valid, city
officials said Thursday.
   Two conservative clergymen submitted a petition with 27,122
signatures to the Registrar of Voters on Wednesday in an effort to
block the law and put it on the November ballot.
   They need 18,800 certified signatures to succeed and have a
``50-50 chance'' of qualifying for the Nov. 7 election, according to
Registrar of Voters Germaine Wong.
   The law, which recognizes gay and lesbian couples as well as
unmarried heterosexual unions, was unanimously approved by the Board
of Supervisors in May. Mayor Art Agnos signed it into law June 5,
making San Francisco the first major metropolitan city to adopt such
legislation.
   The new law permits live-in lovers to register with the city for
$35 in a procedure similar to filing a marriage license. The law
grants hospital visitation rights and bereavement leave to city
employees, and a provision to extend health care benefits to city
workers is being studied.
   No one actually signed up with the city as domestic partners
before the law was suspended, said assistant county clerk La Vergne
Keppard.
   Supporters expressed annoyance at the repeal effort but were
confident that the challenge will be defeated if it qualifies for
the ballot.
   ``We've got more than 60 percent of the voters' support for
domestic partners,'' said Jean Harris, an aide to Supervisor Harry
Britt, who authored the legislation.
   Although Wong said it will take her office several days to
validate the signatures, the city charter requires suspension of the
new law because the petition ``appears to contain the requisite
number of signatures,'' deputy city attorney Buck Delventhal said
after a meeting with city officials.
   If the referendum qualifies for the ballot, the Board of
Supervisors would have the option of repealing the domestic
partnership ordinance or sending it to the voters for approval.
   If the petition is ultimately rejected, the new law will
automatically take effect.
   Proponents heralded the law as a symbol of the validity of gay
relationships. Opponents, led by the Catholic church, said the
legislation weakened the sanctity of marriage.
   ``The up side of this whole (repeal) thing is that we will have
four months to educate the public and to really get the issues out
there and to help people really understand what domestic partnership
is about,'' said Larry Brinkin of the city's Human Rights
Commission, which was responsible for implementing the new law.
   Brinkin, who had planned to register with his lover as domestic
partners at a mass ``sign-in'' party in August, said he was
disappointed but not surprised by the repeal effort.
   ``It's not that I don't think people should have the right (to
vote), but I don't think it's necessary,'' he said. ``That's what I
hire supervisors to do. I want them to make the laws.''
   Leaders of the Catholic church did not sanction the repeal
effort, but Archdiocese spokesman Deacon Norman Phillips said,
``Obviously, we are in sympathy with its being taken off the books.''
   The petition was submitted by the Rev. Charles McIlhenny, a
pastor at the First Orthodox Presbyterian Church, and by Rabbi
Lionel Feldman, who is not affiliated with a synagogue, according to
the Board of Rabbis of Northern California.
   Reached at his church, McIlhenny refused to comment. Feldman also
declined to talk to reporters on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
