<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;LWithdrawals     07-06 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Withdrawals,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Withdrawals Slow, Total Deposits Actually Climb</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Net deposit withdrawals from savings and loan
institutions slowed by more than 50 percent in May to $2.4 billion,
the Federal Home Loan Bank Board said Thursday.
   Two West Coast thrifts that lost a total of $1.4 billion in
deposits during the month accounted for more than half of the net
withdrawals, the S&amp;L industry's chief regulator said.
   After counting interest credited to depositors' accounts, total
deposits in the nation's 2,934 S&amp;Ls grew by $587 million during May
to $955.2 billion. It was the first increase since last December.
   James Barth, the bank board's chief economist, attributed the
slightly improved deposit balances in thrift institutions to a
normal seasonal resumption of savings after April withdrawals to pay
taxes.
   Barth also said the spread between interest rates offered by
money market mutual funds and S&amp;Ls also narrowed modestly in May.
   The May decrease in net deposits _ the 13th in a row _ was the
smallest since savers began pulling their money out of S&amp;Ls more
than a year ago as concern about the health of the industry
heightened.
   ``Passage of legislation permitting troubled thrifts to be
resolved should lessen depositor concerns and thereby enable the
industry to better manage its deposits,'' Barth said.
   Withdrawals from accounts of $100,000 or smaller, the amount
insured against losses by the federal government, declined from $5.7
billion in April to $300 million in May, the board said.
   However, holders of deposits exceeding $100,000 pulled a total of
$2.2 billion out of S&amp;Ls in May, compared with a $400,000 increase
in their deposits in April.
</TEXT>
