<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-06 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Troops Advance Toward Pakistan Border</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said troops supported by
aircraft and heavy artillery advanced toward a major Moslem
guerrilla base near the Pakistani border Thursday on the second day
of an offensive.
   The Soviet-sponsored government said the soldiers killed at least
287 guerrillas, wounded 238 and captured tanks, armored personnel
carriers and ammunition. It gave army casualties as only four dead.
   Each side in the 11-year-old war customarily exaggerates the
other's losses and minimizes its own.
   ``This is our biggest offensive ... since the Soviet troop
withdrawal'' completed Feb. 15, said presidential spokesman Sarwar
Yourish. ``Our aim is to push the rebels toward the Pakistani
border.''
   He said the army drove the insurgents back on the south and
southeast of Jalalabad, capital of Nangarhar province, which has
been under guerrilla siege since March 7.
   Jalalabad is 75 miles east of Kabul and 45 miles from Pakistan,
where most of the guerrillas are based.
   Afghan air force jets bombed rebel positions in and around
Jalalabad for a second day and guerrilla rocket attacks on the city
continued, Yourish said.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said soldiers
advanced toward a guerrilla base at Torkham, six miles from the
Pakistani border, after overrunning insurgent positions around
Jalalabad.
   The Torkham base at the foot of the Khyber Pass, a major route
for supplies from Pakistan, is a staging area for attacks on
Jalalabad.
   In Pakistan, the guerrilla-run Afghan Information and
Documentation Center acknowledged the loss of some positions near
Jalalabad.
   An Afghan pilot landed his Soviet-made ground attack fighter in
Peshawar, Pakistan, and sought asylum Thursday, Pakistani officials
said.
   A Pakistan air force official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the pilot of the Sukhoi-22 jet ``refused to bombard
mujahedeen positions and fled to Pakistan.'' Afghan guerrillas call
themselves mujahedeen, or Islamic holy warriors.
   On Monday, two Afghan helicopters landed in Pakistan and their
crews sought political asylum.
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting after a communist coup in April
1968 and Soviet forces intervened in December 1979. An estimated
115,000 Red Army soldiers were in Afghanistan when the U.N.-mediated
withdrawal began on May 15, 1988.
</TEXT>
