<FIRST>r w AM-BushSchedule     07-06 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Schedule,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>President's Trip Covers 9,040 Miles, 4 Nations in 10 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's four-nation trip to Europe
will take him 9,040 miles over 10 days, with 24.5 hours of flight
time on Air Force One on the way to Poland, Hungary, France and the
Netherlands and back home.
   Bush will leave Washington about 7 a.m. EDT Sunday for Poland.
Because of the six-hour time difference, it will be about 10 p.m.
local time when he arrives in Warsaw.
   During a two-night stay in Warsaw, Bush will meet with Polish
leaders, deliver a speech before the Parliament on Monday and attend
a state dinner.
   On Tuesday, Bush will fly to Gdansk to meet with Lech Walesa and
other Solidarity leaders. He will deliver a speech at the Solidarity
monument near the Lenin shipyard where Walesa worked as an
electrician.
   Later Tuesday, Bush will go on to Budapest, becoming the first
American president to visit Hungary. A state dinner is planned on
the first night of his stay.
   On Wednesday, Bush will meet with students opposed to the
Communist government and deliver a speech at Karl Marx University.
   The president will fly to Paris on Thursday and take part in
ceremonies marking the 200th anniversary of the French Revolution.
   On Friday, July 14, Bush will join the leaders of France,
Britain, West Germany, Japan, Italy and Canada at the annual summit
of industrialized nations. The summit will conclude on Sunday, July
16, followed by a black-tie dinner.
   On Monday, Bush will go to the Hague, where he will meet with
leaders and make another speech. Bush will return to Washington on
Tuesday, expected to arrive early in the afternoon.
</TEXT>
