<HEAD>Bush Says He's Glad North Won't Serve Jail Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Thursday he's glad that
one-time White House aide Oliver North won't serve jail time for his
Iran-Contra convictions.
   But the president, in response to a reporter's question, would
not address the issue of a presidential pardon.
   Asked what he thought about the judge sparing North a prison
sentence and whether he has considered a pardon, Bush replied:
   ``One, I'm happy he's not going to jail. Two, I'm not going to
comment further because this matter is under appeal and is in the
federal courts.''
   North is expected to appeal his conviction but has not yet done
so.
   Bush made his comment during a question-and-answer session with
reporters from foreign news agencies and a small group of American
press.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell sentenced North on
Wednesday to a three-year suspended sentence, two years' probation,
$150,000 in fines and 1,200 hours of community service work.
   Bush has declined to talk about the possibility of a pardon for
North, although 58 members of the House signed a letter asking him
to do so. White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater's standard
answer on a possible pardon is that it has not been discussed.
   North's defense in the case was that he was carrying out his
activities to help the Nicaraguan Contras at the behest of his
superiors in the Reagan administration, at the time when Bush was
vice president. Bush has maintained he did not know the extent of
North's activities to help the rebels.
