<FIRST>r i AM-Greece     07-06 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Premier Says Government Won't Negotiate U.S. Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new conservative-communist government
will not negotiate an agreement on U.S. military bases but will
leave it up to the government formed after elections in October, the
premier said Thursday.
   Premier Tzannis Tzannetakis told Parliament that meantime,
relations with the United States will be kept at ``the level
indicated by the traditional friendship of the two countries.''
   The previous agreement on the four U.S. bases expired in
December. Greece gave the United States 17 months to negotiate a new
one or close the bases.
   Tzannetakis did not say if his government would decide whether to
extradite a Palestinian, Mohammed Rashid, who is wanted by the
United States for his alleged involvement in a bomb attack on a Pan
Am jetliner in 1982.
   The conservative premier, outlining his program to Parliament,
said his top goal was a promised cleanup of Greece's scandal-ridden
politics.
   Parliament is expected to give Tzannetakis a vote of confidence
on Saturday.
   ``The people are relieved to see that the time of cleansing has
come,'' Tzannetakis said in promising to investigate all scandals,
especially if there were indications that former Socialist officials
were involved.
   The Panhellenic Socialist Movement, with 125 seats in the
300-seat unicameral Parliament, failed to win a third term in office
in the June 18 general elections. Charges that officials of former
Premier Andreas Papandreou's government were involved in banking,
financial and arms scandals contributed to their defeat.
   The conservative New Democracy party, with 145 seats, and the
communist-led Coalition of the Left and Progress, with 28, forged an
unprecedented alliance when no party won an absolute majority in the
elections.
   Party leaders say the coalition will govern only for three months
with the purpose of investigating allegations of political
wrongdoing, and that new elections will be held in October.
</TEXT>
