<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Crash 1stLd-Writethru a0656 07-06 0915</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0656,0939</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Say Their Radars Missed Pilotless MiG</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to CLARIFY events surrounding pilot's ejection;
pickup 6th graf pvs, `The West...' ^By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet officer said Thursday radar operators
handling many military flights failed to notice the pilotless MiG-23
fighter zooming halfway across Europe before it crashed in Belgium.
   ``To control every plane when there are so many is not economical
or practical,'' said air force Lt. Col. Anatoly S. Balikin, speaking
at a news conference.
   The pilot of the MiG, Col. Nikolai Skurigin, ejected in Poland
after reporting that the aircraft was smoking and heading into the
Baltic Sea. But the plane sped on and killed an 18-year-old man when
it struck a house in Wevelgem, Belgium.
   Skurigin appeared before reporters Thursday and apologized
profusely to the victim's family.
   Soviet helicopters were still searching the Baltic Sea when they
were surprised by Western reports that the jet had crashed 560 miles
away in Belgium, said Gen. Yevgeny Shaposhnikov, deputy
commander-in-chief of the Soviet air force.
   The plane flew over Poland, East Germany, West Germany, the
Netherlands and Belgium before running out of fuel and crashing into
the house, near Belgium's border with France.
   The West European countries protested the incident to the Soviet
Union for failing to inform them about the wayward plane.
   The Soviet government has offered to pay compensation to the
victim's family in an apparently unprecedented gesture by the
Kremlin, but has not yet spelled out details of the payment.
   At least one East-bloc radar facility picked up an unidentified
plane crossing the border into the West, Balikin said, but
authorities believed the report erroneous because they counted their
planes and found none missing.
   ``This all took place under difficult conditions,'' Balikin said.
``Over the city of Kolobrzeg, there were training flights of East
German, Soviet and Polish planes.''
   There were also training flights over East Germany, he said.
   ``The flight paths were parallel or very close to the flight
paths of this flight or in the opposite direction,'' he added.
   A U.S. official who declined to be further identified said the
Soviet explanation ``calls into question their command and control
of their own aircraft. It's like saying they had an accident because
there was a lot of traffic.''
   Skurigin said he had written a personal letter of apology to the
victim's family, but ``nothing can compensate for the death.''
   ``I must tell you frankly, if I knew or could have foreseen such
tragic consequences of this pilotless flight, I would have stayed in
the plane to the end,'' said Skurigin, a stocky blond officer. His
hand was bandaged, and he said received only a minor finger injury
despite ejecting just 330 feet from the ground shortly after takeoff.
   Shaposhnikov made a similar statement when asked whether the
Soviet offer of compensation would cover the death as well as
material damages.
   The offer of damages and the news conference with six apologetic
senior Soviet officers departed from previous Soviet responses to
military incidents.
   Soviet officials refused to consider compensation when they shot
down a South Korean airliner in 1983 or when a sentry killed a U.S.
major in East Germany in 1985, said Richard Pipes, a Soviet expert
at Harvard University. Soviet authorities did apologize for the
death of the officer, Maj. Arthur D. Nicholson Jr., but not until
three years later.
   Responding to a reporter's questions, Shaposhnikov said Tuesday's
incident ``was not a test of combat readiness'' of North Atlantic
Treaty Organization air defenses.
   Two U.S. Air Force jets intercepted the MiG over West Germany but
did not shoot it down for fear it would fall on a populated area.
   Officials at NATO said nothing to Soviet authorities about the
jet until after it crashed, Shaposhnikov said, calling for a system
for NATO and Warsaw Pact forces to warn each other of such accidents.
   Last month, the U.S. and Soviet governments signed a pact on
avoiding dangerous military incidents, but it apparently was not
applied Tuesday.
   The pilot said he took off normally Tuesday on his second flight
of the day, then felt a sharp jerk at the left air intake and his
airspeed dropped abruptly.
   ``I radioed the tower that 132's engine was out,'' he said, and
turned its nose toward the sea. ``My commander told me to eject and
I bailed out.''
   Skurigin said he did not aim the jet straight down because it
would have crashed into a town near the Kolobrzeg airfield.
   As he parachuted, he saw the jet heading down with black smoke
pouring from the engine. ``I did not see any flames or any
indication it had crashed,'' he said.
   The MiG flew onward using an automatic lock-on navigation system
that kept it on the same course against the horizon, said air force
Maj. Gen. Abrek Ayupov. Western sources said it reached an altitude
of more than 36,000 feet over Western Europe.
   The wreckage was taken to a Brussels military depot Thursday to
await Soviet investigators. Belgium has said the Soviets can take
the wreckage home. NATO officials have said the MiG-23, first shown
in public 22 years ago, is well-known in Western intelligence
circles.
   On Wednesday, a Soviet fighter jet crashed in Poland after a
collision with a Polish civilian glider, whose pilot was killed.
Foreign Ministry spokesman Yuri Gremitskikh said it appeared neither
pilot was flying at his assigned altitude in the accident near
Lublin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
