<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-ExportArrest     07-06 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Export Arrest,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company President Arrested in Illegal Export Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Thursday they arrested the president of
a machinery company in a case involving unauthorized exports to
communist East Germany of rare material that could be used in
nuclear reactor rods.
   A police official, speaking on condition of anonymity, identified
the man as Hirokuni Matsuda, president of Prometron Technics Corp.,
a Tokyo-based maker of air plasma steel cutters.
   He said Matsuda was charged with violating Japan's Customs and
Foreign Exchange Law and could be sentenced to up to five years in
prison if convicted.
   Matsuda exported more than 22 pounds of hafnium valued at $28,600
to East Germany in 1986-87 without government clearance, the
official said.
   Hafnium is on a list of items strictly regulated under rules of
the Coordinating Committee on Multilateral Export Control, or COCOM,
a Paris-based Western watchdog body that regulates trade in
strategic items with the communist bloc.
   Because of its ready emission of electrons, hafnium is reportedly
used mainly in control rods for military reactors aboard
nuclear-powered vessels.
   The official said that Matsuda shipped 6.6 pounds of hafnium by
air to East Germany in February 1987, and an employee of his company
carried 15.4 pounds of hafnium hidden in his personal luggage.
</TEXT>
