<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico     07-06 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Says PRI is Trying to Steal State Legislature</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The conservative opposition charged Thursday
that the governing party was trying to steal the Baja California
legislature to neutralize a conservative victory in the governor's
race.
   The National Action Party accused the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, known as the PRI for its Spanish initials, of setting up
three ``laboratories'' where the ``alchemy'' of vote-changing was
taking place.
   National Action's Ernesto Ruffo won the July 2 gubernatorial
election, but the party's executive secretary, Francisco Gonzalez
Garza, said the PRI would run the government.
   ``Ruffo would be governor, but PRI would control the political
decisions,'' he said.
   Abel Vinicio Tovar, secretary-general of National Action _ known
as PAN _ said at the same news conference that the PRI's commitment
to democracy had been called into question.
   The PRI has been the government's party for 60 years, but in
recent years has increasingly maintained its hold by fraud.
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, who has struck several dramatic
blows against fraud and corruption since taking office Dec. 1, has
promised clean elections.
   The PRI conceded that Ruffo defeated Margarita Ortega in Baja
California. He would become the first non-PRI governor of any
Mexican state in 60 years if he takes office as scheduled Nov. 1 for
a six-year term.
   The vote is counted by party representatives who were at the
polling places on election day, and the parties make claims based on
their own counts.
   The official count by the state electoral commission will not be
released until Sunday, and the PAN claims the PRI and the government
are using the time to cook the figures.
   In the state legislature, the PAN says it is winning nine of 15
seats as well as the mayoralties of Ensenada and Tijuana. The PRI is
claiming Tijuana and 12 legislative seats.
   ``How could they lose the gubernatorial vote badly in Tijuana,
then win all six (of Tijuana's) legislative seats and the
mayoralty?'' asked Francisco Gonzalez Garza, PAN executive
secretary, citing figures gathered by PAN.
   PRI officials have admitted there were irregularities on July 2,
but maintain they were not large enough to affect the results. They
attribute the legislative results to ticket splitting, although they
have released no vote totals of their own.
   A person who answered the telephone at a private house that PAN
alleges is one of the alleged ``laboratories'' in Tijuana said the
owner was not at home. PAN accuses PRI supporters of taking ballot
boxes from vote counting centers to the ``laboratories'' and
stuffing them with PRI ballots or taking out PAN ballots.
   ``It's not true. None of those things are happening,'' said PRI
spokesman Arturo Galvan in a telephone interview from Mexicali, the
state capital. He accused PAN supporters of harassing PRI officials
and picketing PRI offices.
   Meanwhile, in the state of Michoacan west of Mexico City, the PRI
insisted it was winning a majority of 18 state legislative seats and
said it would ``fight for every vote.''
   The leftist opposition Democratic Revolutionary Party has said
its count shows it ahead, and the party accused the PRI of fraud.
   In Baja California, PAN officials said the PRI was trying to
stuff some ballot boxes and invalidate the count from boxes won
heavily by the PAN.
   Gonzalez Garza, PAN's executive secretary, said PAN figures
showed their candidate winning by a vote of 78,158 to 52,658.
   ``For a Baja California government, Tijuana is a determining
economic factor,'' he said.
   Baja California has one of Mexico's strongest state economies,
based on tourism and on cross-border industry. Tijuana is its
largest city, just south of San Diego on the U.S.-Mexico border.
</TEXT>
