<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 2109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MandelOath     07-06 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mandel Oath,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mandel Reinstated as Lawyer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STUCKEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Marvin Mandel was reinstated as
a lawyer Thursday in a 90-second ceremony that he called ``the last
step in a long journey'' back from his 1977 conviction on political
corruption charges.
   Mandel, 69, took the oath from Alexander Cummings, clerk of the
Court of Appeals, as his wife and his lawyers looked on.
   ``We got it done,'' the former Democratic governor said as he
signed his name in a book containing signatures of other lawyers
admitted to the bar in Maryland.
   Asked by reporters after the ceremony to describe his feelings,
Mandel replied, ``It's really an overwhelming feeling. It's been a
long time coming. It's the culmination of many years of struggle.''
   Mandel was disbarred after he failed to overturn his conviction
on mail fraud and racketeering charges. He served nearly 19 months
of a four-year prison sentence before President Reagan ordered his
release in December 1981 from a federal prison camp at Eglin Air
Force Base in Florida.
   He became eligible to apply for reinstatment to the bar when the
U.S. Supreme Court overturned his conviction last month.
   New lawyers normally take the oath at a session of the Court of
Appeals, which is on summer recess and will not return until
September. Mandel got permission from Chief Judge Robert Murphy to
have Cummings administer the oath instead of the chief judge.
   Asked why he moved so quickly to regain the right to practice
law, Mandel replied, ``Because I've been waiting eight years.
September is two months away. Why wait?''
   He was unsure whether he will practice law on his own or join a
law firm.
   ``Those are the kinds of questions I'm going to take a little
time to answer,'' he said.
   Mandel, who was named governor in 1969 and was elected to two
terms, said he will remain active in politics but has ``no intention
at this point of running for political office because there are none
available right now.''
   Having his conviction overturned and regaining the right to
practice law were the two most important steps in returning to a
normal life, Mandel said.
   ``I think this is the culmination of all of it,'' he said. ``I
think it's the last step on a long journey.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
