<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 2117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AbortionPoll     07-06 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Poll,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Half in Poll Oppose Supreme Court Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty percent of Americans surveyed in a new
poll say they oppose the Supreme Court decision making it easier for
the states to regulate abortion, the newspaper USA Today said
Thursday.
   Forty percent of the 662 adults polled by Gordon S. Black Corp.
said they support the court's ruling.
   The court ruled on Monday that Missouri could require certain
medical tests of fetal viability and keep public hospitals from
performing abortions. The justices said they would hear three cases
next year that raise the possibility of even further narrowing or
overturning of the 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision that legalized
abortion in the United States.
   The USA Today poll being published in Friday editions did not ask
respondents their positions on Roe Vs. Wade. The announcement of
results Thursday did not indicate why those opposing and supporting
Monday's decision took the positions they did, and spokeswoman
Sheila Gibbons said she did not know if that was tabulated in the
detailed results.
   The poll found that 38 percent reported they would be likely to
base a voting decision on a candidate's stand on abortion. This was
twice the percentage, 19 percent, that reported basing a past voting
decision on abortion.
   Asked what regulations they might support, 75 percent of the
respondents said parents of those under 18 should be notified if
their daughter seeks an abortion, 63 percent said husbands or
partners should be notified when adults seek abortions and 44
percent said abortions should not be performed in public health
facilities.
   The Associated Press-Media General poll of 1,108 people in April
reported that 53 percent favored Roe vs. Wade and 65 percent said a
woman should be able to get an abortion if her doctor agrees to it.
These responses cannot necessarily be compared with the USA Today
results because the questions were different.
   In a poll of 662 people, the margin of error is about four
percentage points.
</TEXT>
