<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-06 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summer Rains Soak South and East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The South and the East were drenched again with thunderstorm
rains Thursday that swelled rivers in Louisiana, closed roads in
Delaware and washed out bridges in Georgia.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from the central and
eastern Gulf Coast to the Tennessee Valley, the southern and central
Appalachians and the middle and southern Atlantic Coast. Heavy rain
fell in some areas.
   In the South, flooding was reported in Pelham in central Alabama.
Many roads and bridges remained closed in Cherokee and Cobb counties
near Atlanta due to earlier rains that brought an estimated 2 to 4
inches of rain by Thursday morning.
   In Louisiana, high water flooded a highway at Metairie near New
Orleans, and some rivers and streams were at or above their banks.
   The lower Calcasieu River in the southwestern part of the state
was nearly 8 feet above flood stage. Many homes and camps along the
river remained flooded, and many roads near it were impassable. The
Mermenteau River was 4 feet above flood stage near Mermenteau in the
south-central part of the state.
   In the East, standing water continued to block roads in northern
Delaware. Many streets were flooded and small streams overflowed
their banks in Cumberland County, N.J.
   Flash flood watches were in effect from western North Carolina to
western and central Virginia, much of Maryland and northern Delaware.
   Thunderstorms also fell over western South Dakota.
   But there was relief from the heat that had plagued the Pacific
Coast and the New England coast when temperatures dipped into the
60s and 70s. Much of the remainder of the nation had readings in the
80s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57
degrees at Arcata and Crescent City, Calif., to 110 at Needles,
Calif.
   Friday's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from eastern Texas to the lower Mississippi Valley, the Gulf Coast,
the Appalachians, the Atlantic Coast and Florida, and also over the
upper Mississippi Valley.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s through upper Michigan
and along the northern Pacific Coast; above 90 degrees from western
parts of the lower Ohio Valley to the middle and lower Mississippi
Valley, the Plains, the Rockies and interior Oregon and California;
in the 90s from the middle and southern Atlantic Coast to the
Florida Peninsula; above 100 degrees through the interior valleys of
California and near the Big Bend of the Rio Grande River in Texas;
and in the 80s in the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
