<FIRST>r i AM-CouncilofEurope 1stLd-Writethru   07-06 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Council of Europe, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0737,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Council of Europe Promotes Democracy, Civil Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 6th graf, `All West...' to DELETE reference to Finland
not being a member. Pick up 7th pvs, `The European...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 23-nation Council of Europe has
spent four decades promoting parliamentary democracy and human
rights.
   It was established May 5, 1949, as Western Europe's first
cooperative political organization, but now lives in the shadow of
the 12-member European Economic Community and the the European
Parliament, the EEC's advisory body.
   Acting through a Parliamentary Assembly and its executive
Committee of Ministers, the foreign ministers of member countries,
the Council has gained considerable prestige in the human rights
field.
   The Council's stated objectives are to work for greater European
unity, improve living conditions, develop human values and uphold
the principles of parliamentary democracy and human rights.
   Although it has no power over member governments, the Council
exerts influence as a consultative and advisory body on political
and moral issues.
   The Council, comprising the Western European democracies, has
been described as a ``laboratory of ideas.'' Its role has expanded
into a variety of areas, including terrorism and drugs, and it has
produced numerous accords and conventions among members.
   The European Convention on Human Rights is best known, and the
Council's most public arm is the European Court of Human Rights,
which accepts individual cases and makes decisions are binding on
states that have agreed to accept its rulings.
   Other conventions deal with subjects ranging from sports
hooliganism to terrorism.
   Last month, the Council granted the Soviet Union, Poland, Hungary
and Yugoslavia ``special guest status,'' allowing them to address
the body but not participate in decisions. The gesture was aimed at
encouraging better relations by recognizing political reforms under
way in those countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
