<DOCNO> AP890706-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 2135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-AfricaDebt 1stLd-Writethru   07-06 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Africa Debt, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0666,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Promises to Cancel African Debt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 7-9 bgng: ``Bush did not,'' to point out Latin
American debt not affected.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush announced Thursday the
cancellation of the debt of sub-Saharan African countries to the
United States.
   ``Beginning Oct. 1 the U.S. government will forgive official
development loans in the sub-Saharan countries,'' the president told
a news conference.
   In 1987, the most recent year in which figures were immediately
available, the State Department put the total of U.S. loans to
sub-Saharan Africa at $4.3 billion, including $743 million in
development loans, $1.5 billion from the U.S. government's
Export-Import Bank and $1.2 billion in U.S. government loans to buy
surplus American farm products.
   Bush did not say which of these categories would be included.
   Africa south of the Sahara Desert is usually taken to mean all of
Africa except South Africa and the North African countries on the
Mediterranean _ Egypt, Libya, Tunisia, Algeria and Morocco.
   Bush said his action would be in accordance with a decision taken
last year at an economic summit in Toronto to offer different
options to creditor governments. Until now, the United States has
preferred only to stretch out repayment terms.
   Bush did not mention Latin American debt, which is much greater
than African debt but is owed in large part to commercial banks in
North America and Europe rather than to governments. Major examples
are Mexico, which owes more than $100 billion, and Argentina, $60
billion.
   Earlier in the day Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady spoke to
reporters at length about the banks' current negotiations with
Mexico.
   ``With respect to Mexico they will sell those loans at less than
100 cents on the dollar and this is the first time that has been
recognized,'' Brady said. ``The stumbling blocks now they're arguing
about (are) whether those loans, which were borrowed at 100, should
be 90, 80, 70, 60, somewhere in there.''
   Other governments, notably in West Germany, France, the
Netherlands and the Nordic countries, have converted many loans into
grants. When major U.S. aid programs began with the Marshall Plan
for western Europe after World War II, the bulk of the money was in
grants. Over the years, loans became the preferred form of U.S. aid.
   As Third World debt mounted and the burden of interest payments
on debtor countries increased, the pendulum has swung back to
grants. Recipients of the biggest chunks of U.S. aid _ Israel and
Egypt _ now get grants and not loans.
   In 1987, sub-Saharan Africa owed $137.8 billion in medium- and
long-term debt. It was estimated that payments due from these
countries had risen from $5.6 billion in 1979 to $21 billion a year
for the period 1986 to 1989.
   Total Third World debt is put at about $1.3 trillion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
