<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     07-06 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striker Killed in Clash With Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW SCOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police armed with machine guns fired
Thursday on striking construction workers, killing one and wounding
four, witnesses said.
   In Cuzco, a major tourist city, police said guerrillas shot to
death two university students and left notes on both victims that
said: ``This is how informers die.''
   Police opened fire on the strikers after an officer was injured
by a stick of dynamite thrown by someone in the crowd, witnesses
said.
   The clash came after 150 police troopers in riot gear confronted
strikers outside the headquarters of the Civil Construction Workers
Union.
   An Associated Press reporter saw five wounded strikers evacuated
from the building. One of the wounded died later at a hospital, a
union official said.
   The construction workers earlier had joined striking doctors from
public hospitals in hurling firebombs at cars and buses and breaking
windows in downtown Lima. Police arrested 40 construction workers,
according to their union.
   Most areas of this impoverished nation's economy have been hit by
strikes by workers demanding huge wage increases to offset
inflation, which is running at nearly 6,000 percent a year.
   Downtown Lima has been the chaotic scene of numerous marches in
the past week by striking teachers, electric company workers, slum
residents demanding the government provide them with electric
service and a mothers' group demanding government milk donations.
   The doctors' strike, which began more than a month ago, has left
nearly all public hospitals without doctors.
   The construction workers union, which claims 250,000 members, has
been on strike since Monday and has virtually shut down all
construction projects in the nation.
   In the demonstration in downtown Lima, witnesses said between
2,000 and 3,000 strikers took to the streets after a rally at a
hospital. The witnesses said the protesters also smashed windows in
offices, shops and the Crillon Hotel, a downtown landmark.
   Riot police used clubs and tear gas to break up the protests, the
witnesses said.
   The construction workers gathered later outside their
headquarters in La Victoria, an industrial and working-class
neighborhood of Lima.
   During the confrontation that ensued, a secretary at the office
who spoke on condition of anonymity said the office was filling with
tear gas as she spoke and that shots were being fired outside.
   Union director Arturo Vicente said member Manuel Hernando, 32,
died after he was shot twice in the chest. He denied reports that
union members threw dynamite at the police.
   ``Our only weapon is the strike,'' Vicente said at a news
conference. ``We don't respond with dynamite, but with reason.''
   Meanwhile, police in Cuzco said Shining Path rebels shot to death
Walter Huayllani, a 24-year-old law student, as he was driving home
on Wednesday night.
   Huayllani was a member of a radical leftist party associated with
a rival guerrilla group, the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement.
   The movement is pro-Cuban and smaller than the Shining Path,
which considers Cuba, as well as the Soviet Union and China,
traitors to true Marxism.
   Police said Magnolia Zuniga, 30, a nursing student, was shot in
the head by guerrillas when she answered their knock at her door.
She was arrested two years ago as a suspected terrorist but later
released.
</TEXT>
