<FIRST>r a AM-BrownSurgery     07-06 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brown Surgery,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Kentucky Governor Undergoes Open Heart Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. John Y. Brown Jr. underwent
quadruple-bypass heart surgery Thursday, and was in critical
condition in an intensive care unit, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   Brown underwent open-heart surgery from 9 a.m. to 2:30 p.m. at
Humana Hospital-Audubon, according to a news release by hospital
spokeswoman Denise Damron.
   Tests conducted Wednesday determined there was blockage in blood
vessels feeding Brown's heart, and the operation bypassed four of
those vessels.
   Brown is expected to remain in intensive care for several days,
the statement said. It is routine for patients who have undergone
this kind of operation to be listed in critical condition.
   Brown was hospitalized in Florida last week after suffering chest
pains, and was transferred to Audubon on Tuesday.
   He was in good spirits Wednesday, and spent part of the day with
his wife, former ``CBS Morning News'' host Phyllis George Brown and
family members, the statement said.
   Brown underwent triple-bypass heart surgery in 1983 at the end of
his four-year term as governor and developed serious lung
complications.
   He withdrew from his race against Walter ``Dee'' Huddleston for
the U.S. Senate in 1984, saying it was because of doctors' orders.
   In 1987, he finished second in the Democratic gubernatorial
primary to Wallace Wilkinson.
</TEXT>
