<FIRST>r a AM-DalaiLama     07-06 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dalai Lama,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dalai Lama Celebrates Birthday in Malibu</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dalai Lama, the religious leader revered
by most Tibetans as a living Buddha, celebrated his 54th birthday
Thursday with a party in Malibu.
   The exiled Tibetan religious leader is on a 17-day visit to Los
Angeles to address followers of the 2,500-year-old faith and conduct
religious ceremonies. Though respected by all Buddhists, to some
followers he carries no religious authority.
   A group of Buddhist monks and others celebrated his birthday with
birthday cake, a tree planting ceremony, luncheon and traditional
Tibetan dancing in Malibu.
   ``We even sang `Happy Birthday' to the Dalai Lama, although they
don't do that in Tibet,'' said Betty Rogers, spokeswoman for the
religious leader's trip to Los Angeles.
   While the Tibetan people traditionally celebrate all birthdays on
the first of every new year, they mark the Dalai Lama's birthday on
July 6, Ms. Rogers said.
   Tenzin Gyatso, who is the 14th Dalai Lama of Tibet, spoke on
Wednesday to a group of religious leaders from various faiths,
discussing how Buddhists can adapt to life in the United States.
   ``Each new place, new environment, new culture, Buddhism has
adjusted to new environments,'' said the Dalai Lama. ``Eventually,
Western Buddhism, American Buddhism, and English Buddhism will
happen in the same sense.''
   The Dalai Lama advised his listeners to preserve their values,
but to ``be aware of the other culture's values, too.''
   The Dalai Lama is revered as the the 14th reincarnation of a
founder of the Mahayana wing of Buddhism and has spent the last 30
years in the Himalayas, where he was offered sanctuary after fleeing
his native Tibet because of military threats by the Chinese
government.
</TEXT>
