<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Expulsion     07-06 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Expulsion,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Election Observer Expelled</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DORALISA PILARTE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista government has ordered
the expulsion of a U.S. citizen from the human rights group Freedom
House sent here to observe elections, officials and the man being
expelled said Thursday.
   Nicaragua has said it would accept such observers to confirm that
the process leading to general elections next Feb. 25 will be free
and fair.
   Nicaraguan-born Antonio Ibarra Rojas, 40, a sociology professor
at Dubuque University in Iowa, said he came here June 11 to report
for Freedom House on the arrival of Alfredo Cesar and a group of
followers.
   Cesar is the first active member of the Miami-based Nicaraguan
Resistance directorate to return home to join the political process.
The Resistance is an umbrella organization of U.S.-supported
guerrilla and exiled political groups opposed to the Sandinistas.
   Ibarra, a naturalized U.S. citizen who writes for Freedom at
Issue, the official Freedom House magazine, said he applied on
Wednesday for accreditation as an electoral observer with the
Supreme Electoral Council.
   Hours later, Ibarra said, immigration officials took him by force
from his home to immigration offices and accused him of overstaying
his 30-day permit.
   ``I showed them an approved extension for 75 more days,'' Ibarra
said. ``They they said I had changed addresses without notifying
them.
   ``These are just bad excuses,'' Ibarra said. ``If they are so
open and are going to have free elections, why don't they want
independent observers?
   ``At no time have we come to sabotage or boycott the electoral
process.''
   Ibarra said he was consulting his lawyer to appeal the expulsion
order.
   Interior Ministry spokeswoman Patricia Orozco said immigration
authorities visited addresses Ibarra gave them and failed to find
him.
   ``He also had stated `business' as his motive for visiting
Nicaragua. But he is doing journalistic work, and that's another
kind of business,'' she said.
   Freedom House was an observer in 1984 elections won by the
Sandinista National Liberation Front. The leftist Sandinistas came
to power in a popular revolution that ousted U.S.-backed dictator
Anastasio Somoza in July 1979.
</TEXT>
