<FIRST>u a AM-FiresRdp     07-06 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fires Rdp,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fires Rage In Utah, Wyoming and California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA BIBBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Utah firefighters sweltered in 100-degree heat Thursday as they
struggled to contain a 7,000-acre wildfire and forest officials in
Wyoming trying to douse a 2,400-acre blaze worried about weekend
weather forecasts of dry lightning.
   In California, flames that scorched 1,100 acres of thick brush
raged untamed in rugged terrain near the Mexican border, but
firefighters were gaining on the last in a series of wildfires in
the southern part of the state.
   Fires also charred land in Colorado, Georgia and Alaska.
   Utah firefighters, reinforced by fresh crews, labored in the
100-degree heat to hand dig miles of fire lines on steep, tinder-dry
terrain in an effort to stop blazes that have blackened 11,000 acres
of eastern forests.
   Most of the fires still raged out of control, but an army of 200
firefighters was slowly gaining the upper hand on the 7,000-acre
Diamond Peak blaze, the largest uncontrolled fire in the lower 48
states on Thursday, said Mary Plumb, spokeswoman for the Bureau of
Land Management's Moab district.
   The Diamond Peak fire, located about 20 miles west of the
Utah-Colorado border, was 40 percent contained Thursday.
   Officials expect to fully contain the fire by Saturday, Plumb
said.
   In Bridger-Teton National Forest, Wyo., about 340 firefighters
and a helicopter battled a fire that started Tuesday and grew from
2,200 acres to 2,400 acres Thursday in warm, breezy weather.
   The fire about 40 miles southeast of Pinedale and 150 miles
southeast of Yellowstone National Park was 5 percent contained, said
forest spokesman Ed Christian. Officials do not expect to contain
the fire until July 13.
   The weekend weather forecast made the potential for further fire
danger ``very high,'' Christian said. He added that the National
Weather Service was predicting record high temperatures in
northwestern Wyoming for the rest of the week.
   The forest fires across the West were creating a shortage of
firefighters and equipment. Christian said forest officials have
ordered another 160 firefighters and seven helicopters to help fight
the Bridger-Teton fire, but he did not know when they would arrive.
   In California, nearly 5,000 acres have been blackened by an
unrelenting string of fires from Ventura County northwest of Los
Angeles to San Diego County, 160 miles to the southeast.
   Five air tankers and three helicopters bombarding the latest
blaze with water and fire retardants supported 800 firefighters on
the ground as the fire roared unabated through steep, rocky canyons
40 miles east of San Diego.
   A quarter of the fire area was surrounded and another 25 percent
was declared under control at midday, officials said.
   In Colorado, slightly cooler weather and some cloud cover over
the central mountains gave firefighters hope as they continued to
mop up fires in the Colorado mountains.
   In Georgia, a 500-acre fire that broke out when lightning struck
in the Okefenokee Swamp in Fargo was 15 percent contained and three
work crews tried to put out the rest, said Chris Zajicek, fire
information officer for the U.S. Forest Service.
   A prolonged stretch of warm, dry weather in the southern half of
mainland Alaska put the 1989 wildfire season in full swing, state
officials said.
   Thirty-three crews either were in the field or on their way to
fires in six areas, according to Bill Beebe, the state's fire
information officer.
   The worst fires were in the McGrath area. Lightning was suspected
as the cause of a fire that had spread to 9,000 acres near Swinging
Dome near the mostly abandoned mining community of Flat.
   Three fires in steep terrain near Crooked Creek grew from 840
acres to more than 2,000 acres Tuesday night. Beebe said 17 crews
were working the Crooked Creek blazes. Another fire of unknown size
is burning in the DeCourcy Mountain Mine area.
</TEXT>
