<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 2248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-ASEAN-China     07-06 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ASEAN-China,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Democracies Reassessing China Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major Western democracies
Thursday condemned China's crackdown on political dissent, and Japan
urged China's leadership to heed world opinion.
   The foreign ministers of Australia, Canada, the United States,
Japan, and New Zealand denounced the Chinese army's killing of
unarmed civilians in Beijing when the crackdown on the pro-democracy
movement began the night of June 3-4.
   Their speeches began three days of annual talks with their allies
of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, where fears and
suspicions of northern neighbor China remain deep in some quarters.
   A speech on behalf of the sixth dialogue partner, the European
Community, did not mention China, a topic that was added to the
meeting's agenda after the crackdown began.
   ``The recent formation of a new leadership seems to indicate that
China is in a process leading towards settlement of the domestic
situation one way or another,'' said Foreign Minister Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka of Japan.
   ``Japan earnestly hopes that the new Chinese leadership will heed
the international opinion and will govern in a spirit of
reconciliation and restraint, well aware of its position in the
international community and particularly, of the important role it
plays in the Asia-Pacific region,'' he said.
   ``We deeply deplore the fact tht so many lives were lost by the
use of military force,'' Mitsuzuka said.
   The Chinese government has said that 200 to 300 people were
killed when thousands of soldiers marched on Beijing and drove
pro-democracy protesters from Tiananmen Square. Chinese witnesses
and Western intelligence sources said the death toll may have been
as high as 3,000.
   U.S. Secretary of State James Baker III spoke of a ``new order''
in East Asia in which democracy and free enterprise are supplanting
communism.
   ``The going will not always be smooth, as events in China have
proven,'' he said. ``But to stand in the way of necessary, historic
change, as we have seen to our revulsion in China, is to turn one's
back on the future.''
   Foreign Minister Russell Marshall of New Zealand said the
brutality in Beijing was shocking in light of China's progress in
raising living standards and encouraging democratic values.
   ``We recognize fully that there are laws and practices in other
states that are the legitimate internal business of those states,
and none of our business,'' he said. ``But at the same time, there
must be a balance between the rights of sovereign states and the
internationally recognized human rights of ordinary citizens.''
   Japan's Foreign Ministry spokesman, Seiichi Kondo, told reporters
that some delegates at Thursday's talks spoke strongly about human
rights in discussing recent events in China.
   He said Mitsuzaka told these delegates it was not appropriate to
isolate China and urged them to take a longer view.
   ``We should not push China into a corner as it would be
counter-productive,'' Kondo said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
