<DOCNO> AP890706-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 2253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-ASEAN-Cambodia     07-06 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ASEAN-Cambodia,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Japan Urge Cambodia's Fighting Factions To Share Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Baker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Secretary of State James
Baker III and Japanese Foreign Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka spoke of
the risk of prolonged civil war on Thursday in urging Cambodia's
warring factions to share power.
   Mitsuzuka proposed an international body for Cambodia's postwar
reconstruction.
   Their statements came in speeches at the start of annual talks
between members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations and
their Western ``dialogue partners.''
   ASEAN comprises the non-communist, rapidly developing nations of
Brunei, Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia, the Philippines and
Indonesia. The dialogue partners are the United States, Japan,
Australia, Canada, New Zealand and the 12-nation European Community.
   Both groups support a three-party guerrilla coalition fighting
Vietnamese troops who invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and the forces
of the Hanoi-installed government.
   Baker said Vietnam's plan to withdraw all troops by Sept. 30 has
``given new urgency'' to the search for peace. ``The danger of a new
cycle of civil war is very real,'' he said.
   He said Prince Norodom Sihanouk, former head of state in Cambodia
and now leader of non-communist guerrillas, is central to U.S. and
ASEAN goals of a comprehensive stable settlement, including
guarantees against the return to exclusive power of the brutal Khmer
Rouge.
   The Khmer Rouge killed perhaps a million Cambodians before it was
ousted by Vietnam's invasion. It is now the largest guerrilla unit
in Sihanouk's coalition.
   Both the Khmer Rouge and the Vietnamese invaders are communist.
   Appearing to give the pro-Vietnamese government of Premier Hun
Sen more stature than in previous official U.S. statements, Baker
said:
   ``Prince Sihanouk's efforts to work out a power-sharing agreement
with the Hanoi-sponsored Hun Sen regime are crucial to the
achievement of a viable political accord, and we urge our ASEAN
friends to use their unity to strengthen the prince's position as he
seeks to advance the process of national reconciliation.''
   The main barrier is refusal of the pro-Vietnam government to let
the Khmer Rouge join in a provisional four-party government. The
Khmer Rouge reportedly is storing arms for a major push once the
Vietnamese soldiers leave.
   Baker said Washington ``will stay engaged'' in the region as it
faces these and other challenges. ``East Asia is integral to
America's future,'' he said.
   Mitsuzuka also opposed what ASEAN officials now commonly refer to
as an ``Afghanistan-type solution.''
   He said that whatever the settlement, ``It cannot be accepted in
such an unstable character as might prolong the civil war in
Cambodia.''
   Mitsuzuka said it was imperative for the Cambodian parties to
work out a solution to ``forming a provisional politica plan for
implementation of the future general election, not only for the
internal stability of Cambodia but also for the security of all
neighboring countries.''
   He said reconstruction of postwar Cambodia will be a major issue
at the international conference on Cambodia in Paris.
   ``Japan believes we should all now consider establishment of an
International Committee for the Reconstruction of Cambodia as an
international cooperative framework,'' he said.
   He said that ``the very first thing this committee has to do may
be to dispatch a fact-finding mission.''
   Edwige Avice, France's deputy foreign minister and chief EEC
delegate here, said the international conference on Cambodia
probably will be held July 30. She said Sihanouk and his guerrilla
allies will hold talks in France July 24-25 with Hun Sen.
   Japanese Foreign Ministry spokesman Seiichi Kondo said all
participants in Thursday's talks expressed support for Japan's
proposal on forming the body to rebuild Cambodia.
   Sihanouk earlier had sent the ASEAN ministers a letter in which
he wrote of the danger of a partial settlement.
   The statesmen here will discuss Cambodia and other issues
including trade friction and new Asia-Pacific economic cooperation
in sessions from Thursday to Saturday.
</TEXT>
