<FIRST>u i AM-Korea-CopterCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0747 07-06 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Copter Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Soldier Killed in Copter Crach, Korean Killed at Firing
Range</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with details of helicopter crash and death,
injuries at firing range; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A UH-60 Blackhawk helicopter crashed
east of Seoul on Thursday night, killing one U.S. soldier and
injuring two others, U.S. military officials said.
   The military also said a Korean civilian was killed and two
others injured Thursday while U.S. troops were training at a firing
range.
   The helicopter was on a routine night training mission when it
crashed about 10 p.m. Thursday about 8{ miles east of Seoul,
according to a statement the military issued Friday.
   It said the cause of the crash was under investigation.
   The Korean newspaper Hankook Ilbo, quoting witnesses, said the
aircraft went down when its blades hit a high voltage power line
about 500 yards above the ground.
   A unidentified Korean civilian was burned and slightly injured
when he tried to pull the injured soldiers from the fiery wreckage,
witnesses said.
   The names of the dead and injured were expected to be released
later in the day after their families were notified, a military
spokesman said.
   The aircraft belonged to the 2nd Infantry Division's 2nd
Battalion, 2nd Aviation, according to the statement. The 2nd
Infantry Division is the only U.S. infantry unit stationed in South
Korea and includes about 15,000 troops.
   The death and injuries at the firing range also involved units
from the 2nd Infantry and occurred about 1{ miles south of the
demilitarized zone that separates communist North Korea from South
Korea, a military spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   The spokesman said no Americans were hurt.
   A military statement said the accident occurred during a routine
training mission while units were using artillery fire. The
spokesman said the firing range is surrounded by a buffer zone that
is off-limits to civilians.
   South Korean and U.S. military authorities were investigating,
according to the statement.
   The injured Koreans, flown to the 121st Evacuation Hospital at
the 8th U.S. Army Headquarters in Seoul, were identified as Cho
Nam-min, 73, and Shin Dong-sun, 71. Mrs. Shin was treated and
released.
   The name of the dead person was not released.
</TEXT>
