<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--MolecularWires Adv10   07-06 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Molecular Wires, Adv 10,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, July 10, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>UNM Researchers Discover Molecular Wires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT MYGATT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wires as thick as molecules, ``grown''
in rocks containing microscopic channels, could yield tiny,
three-dimensional chips that could be tightly packed into small
computers, a researcher says.
   ``We cannot claim yet that we have electron flow along these
chains, but we have essentially done the first step to make these
systems,'' said Thomas Bein, a University of New Mexico chemist who,
with doctoral candidate Patricia Enzel, grew chains of organic
molecules in the channels of a mineral called zeolite.
   The channels in zeolite are 3 to 12 angstroms wide. An angstrom
is one-tenth of a billionth of a meter. Etched wires on silicon
microchips are about 1 micron, one-25,000th of an inch or one
millionth of a meter.
   Crystals of zeolite _ Greek for ``boiling stone'' _ are believed
to form in volcanoes under high heat and pressure, Bein said. ``They
seem to boil because they contain water in their channels in
nature.''
   Synthetic zeolites are used as filters in such industries as oil
refining because they have a large surface area and their channels
can either absorb or reject different-sized molecules, he said.
   ``I think he's made a substantial advance here,'' said Mark
Ratner, a Northwestern University chemist who had heard about, but
had not read, Bein's research. He described it as ``growing a wire
in a mineral.''
   ``One of the problems has been how to get these things to
structure properly because they are floppy, kind of like boiled
spaghetti,'' Ratner said. ``The advantage of using zeolites is they
are stones _ they're hard, rigid, well-designed structures with
pores in them.''
   If molecular wires can be grown in zeolites, ``you would be
solving the addressing problems, telling the wire where to go,'' he
said.
   Bein said he and Enzel used synthetic zeolite crystals, each
about 1 micron in diameter _ in their research, which was presented
during an April meeting of the American Chemical Society in Dallas.
   Thousands of crystals, in the form of a powder, where placed in a
quartz reactor the size of a large cigar and heated to 400 degrees
Celsius to remove water vapor from the channels. The crystals were
cooled in a vacuum to keep the channels empty so vapors of an
organic substance called aniline could be used to coat the interior
walls of the channels. An oxidant caused the aniline to link into
chains of polyaniline, which is known to conduct electricity.
   ``Other conducting polymers also have been encapsulated in the
crystals, including polypyrrole and polythiophene,'' Bein said. More
research is needed to determine the length of the linked molecules
so a current can be hooked up.
   Some zeolites contain parallel channels, while others contain
networks of channels like hallways and rooms, Bein said. ``We have a
whole shopping list of about 200 structures with different pore
sizes and types of networks.''
   A step after controlling the chemistry in the channels and
determining electrical flow would be to ``introduce active
components like storage of bits or switching ...'' and then to ``try
to put information in and get information out of these assemblies,''
Bein said. ``Then we could create a very dense computer at a
molecular level, and that's what excites us so much.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 10</NOTE>
