<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-06 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0869</SECOND>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Late-June car and light truck sales plummeted 20
percent compared with strong sales in the same period last year.
   The average sales rate among the eight U.S.-based automakers for
the June 21-30 period this year was 26,811 vehicles a day, down from
a daily rate of 33,495 during the same time last year, automakers
reported Wednesday.
   Among the Big Three automakers, Chrysler Corp.'s car sales were
off 28.6 percent, General Motors Corp.'s were down 23.4 percent and
Ford Motor Co.'s were off 22.5 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC nations boosted their crude oil
production in June to its highest level so far this year, surpassing
the cartel's self-imposed output ceiling.
   The International Energy Agency said Wednesday in its Monthly Oil
Market Report that the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries pumped about 21.3 million barrels of crude a day last
month, up 200,000 barrels a day from May.
   The rise lifted second-quarter production to about 21 million
barrels a day, topping OPEC's self-imposed 19.5 million-barrel daily
production limit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boyd L. Jefferies, the one-time workaholic
stockbroker snared in the Ivan Boesky insider trading scandal, is
scheduled to be sentenced Friday for securities fraud.
   Based on his testimony in two key Wall Street fraud trials,
comments of satisfied prosecutors and Boesky's own three-year jail
term, Jefferies was expected to get far less than the maximum
possible 10 years in prison, attorneys and legal scholars said
Wednesday.
   Jefferies, 58, agreed to plead guilty in March 1987 to two
felonies, cooperate in other cases, resign from his brokerage and
stay out of the securities business for five years. In addition to
prison, he faces fines up to $500,000.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A planned $5.53 billion buyout of Newmont Mining
Corp.'s biggest shareholder by Hanson Trust PLC likely will mean
that nearly half of Newmont's stock will be up for sale soon.
   Analysts said Wednesday that Hanson had a history of breaking up
companies it had acquired, in order to keep the businesses it
considered most useful.
   Hanson, a British conglomerate, announced late Tuesday that it
had tentatively agreed to acquire Consolidated Gold Fields PLC,
which owns a 49.3 percent stake in Newmont, the biggest U.S. gold
producer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge has given Eastern
Airlines two more weeks to complete a reorganization plan before
competing proposals may be filed.
   At a court hearing Wednesday, Judge Burton R. Lifland granted the
joint request by Eastern and its major creditors for an extension of
the company's exclusivity period through July 21.
   Companies like Eastern, seeking Chapter 11 bankrutcy protection,
have the sole right to submit a reorganization plan to the court
during the first 120 days of its case, after which other parties may
propose plans. Eastern's exclusivity period was to end Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Time Inc. attorney has revealed that
Cablevision Systems Corp. was considering making an offer for the
media giant.
   Attorney Lawrence Hamermesh told Delaware Chancery Court Judge
William Allen in a letter dated July 3, ``Cablevision is actively
considering a bid for Time.''
   A Cablevision spokesman, David Carey, said Wednesday the company
had no comment on the letter. Time spokesman Edward Adler said his
company _ which is trying to fend off a $12.2 billion hostile bid
from Paramount Communications Corp. _ also would not comment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capital Cities-ABC Inc. has been granted a
permanent waiver to Federal Communications Commission rules that
could have forced the company to sell multimillion-dollar radio and
television stations in New York, Los Angeles, Chicago and San
Francisco.
   The commission granted Capital Cities' request that it be allowed
to own WABC-TV, WABC-AM and WPLJ-FM in New York City; WLS-TV, WLS-AM
and WYTZ-FM, Chicago; KABC-TV, KABC-AM and KLOS-FM, Los Angeles; and
KGO-TV and KGO-AM, San Francisco.
   In March, the FCC loosened cross-ownership rules that prohibited
a company from owning both a radio station and a television station
in the same television ``market,'' such as in the New York or Los
Angeles metropolitan areas.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CROOKSTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Migrant farm workers, drawn by the hope
of work and good pay, have poured into the Red River Valley this
year in what may be record numbers, but what they've found is a
shortage of work and housing.
   City officials acknowledge the housing market is tight. But they
say providing new housing is beyond the community's means and will
require state and federal assistance.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rebounded Wednesday, with the Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials closing up 3.79 points at 2,456.56.
   The dollar ended sharply lower against all key currencies in
choppy trading, while gold prices rallied to two-month highs and
bond prices fell.
   Corn, soybean and oat futures prices soared their permitted daily
limits amid crop-threatening weather forecasts. Prices for future
deliveries of wheat, cattle, coffee, precious metals, and crude oil
also rose sharply.
