<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ConsumerConfidence     07-06 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consumer Confidence,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Optimism Continues, Conference Board Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high level of consumer optimism persists
despite indications of slower economic growth, the Conference Board
says.
   The board said Wednesday that its Consumer Confidence Index was
117.5 in June, little changed from May. Consumer confidence has held
at a relatively high level since late last year, although buying
plans are declining, according to the Conference Board, a business
research group.
   The monthly survey covered 5,000 households throughout the United
States.
   It found a small decline, to 28.7 percent, in the number of
consumers who believe current business conditions are good, and a
slight rise, to 17 percent, in those who believe they are bad.
   Consumer opinion continues to be positive on the issue of job
availability, the survey showed.
   ``Job security and the sustained buying power of the weekly
paycheck are contributing substantially to the consumer's sense of
well being,'' said Fabian Linden, executive director of the
Conference Board's Consumer Research Center. ``As long as the
consumer remains in good spirits, there is faint likelihood that the
economy will take a bad turn.''
   With the big spring car sales over, households planning to buy an
automobile in the next six months dropped to 6.5 percent in June
from 8.5 percent in May. Around 3.2 percent of the respondents plan
to purchase a home, down from 3.4 percent a month earlier.
   The survey also noted a mild loss of interest in buying major
appliances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
