<DOCNO> AP890706-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   07-06 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Gives Eastern Two-Week Extension To File Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines has won a two-week
reprieve for finishing a reorganization plan before competing
proposals may be filed.
   At a hearing Wednesday, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland
granted the joint request by Eastern and its major creditors for an
extension of the company's exclusivity period through July 21, after
they indicated they were nearing agreement on a restructuring plan.
   ``We're making progress, although we're not there at the
moment,'' said Joel Zweibel, the attorney representing Eastern's
major creditors.
   In granting the request, Lifland said, ``There have been few
windows of opportunity in this case. I certainly view the present
period as a real window of opportunity.''
   Miami-based Eastern filed for bankruptcy protection from
creditors on March 9, five days after the start of a crippling
strike by the Machinists union that has been supported by most
pilots and flight attendants.
   A company seeking Chapter 11 protection has the sole right to
submit a reorganization plan to the court during the first 120 days
of its case, after which other parties may propose plans. Eastern's
exclusivity period had been due to end Friday.
   Eastern wants to rebuild as a smaller carrier and pay off
creditors with the proceeds of about $1.8 billion in asset sales,
including several that already have been approved by the bankruptcy
court.
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp., said
Friday that only technical differences regarding the plan remained
between the company and its creditors.
   But Zweibel said after the hearing that two ``substantive''
issues, which he declined to identify, still were unresolved.
   ``We hope that they'll be resolved within two weeks,'' Zweibel
said in an interview. He said the speed of Eastern and the creditors
in devising a reorganization plan was ``unprecedented'' for a large,
complex bankruptcy case.
   Also at the hearing, David I. Shapiro, the court-appointed
bankruptcy examiner for Eastern, said contract negotiations were
continuing in Washington between the airline's management and its
striking pilots, as ordered by Lifland.
   For about a week, Shapiro has been trying to get the two sides to
reach an agreement that would end the pilots' walkout. He did not
disclose details of the talks, saying only that they would be
broadened Monday to include Eastern's other two striking unions.
   But sources close to the talks, speaking anonymously, said little
progress has been made and only minor issues have been addressed so
far.
   Pilots union officials insist that job-security provisions are
necessary for an agreement. Eastern recently sought bankruptcy court
permission to cancel its contract with the Air Line Pilots
Association and to impose about $50 million in wage and benefit
concessions. The airline also is seeking changes in work policies
that would allow it to increase pilots' flying hours.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890706-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-OPEC     07-06 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OPEC,0599</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Estimates: OPEC Production Rose To Year's Highest In June</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC nations boosted their crude oil
production in June to its highest level so far this year, surpassing
the cartel's self-imposed output ceiling, according to estimates.
   The International Energy Agency said Wednesday in its Monthly Oil
Market Report that the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries pumped about 21.3 million barrels of crude a day last
month, up 200,000 barrels a day from May.
   The rise lifted second-quarter production to about 21 million
barrels a day, topping OPEC's self-imposed 18.5 million-barrel daily
production limit. It also was the highest for the April-June period
since the 23.2 million barrels a day produced in that quarter of
1981.
   The OPEC nations last month set their production ceiling at 19.5
million barrels a day for the last six months of the year _ up 1
million barrels from the first-half quota _ in an attempt to support
an $18 benchmark price for a ``basket'' of Middle Eastern crude oil.
The basket price is a composite of seven different crudes.
   OPEC's argument is that by giving member countries higher quotas,
they will be less likely to cheat and exceed the limits.
   The ministers agreed to divide up the extra sales proportionately
among all members, angering Kuwait and others that wanted a bigger
share of the increase. Kuwait has stated it would not be bound by
its individual quota.
   The energy agency _ a body of the multi-nation Organization of
Economic Cooperation and Development _ predicted demand for OPEC oil
would be about 20.9 million barrels a day in the second half of the
year, about the same as the May forecast.
   Michael Rothman, senior energy analyst at Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets in New York, predicted OPEC in July would produce 20.5
million to 21 million barrels a day.
   He said oil stocks already were high and demand was likely to
slow, which could keep prices under downward pressure.
   The average price for a basket of seven crudes monitored by OPEC
was $17.62 a barrel at the end of June, sharply up from $12.34 at
the end of November.
   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, closed at $20.79 a barrel Wednesday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, up 52 cents from Friday's close. The market was
closed Monday and Tuesday for the Independence Day holiday.
   OPEC has said data from nearly all its members shows they
generally are adhering to their targets. The organization measures a
nation's quota by figuring crude production and the amount of oil
put into, or drawn out, of stocks.
   The energy agency estimated Saudi Arabia, the world's No. 1 crude
exporter, produced 4.8 million barrels a day in June, compared with
its OPEC quota of 4.5 million barrels a day.
   ``The major increase was in Iran, which was up 300,000 barrels a
day (from May) to 2.8 million barrels a day (in June),'' the report
stated.
   Iraq, like Iran, pumped about 2.8 million barrels a day, compared
with a quota of 2.64 million barrels.
   Kuwait produced an estimated 1.6 million barrels a day and the
United Arab Emirates 1.7 million barrels, compared with their
targets of about 1 million barrels a day.
   Nigeria produced an estimated 1.6 million barrels a day;
Venezuela, 1.7 million barrels; Ecuador, 300,000 barrels; Indonesia,
1.2 million barrels; Algeria, 700,000 barrels; Gabon, 200,000
barrels, and Libya, 1 million barrels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890706-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0213EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time Bjt   07-06 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time, Bjt,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cablevision Said To Be Considering Time Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cablevision Systems Corp. has been mentioned as
another possible bidder for Time Inc., further complicating the
media giant's plan to merge with Warner Communications Inc.
   Time attorney Lawrence Hamermesh told Delaware Chancery Court
Judge William Allen in a letter dated July 3 that ``Cablevision is
actively considering a bid for Time.'' The letter was disclosed
Wednesday.
   A Cablevision spokesman, David Carey, said the cable-TV company
had no comment on the letter. Time spokesman Edward Adler said his
company _ which is trying to fend off a $12.2 billion hostile bid
from Paramount Communications Corp. _ also would not comment.
   The letter was filed with the Delaware court, which is
considering suits brought against Time by Paramount and a group of
Time shareholders that includes Cablevision and Texas investor
Robert Bass.
   The Time board has rejected Paramount's $200-a-share bid as
inadquate and too dependent upon contingencies to be viable. The
company is trying to preserve its planned merger with Warner and has
launched a $14 billion tender offer for that movie and publishing
concern.
   Paramount sued Time in Delaware to force Time's board of
directors to consider its offer.
   Time stock rose $1.25 a share to $155.25 in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading Wednesday. Warner was up 87{ cents to
$61.25 a share and Paramount slipped 87{ cents to $59.37{ a share,
also in NYSE trading.
   Cablevision, which is based in Woodbury, N.Y., was off 87{ cents
to $41.75 a share on the American Stock Exchange.
   Some analysts who have followed the three-way struggle for Time
were skeptical about a bid from Cablevision, one of the nation's
largest operators of cable-TV systems and a provider of cable
programming.
   Fred Anschel, of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., noted that
Cablevision already has a heavy debt burden and likely could not
handle the high leverage needed to complete a buyout of Time.
   But Frederick Moran, an analyst who follows Cablevision for Moran
&amp; Associates Inc., said, ``If they do it, I would expect them to be
a very tough player.''
   Moran acknowledged that Cablevision's debt load was a concern,
but said the company likely would have a partner if it does make a
bid. ``That makes the situation doable,'' he said.
   It was not immediately known whether Bass was considering joining
Cablevision in a possible bid. David Bonderman, a Bass spokesman,
did not return a telephone call seeking comment and Bonderman's
secretary said it was the company's policy not to comment on
possible bids.
   However, Anschel said, any new bids for Time would be academic
before the Delaware court ruled on the Paramount suit.
   Paramount is seeking to force the Time board to seriously
consider its offer on grounds that the board effectively put the
company up for sale when it agreed to merge with Warner in a
stock-swap earlier this year.
   Under Delaware law, if a company has put itself up for sale, it
must consider whatever bids will give shareholders the maximum
value. If the court rules in Paramount's favor, Time will be
hard-pressed to ignore Paramount's bid, which is $74 higher than the
price at which Time stock traded before Paramount announced its
original $10.7 billion, or $175 a share, bid June 6.
   Allen, the Delaware judge, will hear arguments in the case
Tuesday and is expected to rule shortly afterward. However, any
decision undoubtedly will be appealed to the Delaware Supreme Court.
   Meanwhile Wednesday, Paramount extended the expiration date of
its offer for Time until July 28. The offer had been scheduled to
expire Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890706-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0100EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoeingInspections     07-06 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Boeing Inspections,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inspection of 727s Ordered After Discovery of Unusual Crack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has ordered
rigorous inspections of the 47 oldest Boeing 727s following the
discovery of an unusual 20-inch crack on a United Airlines jet,
officials said Wednesday.
   United inspectors found the crack June 26 during a routine
maintenance inspection and notified Boeing Co. and the FAA
immediately, said United spokesman Rob Doughty in a telephone
interview from Chicago.
   The crack started inside the plane and broke through the surface.
The trijet has been repaired and is back in service, officials said.
   The cracked portion was removed for examination by Boeing
specialists. Preliminary indications suggested the cause was metal
fatigue, FAA officials said.
   The 727, no longer manufactured, was the all-time best-selling
commercial jet before being supplanted by the Boeing 737. Boeing
spokesman Tom Cole said there are 1,765 of the 727s in service.
   Structural problems in older aircraft usually can be anticipated,
often through computers, but the one in the United jet ``was found
in an unexpected place,'' Cole said.
   The FAA order requires the removal of some of the seats and
removal of sidewall linings and insulation to gain access to the
inside of the fuselage skin, Cole said.
   Without corrective measures, cracks in the fuselage skin could
result in rapid decompression of the airplane in flight, officials
said.
   The FAA issued an airworthiness directive Friday for internal
inspection of the fuselage skin lap joints and for repair of cracks
as needed by July 15 for the 47 oldest Boeing 727s, with findings to
be reported back to the agency.
   The directive was distributed by telegram, a method used in cases
considered urgent.
   ``The crack is a serious discovery, and we responded to it in a
serious way,'' Steven B. Wallace, acting manager of the FAA's
Transport Airplane Directorate, told KIRO Television.
   Inspections were ordered only for the 47 oldest 727s because the
skin was made thicker on later models, Cole said. He added that he
did not know which airlines or whether any foreign carriers were
affected.
   Most of the first 47 Boeing 727s were delivered to U.S. carriers
in 1963 and 1964, but many later were sold to other airlines, Cole
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
