<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales     07-06 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auto Sales Down in June, Sparking Concern About Late-Season Glut</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the 1989 automotive model year begins its last
three months, analysts are wondering what manufacturers will do to
get rid of inventories before the next model year gets under way in
October.
   ``It's obvious that incentives aren't working,'' analyst Kathleen
Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International Inc. of New York said
Wednesday after automakers reported a 20 percent decline in vehicle
sales last month compared with June 1988.
   But the comparison was colored by strong sales last June that
helped 1988 become the second-best year in automotive history.
   ``Because June of 1988 was such an exceptionally strong sales
month, unfavorable year-to-year comparisons were anticipated,'' said
Ford Motor Co. sales Vice President Robert Rewey. ``We continue to
be encouraged by the underlying strength of the U.S. economy.
Consumer confidence remains strong, buoyed by record employment
levels and moderating inflation.''
   Ford led the way in late March with a new incentive package that
featured financing as low as 2.9 percent. General Motors Corp. and
Chrysler Corp. followed the move to new consumer enticements, and
since then the Big Three have expanded their programs.
   But it appears that the incentives, designed to spark car sales
this spring and summer, didn't do the trick.
   The average sales rate among the eight automakers with U.S.
plants for the June 21-30 period this year was 26,811 vehicles a
day, down from a daily rate of 33,495 during the same time last year.
   Among the Big Three, Chrysler's car sales were off 28.6 percent,
GM's were down 23.4 percent and Ford's declined 22.5 percent.
   For the month, with imported automakers' figures included, car
and truck sales were down 11.4 percent, going to a daily rate of
49,635 vehicles from a rate of 56,032 during June of last year.
   For the first half of 1989, sales of all domestic vehicles were
off 6.8 percent, with car sales falling 7.6 percent and truck sales
declining 5.3 percent.
   For months, analysts have predicted a downturn in sales. However,
automakers, with some adjustments, have kept up production, meaning
inventories have remained above usual levels.
   ``It's too late in the year for them to do anything other than to
say, `Gee, the market is very weak and we have to get the cars out
the door,''' said analyst Jeannette Garretty of the Bank of America
in San Francisco. ``I think they are at a loss at what to do there.
There can only be more financing deals, more rebates or giveaway
option packages.''
   Heaney agreed, adding that the next few months, as the model year
begins to draw to a close, will be worth watching.
   ``I want to see what they are going to do, what type of
incentives are they going to use to clear out these '89 models'' she
said.
   Added Garretty: ``Although consumer confidence is holding up, the
message is clearly being sent that the economy is slowing down. And
that's got to be on people's minds a bit.
   ``Something that is not showing up in the numbers directly is
that holders of adjustable-rate mortgages have seen a major increase
in their payments ... and that has eaten at their pocketbook.
   ``When it comes between the house and the car, the house is going
to win out.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
