<FIRST>d f PM-Wheeling-Pittsburgh     07-06 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wheeling-Pittsburgh,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Extends Pensions for Retirees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retirees of Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp.
will continue to receive payment of supplemental pension benefits
under a federal court ruling.
   U.S. District Judge Paul Simmons on Wednesday approved a request
to extend the payments, which expired last month for 965 retirees.
   The request was supported by the United Steelworkers, the company
and its major bankruptcy creditors. It was opposed by Pension
Benefit Guaranty Corp.
   At issue were monthly payments for 965 retirees and beneficiaries
that have been paid for about 2{ years under an agreement between
the company and the PBGC, the federally established insurer of
private pension plans.
   Simmons agreed with union and company contentions that the
elimination of the supplemental payments would cause ``severe and
irreparable'' harm to retirees. Those payments average about $230 a
month, said company spokesman Ray Johnson.
   Wheeling-Pittsburgh and the union argued that not paying the
benefits would damage labor relations at the company during a
critical point in its bankruptcy reorganization efforts.
   The pension issues and the labor issues are the last big hurdles
to the steel company's emergence from Chapter 11 protection of the
bankruptcy court, said Peter Shinevar, an attorney for the union.
</TEXT>
