<DOCNO> AP890706-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 0758EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GolfBallSuit     07-06 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Golf Ball Suit,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spalding Wins Golf Ball Suit Against Acushnet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spalding Sports Worldwide has won a golf ball
patent lawsuit against rival Acushnet Co. that could have
industrywide ramifications.
   U.S. District Court Judge Edward Harrington ruled that Acushnet
and its Titleist division infringed on Spalding's patent for a
Surlyn blend used in the company's top selling ball, Top Flite.
   The ruling Wednesday could affect the rest of the golf ball
industry because Spalding's attorney, George McAndrews, said that
the company intends to move ahead with patent lawsuits against
virtually all the golf ball makers in the country.
   Spalding filed the lawsuit against Acushnet in 1981. The two
companies control about 80 percent of the golf ball market, with
Spalding the leader.
   McAndrews refused to tell the Boston Herald the amount of damages
Spalding would seek from Acushnet, but he did say that it would be
``a significant portion'' of Acushnet's profits on balls that
infringed on Spalding patents.
   ``They had hundreds of millions of dollars in sales on those
balls,'' he said. ``We'll now try to determine what portion of that
was profit.''
   A spokesman for Acushnet said the decision would not affect the
company's day-to-day operations.
   ``We're disputing the decision, and we'll appeal it,'' said Wally
Uihlein, president and chief executive officer of Acushnet's
Titleist division.
   Uihlein told the newspaper that the company stopped using the
Surlyn blend four years ago.
   ``This decision has no effect on our day-to-day operations,'' he
said. ``We converted our balls in 1985, and converted again
recently. We maintain a pretty healthy balance sheet.''
   Spalding has six similar infringement suits pending against six
other golf ball companies: McGregor, Wilson, Hogan, McLaughlin &amp;
Son, Cayman and Exim, the Herald said. Those suits were reportedly
on hold pending the outcome of the Acushnet suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
