<FIRST>r f PM-Armstrong-Belzbergs     07-06 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Armstrong-Belzbergs,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Family Interested in Buying Armstrong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armstrong World Industries Inc. says it is
going to court to head off a Canadian family that has expressed an
interest in acquiring the interior furnishing company.
   Armstrong said Wednesday it was informed that the Belzberg family
of Vancouver, British Columbia, recently bought 9.85 percent of the
company's outstanding stock for $181 million through two affiliates.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission July 3,
the Belzbergs said they are considering making a proposal to acquire
the Lancaster, Pa.-based Armstrong, which had 1988 profits of $162.7
million on sales of $2.68 billion.
   Armstrong stock closed up $4.37{ at $47.87{ in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading Wednesday. It was the most actively
traded issue Wednesday, with 1,723,100 shares changing hands.
   Armstrong said Wednesday it was filing suit against the Belzbergs
in U.S. District Court seeking a judgment affirming the
constitutionality of the state's anti-takeover laws and the validity
of Armstrong's shareholders' rights plan.
   One of the Belzberg companies involved in the stock purchase said
in the SEC filing that it would file suit challenging the state's
anti-takeover laws and seeking to prevent Armstrong from
implementing its employee stock ownership plan.
   The ESOP, unveiled June 20, would put 12 percent of the company's
voting stock in employees' hands.
   Belzberg spokesman John Bowles declined to specify the Belzbergs'
next move. But he said they would seek regulatory clearance to
acquire 50 percent or more of Armstrong common stock.
   William W. Adams, Armstrong chairman and president, said in a
statement Wednesday that the company is not interested in selling
and has refused to meet with Belzberg representatives.
   ``We have no interest in meeting with the Belzbergs,'' Adams
said. ``The Belzberg family's interest in Armstrong has been
discussed with our board several times.
   ``Based on a review of, among other things, the Belzbergs' past
record and experiences to date, the board concluded that no
interests of any of the many groups closely associated with
Armstrong would be served by meeting with them.''
   In the SEC filing, the Belzbergs said that if they acquired
Armstrong, they intended to keep the company's floor coverings and
building products segments, while selling others, including the
furniture and industry products segments.
   The floor coverings and building products segments accounted for
a majority of the company's operating profit in 1988.
   The Belzbergs, through their affiliate companies, frequently have
invested in publicly held companies. Their flagship company is First
City Financial Corp. of Vancouver, an investment and holding company
which is 72 percent owned by the Belzbergs.
   The Belzberg family is headed by three brothers _ Hyman, 63,
Samuel, 61, and William, 56. The family originally was in the
furniture retail business. Today, Hyman Belzberg heads that activity
and Samuel is chief executive of First City. William is president of
Far West Savings &amp; Loan Association, Newport Beach, Calif.
   Its other main interests are real estate and investments in other
companies.
</TEXT>
