<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-06 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed in
active early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade as the
markets cooled a bit following a powerful rally in the previous
session.
   Wheat and oat futures were a little lower while corn and soybeans
were mixed.
   Corn and soybean futures advanced by their permitted daily limits
Wednesday, largely in reaction to forecasts for hot, dry weather in
the Midwest through the middle of next week.
   A new National Weather Service six-to-10-day outlook issued late
Wednesday predicted above-average temperatures in the region for all
of next week, but it also suggested the Corn Belt could see more
rain than traders had expected, and that was a moderating influence
in the early going.
   Extreme heat and dryness pose the greatest threat to the corn
crop, which is in the weather-sensitive pollination stage.
   Prospects for spotty showers and cooler temperatures in spring
wheat regions at the end of this week prompted some selling of wheat
futures.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 3 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $4.02{ a bushel; corn was 1} cents
lower to 2{ cents higher with July at $2.82 a bushel; oats were 1\
cents to 3 cents lower with July at $1.65 a bushel; soybeans were 4{
cents lower to 3{ cents higher with July at $7.72 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were lower in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .08 cent lower to .08 cent higher with August at
70.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .58 cent higher
with August at 80.82 cents a pound; live hogs were unchanged to .45
cent lower with July at 46.70 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .25 cent to 1.75 cents lower with July at 30.90 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Wednesday while pork futures were
sharply lower.
</TEXT>
