<FIRST>r f AM-SugarOutlook     07-06 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sugar Outlook,0143</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sugar Production Expected To Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department said Thursday that
U.S. sugar production should rebound sharply after last year's
drought.
   Total production in the 1989-90 crop year that will begin on
Sept. 1 is expected to be about 7.3 million tons, up 5.6 percent
from 1988-89 output estimated at 6.91 million tons.
   With improved growing conditions, sugar production in the coming
year could match or exceed the record level of 7.33 million tons in
1987-88, the department's Economic Research Service said.
   Beet sugar production, forecast at 3.9 million tons, would be up
11 percent from the drought-reduced level of 3.51 million tons this
season, the report said. Cane sugar, which rose to a record of just
under 3.4 million tons in 1988-89, is forecast at about the same in
1989-90.
</TEXT>
