<FIRST>r f BC-NestleSettlement 1stLd-Writethru   07-06 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Nestle Settlement, 1st Ld-Writethru,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nestle's Settles Formula Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf with 2 new grafs to ADD company comment; uppicks
4th graf pvs: Hanaway said ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nestle's Carnation Co. has agreed to pay
$90,000 to nine states to settle allegations it used misleading and
deceptive advertising to promote a new infant formula, Attorney
General Don Hanaway said Thursday.
   Under the settlement, Carnation will pay each state $10,000 and
halt advertising claims that its Good Start H.A. baby fomula is
hypoallergenic, Hanaway said.
   The states include Wisconsin, California, Illinois, Iowa,
Massachusetts, Minnesota, Missouri, New York and Texas.
   Tim F. Crull, president and chief executive officer of Carnation
Co., said the claims by the attorneys general were not supported by
the facts, but that Carnation agreed to the settlement to avoid a
costly, lengthy court case.
   ``We first used the term `hypoallergenic' to accurately and
concisely describe Good Start H.A. and its attributes,'' Crull said
in a statement. ``As soon as we became aware, however, that there
was a potential for confusion over the meaning of hypoallergenicity,
Carnation promptly and voluntarily removed the term from the Good
Start H.A. label'' and other references to the product.
   Hanaway said an investigation by the attorneys general found
Carnation claimed the formula could not cause an allergic reaction
in infants who had problems with other formulas or a milk allergy.
   Hanaway said the attorneys general became aware of medical
reports on a number of infants who suffered allergic reactions,
including shock, from using Good Start.
   The settlement prohibits Carnation from using the word
``hypoallergenic'' in promoting the product and claiming it cannot
cause allergic reactions.
</TEXT>
