<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed in Europe, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed mixed against the major
currencies in Europe on Thursday. Gold prices rose.
   Foreign exchange dealers said their markets traded in narrow
ranges, waiting for Friday's U.S. unemployment figures for June, an
important indicator of the state of the American economy.
   The dollar fell earlier in Tokyo, to 138.80 Japanese yen from
140.20 at Wednesday's close. But it traded higher against the yen in
London late Thursday at 139.10 yen.
   One British pound cost $1.6230 late Thursday in London, more
expensive for buyers than Wednesday's late $1.6155.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Wednesday's late rates: 1.8885 West German marks, down from; 1.6210
Swiss francs, up from 1.6195; 6.4070 French francs, down from
6.4125; 2.1310 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1496; 1.1919 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1909; and 1,370.50 Italian lire, down from
1,380.50.
   Gold bullion prices were higher but traders said a feeling that
the dollar is going up made the rise a modest one.
   Gold closed in London at a bid $386.25 a troy ounce, up from
$385.50. The closing price in Zurich was $385.00 an ounce, up from
$384.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $384.45 an ounce, up from
$379.05.
   Silver bullion fell in London to $5.36 a troy ounce from $5.38
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
