<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mixed Amid Weather Uncertainty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mixed
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid conflicting weather
forecasts for the Midwestern corn and soybean country.
   ``There's supposed to be a minor cooldown before it heats up
again in a couple days and there could be some sporadic showers, but
it depends which forecaster you talk to,'' said Ted Mao, a grain
specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   ``It's just a very nervous weather market,'' he said.
   The day of active but unfocused trading followed a powerful rally
in Wednesday's session. The market's failure to build upon
Wednesday's gains _ which were based on forecasts for hot, dry
weather in the Corn Belt next week _ also was blamed for its
uncertain performance on Thursday.
   The corn market is especially sensitive to weather forecasts
because the Midwestern corn crop has entered its pollination phase,
a sensitive period when hot, dry conditions pose a particular threat.
   At the close of trading, wheat was 3{ cents lower to 4 cents
higher with the contract for delivery in July at $4.08 a bushel;
corn was 2} cents lower to 6 cents higher with July at $2.81 a
bushel; oats were 2\ cents to 4{ cents lower with July at $1.63{ a
bushel; soybeans were 5 cents lower to 3{ cents higher with July at
$7.71{ a bushel.
