<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $2.83 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 469 money market mutual
funds rose $2.83 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The rise, to a record $323.63 billion in the seven-day period
ended Wednesday, followed a revised $462.3 million drop in the
funds' assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based
mutual fund trade group. The previous week's drop originally was
reported by the group as $445.8 million.
   The funds' assets hit the previous record high of $321.26 billion
in the week ended June 21, 1989.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 231 general purpose funds rose $1.99 billion to $105.03
billion, assets of 95 broker-dealer funds increased $582.3 million
to $136.60 billion, and assets of 143 institutional funds rose
$256.8 million to $81.99 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.85 percent from 8.89 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 8.91 percent from 8.96 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 38
days, down from 39 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts fell to
6.55 percent as of Wednesday from 6.56 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, was 5.14 percent, unchanged from the previous week.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.79
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 8.84 the
previous week. Yields were 8.83 percent on 1-year CDs, down from
8.89 percent; 8.66 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 8.73 percent;
and 8.63 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.67 percent.
</TEXT>
