<FIRST>u f AM-AutoSupply Bjt   07-06 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Supply, Bjt,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rewards Await Patient Car Buyers; But Are There Any Out There?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sagging consumer demand and swollen inventories
may have automakers looking at end-of-the-model-year fire sales or
further production cutbacks accompanied by layoffs, industry
analysts said Thursday.
   Domestic automakers, which assemble more than three-fourths of
the vehicles sold in the United States, reported Wednesday that car
and light truck sales for the first half of 1989 were down 4.8
percent from the same period last year.
   That bolstered what analysts have been saying for months:
automakers have been making too many vehicles while demand was
weaker than anticipated. Slower sales plus excessive production add
up to bloated inventories.
   Estimates vary, but industry watchers say automakers have new car
supplies as high as 80 days at the current selling rate. Because
supplies should be between 60 and 70 days, something has to spur
new-car sales or to slow inventory growth during the rest of the
year.
   ``The industry is going to be very hard pressed to turn the
spigot on for the third quarter,'' auto analyst John Kirnan of
Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. of New York said Thursday. ``You've got the
greatest levels of incentives out there and they don't seem to be
generating the interest.''
   The combination of buyer incentives in effect since April _
including cut-rate financing or cash rebates on everything from
subcompacts to luxury models _ and high inventories should have
lured consumers into showrooms. But that has not been happening.
   Furthermore, increased cash-back incentives or lower cut-rate
financing do not appear to be the breeze to fan a sales fire, said
Bill Meier, general manager of Ray Green Chevrolet in Jacksonville,
Ill.
   ``It's been slow and it's beginning to taper off,'' he said
Thursday. ``I was here in '79 and '80 and it was bad back then.
We'll come around.''
   In the short run, times may be getting tougher for the
automakers, their dealers and their factory workers. One way to fix
inventory problems is production cuts, and that means layoffs.
   ``I think there will be some, it's just a question of degree,''
said analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. of New York.
``I'm looking for some significant cutbacks.''
   A United Auto Workers spokesman who declined to be identified
said the union was watching sales and production figures closely to
ensure that any production cuts and layoffs are warranted under
contracts with automakers.
   During the past few months, automakers have been selectively
shutting down production at plants making a variety of cars. The
closings have been relatively brief, mostly lasting for a week or
two.
   In the next few months, plants will close for vacations and to be
retooled for the 1990 models, a process that usually takes two
weeks. This week and next, Ford Motor Co. has scheduled no
production at any of its assembly plants.
   On Thursday, Ward's Automotive Reports said domestic automakers'
production levels were sharply lower during the week this year than
a year ago. The trade journal said automakers scheduled the
production of 71,167 cars and trucks in the United States during the
week this year, 42.6 percent lower than the 124,029 vehicles they
produced during the same week last year.
</TEXT>
