<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-06 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise While Gasoline Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices slumped Thursday as labor
problems in the North Sea showed signs of easing.
   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, fell 46 cents to close at $20.33 a barrel
on the New York Mercantile Exchange. On Wednesday, the contract rose
52 cents.
   The August contract for home heating oil fell 1.17 cents a gallon
to close at 49.89 cents after rising the same amount on Wednesday.
Wholesale unleaded gasoline for August delivery dropped 1.15 cents
to settle at 56.27 cents a gallon after falling 0.35 cent Wednesday.
   Richard Redoglia, an analyst with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures,
said reports that British oil maintenance workers in the North Sea
would end a strike and return to work sent prices lower.
   The New York market had rallied in recent sessions on concerns
that the walkout would cut oil supplies. But prices began falling in
Europe when it appeared the strike was ending, giving U.S. traders
the cue to sell, Redoglia said.
</TEXT>
