<DOCNO> AP890706-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1821EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-06 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Slide Further After Brazil Evades Freeze</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Raw coffee futures prices slid to new 8-year lows Thursday on New
York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange as the battered market reacted
to news that an expected freeze in the Brazilian coffee fields had
not materialized.
   On other markets, sugar futures fell sharply for the second
straight day; energy futures fell; pork futures continued to
retreat; grains and soybeans were mixed; and precious metals were
mixed.
   Coffee settled 1.49 cents to 6.62 cents lower with the contract
for delivery in July at 93.38 cents a pound.
   The selloff erased all of Wednesday's gains and deepened the
market's anxiety stemming from the suspension of coffee export
quotas Monday by the International Coffee Organization.
   Some analysts believe the lifting of quotas _ the result of
long-running discord among the 74 coffee-producing and consuming
nations that make up the organization _ will result in a flood of
high-quality coffees that had been withheld from the market in a bid
to stabilize prices.
   Coffee futures had rallied Wednesday on expectations for a freeze
in Brazil, the world's largest coffee producer.
   But frost touched only a few areas, skirting the main producing
regions altogether, said Esther Eskenasy, an analyst with Cargill
Investor Services Inc. in New York.
   She said producer selling of coffee occurred at price levels
above 98 cents a pound but dried up at lower levels.
   Most of the offers to sell coffee futures below 98 cents a pound
came from European traders, who expect the availability of raw
coffee to balloon in the near future.
   ``I think the market will continue to be under pressure because
of all these supplies that they have not been able to sell'' due to
the quotas, Ms. Eskenasy said.
   Sugar futures lengthened their steep slide on the Coffee, Sugar &amp;
Cocoa Exchange. Analysts said the market was correcting from an
overbought condition after making strong gains in mid-June.
   Sugar settled .18 cent to the permitted limit of .50 cent lower
with October at 13.12 cents a pound.
   Energy futures sagged on the New York Mercantile Exchange on
reports that striking maintenance and construction workers planned
to return to work Friday on North Sea oil production platforms.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 26 cents to 54 cents lower
with August at $20.30 a barrel; heating oil was 1.01 cents to 1.32
cents lower with August at 49.89 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .15 cent to 1.15 cents lower with August at 56.27 cents a gallon.
   Hog and pork-belly futures sank for the third consecutive session
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in a continuing reaction to last
Friday's quarterly Agriculture Department report showing an
unexpectedly large number of hogs and pigs on U.S. farms.
   Cattle futures struggled to a mixed close.
   Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .25 cent higher with July at
70.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .27 cent to .40 cent higher
with August at 81.02 cents a pound; hogs were .22 cent to .65 cent
lower with July at 46.77 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .60
cent to the limit 2 cents lower with July at 30.47 cents a pound.
   Corn and soybean futures fell sharply late in the session on the
Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for slightly cooler
temperatures and spotty showers in the Midwest this weekend.
   Wheat settled 4{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with July at $4.05
a bushel; corn was { cent to 8 cents lower with July at $2.78} a
bushel; oats were 4} cents to 8 cents lower with July at $1.60 a
bushel; soybeans were 4} cents to 13 cents lower with July at $7.65
a bushel.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled 20 cents to 70
cents higher with August at $388.60 a troy ounce; silver was 1.6
cents to 1.7 cents lower with July at $5.377 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
