<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld - Writethru,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up; Gold Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, In Tokyo... to CORRECT New York yen figure
to 138.88. Picks up 9th graf, The dollar...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed narrowly higher Thursday
against all key currencies in thin, uneventful trading after a mixed
performance overseas.
   Gold prices were mostly higher. On the New York Commodity
Exchange, gold bullion for current delivery rose 40 cents to $386.40
a troy ounce. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid
for gold at $384.25, down 35 cents from late Wednesday.
   Currency dealers said the dollar started out higher as traders
looked for bargains following Wednesday's selloff, which stemmed
from continued fears that interest rates will fall because the U.S.
economy is slowing.
   Gary Lutnick, a trader in the New York office of Banco di
Sicilia, said the currency traded in a fairly narrow range
throughout the session in anticipation of Friday's unemployment data
for June, an important indicator of the state of the economy.
   ``People were trying to limit their exposure due to the
unemployment numbers,'' he said.
   Some dealers said they expected the employment figures to show
growth at the rate of about 200,000 in nonfarm payroll employment,
about double the 101,000 preliminary increase reported for May.
   Lutnick said traders also were awaiting the start of next week's
Group of Seven meeting in Washington to learn more about the
industrialized nations' views on currency exchange rates. The
so-called G-7 includes the United States and its six major trading
partners _ Japan, West Germany, Britain, France, Canada and Italy.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell to 138.80 Japanese yen from 140.20 yen Wednesday. It
traded higher in London at 139.10 yen, and in New York at 138.88
yen, up from 138.40 yen late Wednesday.
   The dollar was mixed against the British pound. One pound cost
$1.6230 in London, more expensive than Wednesday's $1.6155. Sterling
bought $1.6265 in New York, down from $1.6285.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday, included: 1.8850 West German marks, up from 1.8820;
1.6175 Swiss francs, up from 1.6115; 1.1916 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1908; 6.3935 French francs, up from 6.3875; and 1,365.50
Italian lire, up from 1,362.00.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,
included: 1.8885 West German marks, down from 1.8907; 1.6210 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6195; 6.4070 French francs, down from 6.4125;
2.1310 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1496; 1.1919 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1909; and 1,370.50 Italian lire, down from 1,380.50.
   Gold rose in London to $386.25 an ounce from $385.50, and in
Zurich, Switzerland, to $385 an ounce from $384.50. Earlier, in Hong
Kong, gold closed at $384.45 an ounce, up from $379.05 Wednesday.
   Silver prices declined. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $5.377 a troy ounce from $5.393 Wednesday.
Silver slipped in London to $5.36 an ounce from $5.38.
</TEXT>
