<FIRST>r f AM-Telephone-Capitol     07-06 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Telephone-Capitol,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>MCI Wins Congressional Phone Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCI Telecommunications Inc. has won a contract
potentially worth up to $20 million over two years to provide
long-distance telephone service to the legislative branch, officials
said Thursday.
   Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., chairman of the Senate Rules Committee,
and Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., chairman of the House
Administration Committee, selected MCI based on recommendations from
a team that included staff from the architect of the Capitol's
office.
   MCI was chosen over U.S. Sprint and the American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co. in a competitive bidding process, said Dan Hanlon, a
spokesman for the architect. The final contract should be awarded
within three months, he said.
   The selection boosts the fortunes of MCI, a Washington-based
company which was part of a team that lost its bid to provide
long-distance service to the rest of the government.
   The General Services Administraton awarded that business _
potentially worth $25 billion over ten years _ to AT&amp;T and U.S.
Sprint in December 1988.
   Pam Small, a MCI spokesman, said Thursday's decision was a ``very
important contract for MCI'' that underscores the company's ability
to do business with the government.
   MCI will replace a system in which several companies have
provided long-distance service to the legislative branch, comprised
of the Senate, the House, the Library of Congress, the General
Accounting Office, the Government Printing Office and Congressional
Budget Office and the Office of Technology Assessment.
   Hanlon said the contract will cost between $5 million and $10
million annually, a savings of nearly half for the legislative
branch. Long-distance service now costs between $20 million and $30
million a year, he said.
   The initial contract will be for two years, which options for
renewal.
</TEXT>
