<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     07-06 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Share Prices Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened higher Friday against the
Japanese yen, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
moderately in early trading.
   The dollar opened at 139.33 yen, up 0.43 yen from Thursday's
close of 138.90 yen, which also was the level at which it closed in
New York overnight.
   Dealers said trading in Tokyo started in a cautious mood as
investors avoided major moves ahead of the release of U.S.
unemployment figures for June later Friday.
   The dollar in New York inched up overnight on expectations that
the jobless rate might be better than expected.
   The dollar-yen rate was moving little in Tokyo Friday morning,
said a Bank of Tokyo trader, who spoke anonymously.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average quickly
earned 113.76 points, or 0.34 percent, rising to 33,537.24 points
within the first 15 minutes of morning trading. The index had gained
113.77 points Thursday.
   The upward move followed a slight gain in the Dow Jones
industrial average of 30 major issues in New York overnight.
</TEXT>
